<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines     08-04 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leftists Say Three Members Organizing US Base Protests Disappeared</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leftist group said today that three
members who were organizing protests against U.S. military bases
disappeared in what it charged was a military plot to stifle
dissent.
   Zenaida Uy, secretary-general of the New Patriotic Alliance,
said Jose-Marie Enriquez left his home in Quezon City on Wednesday
to visit a shopping mall but never returned.
   Ms. Uy said Alejandrino Sarile left a meeting in suburban Makati
to change clothes but never reached his home.
   The third, Benedicto Clotario, was dropped off in Makati last
Sunday after attending a meeting in Cavite province and has not
been seen since, she said.
   She said checks of hospitals, morgues and police stations failed
to turn up any trace of the three.
   ``We believe that these incidents are part of a systematic
national campaign of terror being waged by the military or
paramilitary groups as part of a national policy of repression and
violence against organized groups,'' the alliance said in a
statement.
   It said the abductions were an attempt to prevent rallies
protesting the government of President Corazon Aquino.
   ``Because public opinion is snowballing against the Aquino
government's subservient and mendicant conduct in the bases review
talks, the present regime wants to paralyze resisting organizations
in their campaign machinery so that they can easily force the
decision to extend the bases stay on the Philippines and subvert
the will of the people,'' the statement said.
   Last September, the alliance's national chairman, Lean
Alejandro, was slain and his killers remain unknown. Leftists have
accused right-wing groups of mounting a liquidation campaign
against members of legal left-wing organizations.
   In July, the American Bar Association expressed concern in a
letter to Mrs. Aquino over recent killings of human rights lawyers
who also were alliance members.
   Meanwhile, the United States and the Philippines today continued
talks on the status of the six bases. They broke down July 26
because of differences over compensation but resumed on Tuesday.
   On Wednesday, Foreign Secretary Raul Manglapus said the
Philippines would welcome the inclusion of debt relief as part of
the compensation package the United States has to pay for the use
of its bases here.
   The United States gives the Philippines $180 million in military
and economic aid each year in exchange for the use of Clark Air
Base, the Subic Bay naval base and four smaller facilities here.
   The talks are part of negotiations that began four months ago to
review a 1947 agreement giving the Americans the right to operate
military bases in the Philippines.
</TEXT>
