<1ST_LINE>u i PM-PLO-Jordan 1stLd-Writethru a0486 08-04 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PLO-Jordan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0486,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Leaders Welcome Jordanian Action</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS graf after 6th, `Hussein announced,' to UPDATE with
king's latest move. SUBS 7th pvs, `The official...' to conform.
Pick up 8th pvs, `Jordan is...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A PLO official says the organization is
still trying to sort out the significance of King Hussein's
decision to sever legal ties with the West Bank but is treating the
move as a positive step.
   But the official expressed skepticism about the Jordanian
monarch's intention, saying the king might be trying to pressure
Palestinians in the Israeli-occupied territory into reliance on
Jordan.
   ``We are dealing with it on the basis it is a positive step on
the part of Jordan,'' the senior PLO official, who insisted he not
be identified further, said Wednesday.
   ``Also we are dealing with it on the basis of removing from our
minds the Jordanian intentions behind this step _ whether it is
pressure or not,'' he added, echoing doubts expressed by other PLO
officials meeting in Baghdad.
   The official indicated Jordan's action might prompt new PLO
diplomatic activity. He said it has ``accelerated Palestinian
thinking regarding realistic political initiatives,'' but declined
to specify what steps might be taken.
   Hussein announced Sunday he was severing administrative and
legal ties with the West Bank, which his family ruled from 1948
until Israel seized it in 1967. He said he is stepping aside in
favor of the PLO and called for an independent Palestinian state.
   In keeping with that decision, the Jordanian government today
announced it was laying off or retiring as of Aug. 16 more than
21,000 Jordanian employees of Palestinian origin working in the
West Bank.
   The PLO official attributed Hussein's decision to cut ties to
the 8-month-old uprising, during which ``Jordanian institutions in
the occupied territories were rendered valueless.''
   Jordan is the primary financial avenue for the 800,000 West Bank
Palestinians. Most hold Jordanian passports and many receive
Jordanian salaries.
   A PLO communique issued here after several days of talks by the
PLO Central Council said the 66 members on hand discussed Jordan's
action ``which was taken without any consulation with the
organization.''
   It urged the cabinet-like Executive Committee ``to study all the
aspects and the expected results of the Jordanian measures and to
take all necessary measures.''
   It neither praised nor criticized Jordan's action.
   The senior PLO official said Hussein's action ``canceled the
Jordanian option'' advocated by some American and Israeli officials
who favor returning the West Bank to Jordan in exchange for peace
rather than allowing a Palestinian state.
   ``It put the Americans and the Israelis face-to-face with the
Palestinians,'' the PLO official said.
   He also said it should lead to a renewed PLO agreement with
Jordan ``because we are still committed to the idea of a
confederation'' between a Jordanian and Palestinian state.
   The Central Council called for an extraordinary session of the
Palestine National Council to discuss the Jordanian action as well
as the Palestinian uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
   The national council is the PLO's parliament.
   A PLO delegation will visit Jordan soon to discuss the issue and
prepare for a visit by PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat, whose relations
with Jordan have been strained since Hussein broke off talks with
him in mid-1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
