<HEAD>U.S. Envoy Meets Leaders On Presidential Election</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES thruout with Murphy meeting with Husseini, quotes. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Richard
Murphy today held talks with government leaders on arranging the
smooth election of a new president of the war-torn country.
   Accompanied by U.S. Ambassador John Kelly, Murphy met for an
hour with acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss in Hoss' heavily
fortified house in Moslem west Beirut. He then met with Parliament
Speaker Hussein Husseini.
   It was not known whether the officials discussed the 18 Western
hostages held in Lebanon. The Lebanese government has not been able
to do anything about the hostages because civil war has eroded its
power.
   Murphy refused to speak to reporters after the Hoss meeting.
Hoss, a Sunni Moslem, also refused comment.
   After his two-hour meeting with Husseini, a Shiite Moslem,
Murphy told reporters: ``My visit is not to demonstrate that we are
the major force in the elections. It is to underline our interest
that the elections take place for the new president of Lebanon.''
   Murphy, in charge of Middle East affairs at the State
Department, added, ``We hope that those elections will take place
in the very near future, that they will take place in a peaceful
atmosphere, in an orderly atmosphere so that the candidate would be
a legitimate transition from one hand to another.''
   Murphy also planned talks with Christian President Amin Gemayel
at his palace in suburban Baabda.
   The United States and Syria, Lebanon's main power broker, have
been trying to get Lebanon's warring Moslems and Christians to
negotiate political reforms that could end 13 years of civil strife.
   Gemayel's six-year-term expires Sept. 23. Parliament must elect
a successor at least one week before Gemayel bows out.
   Nine Americans are among the hostages believed held by
pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem extremists. The longest held of the 18 is
Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press. He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
