<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Violence,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hindu Leader Shot to Death in Hospital Room</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHANDIGARH, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh terrorists burst into a hospital
room in a northern Indian town today and killed a Hindu leader who
was recovering from injuries sustained in a car accident, a police
official said.
   The official, who cannot be identified under briefing rules,
said two Sikhs entered the Dayanand Medical College and Hospital at
Ludhiana town and gunned down Tej Pal Sathi, the president of the
Shiv Sena, a fundamentalist Hindu party.
   Two of Sathi's police bodyguards were also shot and killed, the
official said. A news agency report said the militants fired at
least 30 rounds from automatic rifles during the attack.
   Sathi was involved in the car accident Monday while returning
from the funeral of another Hindu leader shot to death by Sikh
militants.
   Ludhiana, in Punjab state, is 55 miles west of Chandigarh, the
state capital.
   Also today, the United News of India news agency said three
Sikhs were shot and killed by militant Sikhs in Punjab's Ferozepur
district on Wednesday night.
   Sikh militants have been fighting since 1982 for an independent
homeland in Punjab state. At least 1,638 people have been killed in
Sikh violence in Punjab this year. Most of their victims are Hindus
or moderate Sikhs.
   Sikhs are a minority in India and claim they are discriminated
against by the majority Hindus. Sikhs are the majority in Punjab.
</TEXT>
