<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a0532 08-04 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0532,0652</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Says Iraqi Chemical Attack Injured 1,700</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT graf after 1st to ADD Iranian claims. Pick up 2nd pvs,
`In the...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said today that 1,700 people were
injured in an Iraqi chemical bomb attack on a northern town, and
Iran's foreign minister formally protested to the U.N. Security
Council.
   Iran also said Iraqi military aircraft bombed two industrial
targets in western Lorestan province and injured a number of
workers. It did not give details.
   In the Persian Gulf today, Iranian gunboats fired at a Norwegian
tanker after it refused to stop for an inspection, gulf-based
shipping executives said. The captain said a few bullets pierced
the ship but caused no injuries.
   Earlier reports from Iran's official Islamic Republic News
Agency said 1,031 civilians were injured in an Iraqi chemical bomb
attack Tuesday in the town of Oshnaviyeh in the northern province
of West Azerbaijan.
   Today, IRNA raised the injury toll to 1,700.
   ``Over 100 of the victims, mainly women and children, have
reportedly been seriously affected and are being treated in various
hospitals in the province,'' IRNA said.
   Iraq denied it dropped chemical bombs on the area, according to
the official Iraqi News Agency.
   On Wednesday, Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati lodged
a formal protest with the Security Council over the alleged
chemical attack, and said it should impose sanctions on Iraq.
   A report released Monday by a U.N. team concluded that Iraq has
made repeated and extensive use of chemical warfare in the war,
violating international law. Iraq claims Iran used chemical weapons
first.
   It also found that nine Iraqi soldiers were poisoned recently by
chemical weapons, but left open the question of whether Iran was to
blame.
   Velayati was in New York to represent Iran at U.N.-sponsored
talks aimed at ending the 8-year-old war. Iran said July 18 it
would accept a year-old Security Council cease-fire resolution.
   Iraq, which said it would accept the resolution soon after it
passed, insists on direct talks with Iran before a cease-fire. Iran
wants a cease-fire before direct talks.
   Lt. Gen. Martin Vadset of Norway, head of a U.N. cease-fire
team, was expected to arrive today in New York from Amman, Jordan,
to deliver a report to U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar.
   Vadset spent about 10 days in Tehran and Baghdad.
   Shipping executives, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Iranian gunboats fired at the 284,502-ton Berge Lord tanker today
about 25 miles off the southern gulf port of Dubai.
   ``Apart from some bullet holes near the bridge, we've got no
damage at all,'' the captain, Leif Klausen, told the Norwegian NTB
news agency.
   ``Six fast gunboats approached us and asked us to stop for
inspection. When I refused because the boats had no markings, one
boat opened machine-gun fire,'' he was quoted as saying in a
telephone interview.
   The tanker was headed to Rotterdam from Saudi Arabia with a load
of crude.
   The Berge Lord, attacked previously this year, did not stop and
proceeded with its voyage southward, the sources said.
   U.S. Navy sources said the missile cruiser USS Halsey responded
to the tanker's distress calls, but when it checked if assistance
was required, the captain of the Berge Lord declined and kept
sailing.
   It was the first hostile incident involving a neutral ship in
the gulf since Iran announced it would accept a cease-fire. Iranian
gunboats last attacked a tanker on July 15.
   Sources said Iran was exercising the right, under international
maritime law, for nations at war to stop and inspect ships anywhere
at sea to check for cargo bound for their enemy.
   Iran says it has stopped thousands of ships for inspections, and
shipping executives say the Iranians occasionally fire warning
shots.
</TEXT>
