<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ShopliftLawsuit     08-04 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shoplift Lawsuit,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Couple Awarded $2.5 Million In Damages Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple who were arrested and falsely accused by a
department store of shoplifting a $200 computer printer they were
trying to exchange has been awarded $2.25 million by a jury.
   ``I hope this will teach them a lesson and it won't happen
again,'' said Kenneth Geringer, 32. ``It could happen to anybody.
One minute you're walking through a store, and the next minute they
call you a criminal.''
   The verdict Tuesday went against Zayre Corp. and two security
employees even though the couple testified they bought the
defective printer from a rival store then attempted to exchange it
at the Zayre store in Hallandale in 1985.
   After two hours of deliberations, the state jury found that
Zayre and the employees caused the couple ``emotional distress''
and ``maliciously and without probable cause'' brought grand theft
charges against them.
   The charges, which carry up to five years in prison, were
dropped several months after the arrest.
   The jury awarded $700,000 in actual damages and $1 million in
punitive damages to Allisa Geringer, 31, and $50,000 in actual
damages and $500,000 in punitive damages to her husband.
   Charles Sinclair, an attorney for the Massachusetts-based Zayre
Corp., said he wil ask the court to reduce the award.
</TEXT>
