<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hungary-Objectors     08-04 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hungary-Objectors,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>590 Refused to Bear Arms since 1977, At Least 40 Jailed a Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Communist Party official said
590 conscientious objectors have refused to do compulsory 18-month
military service in Hungary since 1977, a newspaper said today.
   It was believed to be the first such public admission regarding
conscientious objectors by a Hungarian official.
   Ferenc Szombathelyi, deputy head of department in the party's
Central Committee, told the party daily Nepszabadsag that 40 to 45
young people were jailed annually.
   ``This practice must be changed now,'' he said.
   He said that ``compulsory work in health and social
institutions, communal establishments and major investment
projects'' might be suitable alternatives to military service.
   The issue of conscientious objectors has been under debate in
Hungary, with church officials and dissidents demanding that
authorities change draft provisions.
   In June, at least 700 people signed a petition for introduction
of an alternative to military service that was presented to
Parliament.
   People who refuse to do mandatory military service in Hungary
for reasons of conscience or religion can be imprisoned for up to
five years.
   However, Jehova's Witnesses, members of the Church of the
Nazarene and Seventh-Day Adventists are exempted from military
service.
   ``A conscript serves 18 months in the armed forces (and) it is
conceivable that those doing civilian work instead would serve a
longer term,'' Szombathelyi said.
   ``The cases would be examined individually and meticulously
...(and) on no account should exemption be granted to `clever guys'
or irresponsible persons,'' the official said, without elaboration.
   In June, Poland became the first East bloc country to establish
an alternative civilian service.
</TEXT>
