<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BodyRecovered     08-04 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Body Recovered,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Body Of Aged Nursing Home Patient Found In National Park</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOT SPRINGS, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 87-year-old man found dead in a park
may have tried to re-live his escape from a World War II prison
camp by fleeing a nursing home during a fire drill, his doctor says.
   Josef Fruewirth was found Wednesday a half-mile from Hot Springs
Nursing Home, which he left on June 30, said his physician, William
R. Mashburn, who is also the Garland County coroner.
   During World War II, Fruewirth tunneled out of a Soviet prison
camp and walked 625 miles to his native Austria, where he was
reunited with his family, Mashburn said.
   Fruewirth died of exposure complicated by lack of medication for
heart disease and probably did not survive 24 hours after leaving
the home, Mashburn said. The three-pack-per-day smoker also had
emphysema and signs of early Alzheimer's disease, the coroner said.
   ``The bell ringing and confusion may have caused a flashback to
a time in his life when he was a prisoner. He was very unhappy in
the nursing home. He felt, to a degree, incarcerated,'' Mashburn
said. ``This drill was evidently what he had been waiting for. I
truly believe the clanging and people being pushed out _ well, he
escaped once, and I think he tried to do so again.''
   ``He had amazing stamina,'' said Becky Ponder, a registered
nurse at the home. ``Anyone who would walk over 600 miles to get
back to his family is capable of anything.''
   His body was found in the rugged, mountainous terrain of Hot
Springs National Park, which begins near the nursing home.
   ``We found him within a few feet of a beautiful little spring.
You wouldn't find a more peaceful place to go to God,'' Mashburn
said.
</TEXT>
