<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Rowan-NAACP     08-04 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rowan-NAACP,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hooks Calls for Dropping of Charges against Rowan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the NAACP is calling on District
of Columbia Mayor Marion Barry to overrule the city's legal counsel
and drop weapons charges against newspaper columnist Carl Rowan.
   But a spokesman for the mayor says Barry doesn't have the
authority or the inclination to ask that the charges be dropped.
   ``Carl Rowan is not, and never has been, a lawbreaker,''
Benjamin Hooks, executive director of the civil rights group, said
in a statement Wednesday. ``To the contrary, he has spent 40 years
as a distinguished journalist, trying to force presidents,
governors, Congress and others to obey the Constitution, to enforce
decent laws, so that black people might be free.''
   Last week the city's corporation counsel, Frederick Cooke, filed
charges of possession of an unregistered weapon and ammunition
against Rowan in connection with the shooting of a teen-ager in the
columnist's back yard.
   John White, a spokesman for Barry, said the mayor had not yet
seen the letter but didn't plan to ask Cooke to drop the charges.
   ``The mayor does not have the authority,'' said White. ``It is
the feeling of this office that perhaps Mr. Hooks has not read the
D.C. law. Under the city charter, the corporation counsel is the
chief legal officer of the city.''
   Hooks told The Washington Post that every executive must
occasionally correct staff members' mistakes.
   ``People in my office quite often do things that I overrule
because it's not in the best interest of my organization in the
long run to do that,'' he said. ``And that's what I'm asking Marion
Barry: to overrule a mistake made by his corporation counsel.''
   But White said, ``It's the mayor's policy not to interfere with
the corporation counsel's decisions. He feels that, where would it
stop if he started telling the corporation counsel when or when not
to press charges.''
   Benjamin Smith, 18, of Chevy Chase, Md., had scaled Rowan's
eight-foot fence with at least one friend on June 14 to take a
late-night dip in the columnist's pool. Rowan told police he shot
the youth in the hand with a .22-caliber revolver because he
thought the teen was lunging toward him.
   Investigators discovered that the gun, which had been given to
Rowan by his son, a former FBI agent, was not properly registered
with the city.
</TEXT>
