<HEAD>Dallas Ballet Will Become Road Show Only For This Season</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For at least the next year, the Dallas Ballet will
be a road show only, having failed to raise the $1.3 million needed
to begin its home season in October.
   ``We didn't have enough funds pledged to start paying the
dancers and launch the season,'' said executive director Jack Page.
``And rather than start out and run out of gas before we got to the
end of the line, we elected not even to start.''
   However, the company has arranged a Sept. 2-12 tour of Denmark,
Page said Wednesday. Negotiations with Spain also are under way for
a tour there.
   The 28-dancer company was scheduled to begin a three-month
season Oct. 13 with a production of ``Swan Lake.''
   The cancellation came despite an offer by dancers to accept only
half the back pay owed them and to reduce the number of contract
weeks for the season.
   The company has been plagued by money problems since early 1987,
when dancers with tin cans stood on street corners, trying to raise
money.
