<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NoAC     08-04 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-No AC,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Residents Find Ways to Stay Cool Despite Air Conditioner Ban</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tenants of an apartment complex that bans air
conditioners are among the city's most creative when it comes to
finding ways to beat this summer's record heat.
   The Stuyvesant Town apartment complex in Manhattan is home to
18,000 middle-income tenants, many of whom could pay the price for
cooling units.
   But air conditioning is not allowed and hasn't been since the
complex was built 40 years ago for returning World War II
servicemen.
   Metropolitan Life Insurance Co., which owns the complex, says
the aging wiring couldn't safely support thousands of air
conditioners.
   Rewiring the apartments would cost at least $50 million, said
Fred Wortman, a Metropolitan Life vice president. Officials hope to
have a plan ready by year's end, he said, but rewiring would take
years to complete.
   Meanwhile, tenants do what they can. Some don't cook. Some spend
as much time as they can at friends' air-conditioned apartments or
in grocery stores.
   Others have four or eight fans going at the same time _ setting
them up at strategic angles to get the best breeze possible.
   ``There is an art to this,'' said Ed Petty, a four-fan resident.
   Some tenants have broken the rules and shelled out $850 for the
Delonghi Pinguino, an Italian-made, windowless free-standing air
conditioner.
   After this record-breaking summer, others have a more permanent
solution on their minds _ moving.
</TEXT>
