<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Jordan-WestBank 2ndLd-Writethru a0545 08-04 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jordan-West Bank, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0545,0601</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jordan Dismissing 21,200 Employees In Occupied Lands</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with details of dismissal program, reax
from Shamir and a Palestinian employee. ADDS background and byline.
No pickup.
^By JAMAL HALABY</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jordan today said it was dismissing within
two weeks all 21,200 Palestinian civil servants working at
Jordanian institutions in the Israeli-occupied territories.
   In Israel, a spokesman for Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said
the move will only hurt Palestinians living in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip.
   The decision, announced by state-run Radio Jordan, followed King
Hussein's announcement Sunday that he was severing administrative
ties with the West Bank to give more responsibility to the
Palestine Liberation Organization.
   The announcement was carried by the radio following a Cabinet
meeting headed by Prime Minister Zaid Rifai.
   ``The decision is in accordance with the kingdom's decision to
cut legal and administrative links with Palestinians in the
occupied lands,'' the radio said.
   ``All Jordanian citizens working for official and government
agencies will be retired as of Aug. 16,'' the radio said.
   The radio said civil servants who have worked less than 15 years
will be dismissed with a month's salary for every year of service.
A Jordanian official said 16,000 of the civil servants fall into
this category.
   The official said responsibility for those 16,000 will lie with
the PLO.
   Those who have worked more than 15 years also will be dismissed,
but they will continue to receive their monthly salaries from
Jordan until they retire on a pension after 20 years have elapsed
since they began working, the report said. The official said 5,200
civil servants fall into this category.
   Israel captured the West Bank from Jordan and the Gaza Strip
from Egypt during the 1967 Middle East War. Since December,
Palestinians in the occupied lands have been waging an uprising
against Israeli occupation in which more than 235 Palestinians and
four Israelis have been killed. The uprising has been directed by
underground leaders linked to the PLO, which also provides funding.
   Even after Jordan lost control of the West Bank, it continued to
pay its employees there and run the schools as well as other
administrative offices. About 850,000 Palestinians live in the West
Bank.
   One Palestinian affected by the decision, 55-year-old Jamila
Azmi of Bethlehem, who has worked 30 years as a school principal,
said:
   ``I don't think it is fair. Who is going to take care of the
fired employees? The only alternative is to work in Israel. I wish
they had thought before they made the decision.''
   In Israel, a spokesman quoted Shamir as saying that Jordan's
dismissal of the Palestinian employees will only hurt Palestinians
in the occupied lands because they ``will have to live with less
money.''
   The decision also terminates the services of an unspecified
number of workers at private institutions and companies linked to
the government, who will receive severance pay according to their
employers' rules, the radio said.
   Those working for courts and the authority that controls mosques
and other religious institution are exempt from the measures, the
announcement said.
   On Saturday, the king dissolved the lower house of the Jordanian
Parliament, where 30 of the 60 members came from the West Bank.
   Late last month, he also canceled a $1.3 billion development
program for education and economic projects in the West Bank.
   About 110,000 Palestinians are employed in Israel but about
one-quarter of them have frequently missed work during the uprising.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880804-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 1044EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WritersStrike-Lawyer     08-04 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike-Lawyer,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ziffren Praised By Both Sides</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note language in 6th graf.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Writers Strike, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An entertainment lawyer whose clients include
writers and producers was credited with a key role in reaching a
settlement in the strike that crippled Hollywood for 22 weeks.
   Kenneth Ziffren, 48, was hailed as ``the Philip Habib of
Hollywood'' by one writer-producer after negotiators announced a
settlement in the strike Wednesday. He served as a non-official
go-between during the talks.
   ``He could communicate through this haze of anger, vitriolic
hatred and distrust,'' said Gary David Goldberg, who compared
Ziffren to the U.S. diplomat Habib.
   Ziffren, described as an intensely private man, did not return
phone calls seeking comment on his role in helping reach a
compromise.
   Colleagues and clients said Ziffren was effective because of his
diplomatic style and rapport with writers and producers as well as
his ability to get to the heart of the strike's issues.
   ``His mind is so precise,'' said Norman Steinberg, a
screenwriter and Ziffren client. ``He just clicks onto the salient
facts and all the crap is swept away.''
   Colleagues also said Ziffren has a remarkable ability with
numbers, something that would help him in calculating complex
residual formulas, which determines payments from reruns and
syndication.
   ``He carries all the numbers in his head,'' Goldberg said.
   Ziffren's firm, Ziffren, Brittenham & Branca, represents a
variety of Hollywood talent, including TV writers and
writer-producers like Goldberg (``Family Ties''), Stephen Cannell
(``Hunter,'' ``Wiseguy'') and Glen Larson (``Quincy,'' ``Magnum
P.I.).
   The firm also represents financiers like oilman Marvin Davis and
broadcaster Ted Turner, and studio executives such as ABC's Brandon
Stoddard and Harris Katleman, president of 20th Century Fox
Television Productions.
   His actor clients include Harrison Ford, Tom Selleck, Richard
Pryor and John Ritter.
   Ziffren, described by friends as a workaholic, didn't let his
work keep him from attending to at least some details of his
personal life. He was married during the strike.
</TEXT>
