<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HoagieHassle     08-04 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hoagie Hassle,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Troopers Not Amused By Teen Clerk's Practical Joke</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-year-old convenience store clerk has
been charged with putting too much salt on a state trooper's
sandwich.
   The clerk, who was charged with disorderly conduct, punishable
by up to a $300 fine, said that he did nothing wrong and that if
anyone sabotaged the sandwich, it was done when he wasn't looking.
His boss is backing him up.
   Trooper Barry Gaston said Wednesday a fellow officer ordered the
sandwich by telephone from the store in suburban Philadelphia on
July 26. The officer, whom police declined to identify, told the
clerk he was a trooper.
   When another trooper arrived to pick up the sandwich, Gaston
said, ``He noticed people snickering and laughing.''
   Gaston said the officer who ordered the sandwich found it
heavily salted. The officer has high blood pressure, which can be
aggravated by salt.
   ``I'm not sure how practical and how much of a joke it is,'' Lt.
Daniel Worst said. ``It's not amusing. It makes you wonder. If
they're going to do this to the police, what are they going to do
to other people?''
   David Uriarte, who this fall will be a junior in high school,
said that he used the usual amount of salt and pepper and that if
more was on the ham and cheese sandwich either he made an honest
mistake or someone else sabotaged it.
   ``I wrapped it up, and while I was making it I had to leave a
few times to wait on other customers,'' Uriarte said Wednesday. He
said someone could have overheard him refer to the call-in customer
as a state trooper.
   Louis Marks, the store owner, said police came to the store the
day after the incident and urged him to fire Uriarte. ``They're
making a great deal out of this thing. I just can't believe it,''
Marks said.
   Cpl. Joe Fuentes said the charge carries a message. ``Basically,
we don't want the other kids out there to get the idea, `Hey, let's
fool around with the state troopers' food,''' he said.
</TEXT>
