<HEAD>Experiment Begins Using National Guard In Battle Against Drug
Smugglers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 5th graf pvs, `Florida's National ...'
with background on Florida program.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIDALGO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Guardsmen have moved to the front
line in the war on illegal drugs at the southern frontier as part
of an experiment using soldiers in an intensified search for drug
smugglers.
   The soldiers, who began searching cargo trucks from Mexico on
Wednesday, are among more than 100 National Guard personnel working
with U.S. Customs at border points in Texas, Arizona and Florida,
Customs Service officials said.
   ``I was told it was to test the effectiveness of the National
Guard in working with Customs,'' said Billy McFarland, chief
Customs inspector at Hidalgo on the Mexican border in the lower Rio
Grande Valley.
   The guardsmen underwent training on Monday and Tuesday, said
Charles Conroy, a Customs spokesman in Houston. The experiment ends
Aug. 20.
   ``Today, for all practical purposes, was the first day on the
job,'' Conroy said Wednesday.
   The National Guard last week announced a similar operation
concentrated in southeastern Florida. Authorities estimate up to 70
percent of the drugs entering the United States come through
Florida's 1,350 miles of coastline.
   Gilbert Medina, Customs supervisor of cargo enforcement at
Hidalgo, said the presence of the guardsmen means more trucks
coming from Mexico will be searched.
   ``They're looking for narcotics,'' he said. ``We're
intensifying, more vehicles, more trailers, just intensifying the
examinations.''
   Nearby, an unarmed National Guardsman dressed in camouflage gear
and army boots looked through an 18-wheeler loaded with jalapeno
peppers, while trucks loaded with television sets and mangos
awaited inspection.
   Guardsmen on duty declined to discuss their mission.
</TEXT>
