<HEAD>Shamir Says Dismissal Of Palestinians Won't Hurt Israel</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Jordan to dismiss 21,200 civil
servants in West Bank, reax from Shamir, Palestinian employee and
pro-PLO editor. TRIMS outdated material to tighten. No pickup.
^By KARIN LAUB</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir believes Jordan's
move to dismiss 21,200 Palestinia employees in the occupied
territories will hurt Palestinians and not Israel, a spokesman said
today.
   Jordan said today the civil servants will be dismissed by Aug.
16.
   The move came four days after Jordan said it was abandoning
legal and administrative links with Palestinians in the occupied
lands and handing over responsibility to the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   The decision dismissing the employees was criticized today by
one West Bank worker who will lost his job. But it drew praise from
a pro-PLO newspaper editor who said the PLO will fill ``the
political vacuum left by Jordan.''
   Jordan's decision ``will certainly increase the pressure on
Arabs in Judea and Samaria,'' Shamir's spokesman, Yossi Ahimeir,
said, using biblical names for the West Bank. ``They will have to
live with less money.''
   Ahimeir said it was difficult to predict how the dismissals
would affect the 8-month-old uprising in which Palestinians have
been protesting Israel's occupation of the West Bank and Gaza
Strip. More than 235 Palestinians and four Israelis have been
killed since the uprising began Dec. 8.
   One Palestinian worker who will be dismissed, 55-year-old Jamila
Azmi of Bethlehem, said: ``I don't think it is fair. Who is going
to take care of the fired employees? The only alternative is to
work in Israel.''
   Azmi, who has worked as a school principal for 30 years, added:
``I wish they (Jordanian officials) had thought before they made
the decision.''
   Before Jordan's announcement today, underground leaders of the
Palestinian uprising praised the kingdom for severing ties with the
West Bank and called the move a major achievement of the revolt
against Israeli occupation.
   The statement, in leaflets distributed in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, was the first reaction by the pro-PLO leadership to Sunday's
announcement by King Hussein that he was cutting ties with the West
Bank.
   In Jerusalem, meanwhile, U.S. diplomats said on Wednesday they
were investigating the death of Ribhi Barakat Kayed, 67, a
Palestinian-American who relatives said died after Israeli soldiers
prevented him from getting medication for a heart condition. The
army denied the allegations.
   Violent clashes erupted in two Gaza Strip refugee camps
Wednesday night, and dozens of Arabs were injured by troops,
including a 15-year-old struck in the eye by a rubber bullet.
   In a leaflet distributed in the occupied lands, the PLO-backed
United National Leadership of the Uprising praised Hussein's
decisions.
   Leaflets are the main means of communications between leaders of
the uprising and Arab protesters in the occupied lands.
   The announcement ``enforced the status of the PLO as the sole
representative of the Palestinian people,'' the leaflet said. The
underground leaders took credit for the monarch's move, calling it
``one of the most important achievements of the uprising.''
</TEXT>
