<1ST_LINE>r i PM-HamadiTrial     08-04 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hamadi Trial,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness Says Hamadi Wanted To Exchange Freedom for Hostages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A witness in the trial of
Mohammed Ali Hamadi, charged in the 1985 hijacking of a TWA
jetliner, said today that Hamadi sought to trade freedom from
prison for two West German hostages in Lebanon.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, is charged with air piracy and
murder in the hijacking. Thirty-nine Americans were held captive
for 17 days U.S. Navy diver Robert Stetham was killed in the ordeal.
   Today's main witness was Gabriel Lapite, who was imprisoned on
drug charges in a cell near Hamadi's from January to March of last
year.
   Lapite testified that Hamadi gave him the telephone number of a
sister in Beirut with the request: ``Tell her that my brother
should start to go to work. Both Germans should not be freed unless
I am released.''
   Lapite did not say which of Hamadi's brothers was to be
contacted. He did not say if he placed the phone call, and Chief
Judge Heiner Mueckenberger did not ask him.
   However, Lapite did testify that Mohammed Hamadi gave him five
letters to mail to family members and friends. Lapite said he did
not mail the letters and handed them over to police.
   Reiner Hamm, a lawyer representing hijack victims and their
families in the trial, said the letters attempted to arrange
Hamadi's release from prison.
   One of Hamadi's brothers, Abdul Hadi Hamadi, is Beirut security
chief for Hezbollah, a radical Shiite Moslem organization suspected
of holding Western hostages in Lebanon.
   Another brother, Abbas Hamadi, was arrested in January 1987 at
Frankfurt airport and convicted in April of kidnapping the two West
Germans. He was sentenced to 13 years in prison.
   Prosecutors say the kidnappings in January 1987 were aimed at
forcing West Germany to free Mohammed Ali Hamadi. They occurred
just a few days after Mohammed Ali Hamadi was arrested at
Frankfurt's airport after being caught with explosives.
   One West German, Alfred Schmidt, was released in September, but
the second, Rudolf Cordes, remains a hostage.
   Cordes is one of 18 Westerners, including nine Americans, held
hostage in Lebanon. The hostage held longest is Terry Anderson,
chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press.
   There was no court session Wednesday.
   The defendant told the court on Tuesday that he had been sick
and wants treatment, but he did not want to discuss his ailment
publicly.
   Court spokesman Falk Thomas said Hamadi has requested hospital
treatment when the court recesses for four weeks on Aug. 9. Thomas
would not specify the nature of the illness.
   Also on Tuesday, Judge Mueckenberger read from a report police
prepared after questioning witness Hamza Kassim about a
conversation with Hamadi's older brother, Abbas.
   The report quoted Kassim as telling police that he had been told
by Abbas that Mohammed was arrested ``because he was a hijacker of
the American plane.''
   Questioned by the judge about his statement, Kassim said he
could not remember saying it.
   ``Are you afraid to repeat it?'' Mueckenberger asked.
   ``No, but I can't remember now,'' Kassim said.
   Kassim said he was a Palestinian who lived in Lebanon before
coming to Germany in 1979. He now lives in the town of Merzig in
Saarland state, near the former residence of Abbas Hamadi.
   Mueckenberger said police questioned Kassim after Mohammed
Hamadi's arrest, but he did not specify the date.
</TEXT>
