<DOCNO> AP880804-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 1118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Sessions     08-04 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sessions,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Hopes New Program Will Help Reduce Demand for Illegal Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI Director William Sessions said today his
agency hopes a new program will help reduce the demand for illegal
drugs across the nation.
   Under the program, which began in April, one FBI agent in each
of the bureau's 58 field offices has been assigned to work with
local, state, school and business officials to educate the public
about the dangers of drugs.
   ``The bureau expanded its own view in the belief that we could
have a meaningful impact on demand reduction,'' Sessions told a
news conference.
   Agents in the field offices will spend only part of their time
on the drug program, according to Bob Davenport, an FBI official
who is directing the low-budget, $200,000 program.
   ``I think we have finally turned the corner in public
awareness,'' Davenport said.
   On another matter, Sessions said he will discuss with members of
Congress early next month a report on the FBI's investigation of a
group opposed to President Reagan's Central America policies.
   Reagan's spokesman, Marlin Fitzwater, said in February that he
was confident that the FBI did not conduct a massive spying
campaign into the Committee in Solidarity with the People of El
Salvador, or CISPES.
   Members of Congress have complained that the investigation was
mishandled.
</TEXT>
