<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0455,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede BUENOS AIRES</HEAD>
<HEAD>Shultz Arrives In Uruguay After Visit To Argentina</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs with Shultz in Montevideo. Changes byline.
Pickup 4th graf pvs, ``In Argentina...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL GIANELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz
arrived in Uruguay today for talks with top officials on drug
trafficking, the nation's eonomy and regional issues such as
Central America.
   Shultz arrived in Montevideo from Buenos Aires, where he said
relations between Argentina and the United States have improved.
   Several Marxist-controlled political, union and student
organizations have criticized the Shultz visit and threatened
demonstrations. After 11 hours in Uruguay, the third stop on his
nine-country Latin America tour, Shultz planned to fly to Brazil.
   Relations between the Unitd States and Argentina were strained
when the United States sided with Britain and against Argentina in
the 1982 Falklands War.
   ``There may be some wounds, but they are healing and that's what
we want to have happen,'' Shultz told a news conference in Buenos
Aires on Wednesday.
   In Argentina, Shultz met top government officials, businessmen
and political figures and dined privately with President Raul
Alfonsin.
   Defense Minister Horacion Jaunarena accepted an invitation,
delivered by Shultz from U.S. Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci, to
visit the United States this fall.
   The aim of Shultz's trip was to acknowlege a country that after
years of cool relations has become an ally and friend and to call
attention to Argentina's return to democracy.
   Generals and admirals ruled Argentina for most of the two
decades leading up to Alfonsin's election in October 1983 and
inauguration five weeks later.
   Most people who spoke with Shultz focused on Argentina's
economic problems and asked what the United States might do to help
overcome a $56 billion foreign debt and triple-digit inflation.
   Shultz's solution: the free market system.
   ``If you want to see economic development in a country, then
what needs to be done is to lighten up the regulatory load ...
privatize economic incentives, get tax rates down, get fiscal
policies into reasonable shape,'' he said.
   Shultz acknowleged that Argentina has asked the United States to
support a $500 million bridge loan, but refused to comment on the
status of the loan.
   He told the three main presidential candidates that the United
States would support whoever freely wins elections set for next
year to replace Alfonsin.
   ``What the United States supports is the process, the democratic
process,'' Shultz told reporters at the residence of U.S.
Ambassador Theodore Gildred. ``The outcome of the process is for
the people of Argentina to decide.''
   After lengthy meetings for two days, Shultz took time off
Wednesday to attend with his wife a cookout at a ranch in the heart
of this beef-producing country and tour Colon Theatre, Buenos
Aires' 80-year-old opera house.
   Britain and Argentina fought the 74-day Falklands War over
jurisdiction of islands in the South Atlantic. Argentina started
the war by attacking a British post and moving in 11,000 troops.
Britain retook the islands and won.
</TEXT>
