<HEAD>Ousted Panamanian President Reported Ready to Negotiate with
Noriega</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Eric Arturo Delvalle of Panama met last
month with an envoy sent by Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega and is
ready to negotiate to ease the country's crisis, The Miami Herald
reported today.
   Jose Blandon, a Panamian exile who was close to Noriega until
his defection earlier this year, told the Herald that he spoke with
Delvalle by telephone on Wednesday, and ``President Delvalle told
me that Noriega sent an emissary to him last month in the hope of
starting a negotiating process.
   ``He is ready to meet with Noriega to find a political
solution.''
   According to Blandon, Delvalle, who is living in hiding in
Panama since he was ousted earlier this year by Noriega, will
release a document this week announcing ``his willingness to
negotiate'' with Noriega.
   Noriega ``knows that only Delvalle can ask the U.S. government
to lift the U.S. economic sanctions against Panama,'' Blandon said.
The United States still recognizes Delvalle as the head of state
despite his ouster.
   Juan Sosa, the Delvalle appointee still recognized in Washington
as Panama's ambassador told the Herald that Delvalle had telephoned
him Wednesday to tell him about the meeting.
   Delvalle dismissed Noriega as defense chief Feb. 25, but was
ousted the following day by a vote in the Noriega-dominated
National Assembly.
