<2ND_LINE>PM-Carlucci,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Views Soviet Missile Cruiser</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEVASTOPOL, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci
ended a four-day visit to the Soviet Union today by boarding the
pride of the Black Sea Fleet, a new missile cruise capable of
carrying up to 16 nuclear weapons.
   Carlucci and Soviet Defense Minister Dmitri T. Yazov toured the
561-foot cruiser Slava docked in this important port on the Crimean
Peninsula 800 miles from Moscow.
   A U.S. naval officer said the defense secretary was the first
American official to board the cruiser.
   After inspection of the cruiser, Carlucci headed to Ankara,
Turkey, where he planned talks on Turkish-U.S. defense cooperation.
   Carlucci's visit to the Soviet Union was marked by a more open
posture by the Soviet military, which permitted close inspection of
some previously secret Kremlin hardware and military bases.
   However, Carlucci indicated on the first day of his visit that
he had his doubts about the Soviet peace initiative.
   Before 200 of the Kremlin's top brass, he said he has yet to see
evidence of a claimed change in Soviet military strategy to a
doctrine of defense.
   He also visited the Kubinka Air Force Base for the first look by
a Western official at the top-secret Blackjack bomber, then watched
Soviet war games at the Taman motorized rifle division base
southwest of the capital.
   Sevastopol was the last stop for Carlucci on his Soviet tour.
Earlier he toured an opulent mansion built by Russian Czar
Alexander III in a small town four miles from Yalta.
   He met there with President Andrei A. Gromyko in what Carlucci
called constructive talks. The defense secretary did not reveal the
nature of the talks, but said they touched on arms control.
</TEXT>
