<1ST_LINE>u a PM-BlackFratFire     08-04 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Black Frat Fire,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ole Miss's First Black Fraternity House Gutted by Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire today destroyed what was to be the
first black fraternity house at the University of Mississippi.
   The cause of the blaze at the vacant house was under
investigation by the state fire marshal's office, said fire Capt.
Ronnie Mills.
   The 20-member Phi Beta Sigma fraternity had planned to move in
to the two-story house later his month after winning approval to
become the first black tenants among the approximately 16
antebellum-style houses on Fraternity Row.
   ``There is no reason to expect any foul play at all. People are
going to make that assumption, but it's simply an old house and we
don't know what happened,'' said university spokesman Ed Meek.
   No utilities were connected at the house, and no one was
believed inside when the fire was reported at 3:28 a.m., he said.
Meek said the 50-year-old house had been vacant for some time.
   Some fraternity members who came to the house today declined to
comment. Phi Beta Sigma chapter adviser Thomas Wallace of New
Albany does not have a listed telephone number and couldn't
immediately be reached for comment.
   Meek said the state College Board recently approved leasing the
house to the black fraternity. He said the lease hadn't been signed
yet, but fraternity members had been allowed in in the past few
days to prepare to move in.
   ``It's a total loss. There's brick walls left on the outside,
but everything else is gutted,'' Meek said.
   Ann Cook, associate commissioner of higher education for the
state College Board, was among the educators who had applauded the
prospect of a black fraternity at Ole Miss, where riots broke out
in 1962 when James Meredith became the first black student to
register at the school.
   ``We feel like it just shows the new change in Mississippi _ the
new Mississippi,'' Cook said when the lease was approved.
   Meek said he didn't know if there were other vacant houses on
Fraternity Row that could be offered to the black fraternity. He
said the school will do its best to find other accommodations
before the students start arriving Aug. 20.
</TEXT>
