<1ST_LINE>u w PM-VincennesReport 2ndLd-Writethru a0560 08-04 0917</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vincennes Report, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0560,880</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, first 9 grafs, picking up 5th graf pvs, One
Pentagon</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It will take ``a considerable amount of time''
to determine how to compensate families of the 290 people killed
last month when a U.S. Navy missile destroyed a civilian Iranian
jetliner over the Persian Gulf, Reagan administration officials
said today.
   Meanwhile, the chairman of the House Armed Services Committee,
Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., said a conclusion that human mistakes in
the midst of combat caused the United States to shoot down the
plane could persuade Congress to approve the compensation.
   Pentagon sources said Wednesday that preliminary findings show
human error rather than malfunctioning equipment caused the Navy
warship Vincennes to fire on the Iran Air jetliner July 3.
   Testifying before the Armed Services Committee today, Abraham
Sofaer, the State Department's legal adviser, said the
administration will work as quickly as possible to fufill President
Reagan's promise that humanitarian compensation will be paid.
   But Sofaer terstified:
   ``We will need a considerable amount of time to determine how to
assess compensation and to obtain the information necessary from
the families or their governments.''
   While aiming to make tha payments promptly, he said, the United
States must also ``satisfy all professional and legal requirements
before making any payment, including obtaining legislative
authority if necessary or desirable.''
   Aspin said earlier that he has not seen a report that, according
to the sources, concludes there was no problem with the
sophisticated Aegis air-defense radar system on the USS Vincennes.
   ``If it turns out the United States is totally responsible and
human error was the responsibility, I think it will tilt the
chances of ... Congress going along with the idea of compensation,
not to the government but to the families,'' Aspin said on ABC-TV's
``Good Morning America.''
   One Pentagon official said, ``The biggest question when this
started was whether Aegis worked properly, and the inquiry has
found no evidence of a malfunction.'' Another official said the
inquiry determined there was ``no problem with the Aegis.''
   The defense officials agreed to discuss the preliminary findings
into the tragedy only on condition they not be identified. The
Vincennes shot down the airliner shortly after it had taken off
from a military and civilian airfield in Iran. All 290 passengers
and crew aboard the plane were killed.
   The sources stressed that the findings of the investigative team
that just returned from the gulf had yet to be accepted formally or
``endorsed'' by military brass or Defense Secretary Frank C.
Carlucci.
   ``But this (explanation) is very plausible,'' one source said.
``People underestimate the human factor and stress. You can't
replicate that in exercises and training.''
   The Vincennes, one of the Navy's newest and most sophisticated
ships, fired on the Iranian airliner after concluding it was an
Iranian jet fighter. The Vincennes' crew classified the approaching
radar ``contact'' as hostile and when the plane failed to respond
to radio warnings, the ship's skipper gave the order to open fire.
   The classification of that radar contact as hostile appears to
have been made by crewmen in the heat of battle without adequate
technical justification, one official said. There is no evidence
the Aegis radar system malfunctioned or that it presented technical
data to justify the ``hostile'' classification, the source
explained.
   ``Perhaps, understandably, there was misinterpretation,''
another official said.
   The ship was on high alert; Iranian fighters had been detected
operating from the same airfield in Iran just a short time earlier,
and the Vincennes had just survived its first combat action in the
gulf, a fight with three Iranian gunboats.
   Very quickly, almost upon takeoff, the plane was classified as
hostile, a source said.
   ``Here you had a bunch of people believing that the inbound was
hostile and thought to be a threat,'' the official said. ``So here
you've got a mindset.
   ``And you've got something (a contact) that obviously was not
responding to warnings, which further suggests that it might be
hostile. It's not as simple as just saying human error. They didn't
purposely shoot down an airliner.''
   The Pentagon refused to discuss the matter Wednesday, saying the
findings were still being reviewed by Gen. George B. Crist, the
head of the U.S. Central Command, and had yet to be forwarded to
Washington.
   Crist must decide whether to accept the findings of his
investigative team, which was led by Rear Adm. William Fogarty, the
Pentagon noted.
   President Reagan, in a brief question-and-answer exchange with
reporters, also declined to comment on the matter.
   ``I have read and heard and seen what is being said about the
report and assigning the blame to the people in the radar room
interpreting the signals and all,'' the president said.
   ``I can't comment because neither the military nor my office has
received the report,'' Reagan said.
   The sources said Wednesday the written report and documentary
evidence were still in Crist's hands, but that a few defense
officials _ including Carlucci _ had received oral briefings on the
status of the work.
   The New York Times, in a report Wednesday, said it appeared the
Vincennes crew mistook an electronic identification signal from a
C-130 aircraft at Bandar Abbas to be from the passenger airliner.
   The sources contacted by The Associated Press declined comment
on that aspect of the inquiry and also refused to say whether
investigators had advanced any explanation for the failure of the
Iranian airliner to respond to the Vincennes' radio warnings.
</TEXT>
