<2ND_LINE>PM-Pregnant Ticket,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pregnant Woman and Invalid Mother Left By Road When Car Impounded</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND HEIGHTS, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Missy Hasson's baby was due today,
but her license tag was due for renewal in June, so a police
officer impounded her car and left her by the road eight miles from
home.
   Mrs. Hasson, her 2-year-old son and her disabled mother were out
of the car and on the street after being stopped Tuesday. The
temperature was 93.
   ``It was very routine,'' said Officer Thomas A. Noonan. ``I've
arrested pregnant women before, and I've had their cars towed
before.''
   He said he knew Mrs. Hasson was pregnant when he approached the
car. He said he didn't know Mrs. Hasson's mother, Mary Ann Fetters,
42, was disabled until after he called a tow truck and Mrs. Hasson
opened the trunk to get a wheelchair.
   Fetters has suffered for 18 months from Lou Gehrig's disease,
her daughter said. She cannot walk, talk or feed herself, she said.
   Mrs. Hasson, 21, got her mother into the wheelchair, positioned
her son, Daniel Jr., on her mother's lap, and pushed them across a
busy four-lane highway to a nearby bowling alley, where she called
a friend for a ride home.
   ``He (Noonan) didn't help us at all,'' Mrs. Hanson said.
   Noonan, a police officer in northern Kentucky for four years,
defended his action and said the conditions of Mrs. Hasson and her
mother had no bearing on the citation for having an expired tag or
the decision to impound the car.
</TEXT>
