<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Doko     08-04 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Doko,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Business Leader Dead at 91</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toshiwo Doko, who helped revitalize Japanese
manufacturing firms after the war and promote the nation's recent
administrative and fiscal reform, died Thursday at the age of 91.
   Doko served as president of Toshiba Corp., the electronics
giant, and oversaw the privatization of Japan's railways.
   Born in southwestern Okayama city in 1896, Doko joined the Tokyo
Ishikawajima Shipyard, later renamed Ishikawajima Heavy Industries
Co., following his graduation from the Tokyo Higher Technical
School.
   Doko became president of Ishikawajima Heavy Industries in 1950
and helped rescue the firm from a recession.
   In 1964, Doko became chairman of Ishikawajima-Harima Heavy
Industries Co., a major heavy machinery maker, and was named
president of Toshiba the following year.
   From 1974 to 1980, Doko served as chairman of the powerful
Federation of Economic Organizatons, Keidanren, which groups about
1,000 major Japanese companies. While at Keidanren, Doko led
delegations to the Soviet Union and China.
   Doko was appointed chairman of the Prime Minister's Advisory
Council on Administrative Reform in 1981, and his group submitted a
recommendation two years later which led to the division of the
state-run Japan National Railways into several private companies in
1987.
</TEXT>
