<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 1226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-ContraAid 1stLd-Writethru a0420 08-04 0997</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Aid, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0420,960</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republicans Wary of Wright's Sway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Tops with 10 grafs with GOP considering package, White House
comment, picking up 2nd graf pvs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Democrats are proposing a new aid
package for Nicaragua's Contra rebels that defers a decision on
whether to resume the flow of U.S. weapons, but Republicans said
today they are wary because the deal gives too much influence to
House Speaker Jim Wright.
   The White House rejected the Democratic plan outright.
Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said it failed to provide
``any real hope for freedom and democracy in Nicaragua.''
   On Capitol Hill, Sen. Malcolm Wallop, R-Wyo., commented,
``Nobody trusts the speaker.'' He said Wright has reneged on past
promises as to when and how he would bring Contra aid to the House
floor.
   Republican senators _ along with Democratic Contra aid supporter
David Boren _ met today in Dole's office with National Security
Adviser Colin Powell to work out a strategy for reaching a
bipartisan agreement on an aid package that would give Wright less
discretion over whether lethal aid will ultimately flow to the
rebels.
   ``There are some clear differences'' between the two sides,
Powell said after the meeting. ``There's always room for a
compromise. We have to have a Contra aid bill'' before Congress
adjourns this fall.
   Fitzwater told reporters the Democratic proposal ``falls far
short. ... Humanitarian aid is too limited, too narrowly defined,
to be of any real help.''
   Drafting a bill that would win approval without giving Wright
what the Republicans feel is too much power is ``the No. 1
question,'' said Senate GOP Leader Bob Dole of Kansas.
   Added Jesse Helms, R-N.C., said, ``If cousin Jim doesn't sign on
this thing, it's not worth the paper it's written on.''
   On Wednesday, Dole said: ``No one elected Speaker Wright
president. I will not be a party to giving him a unilateral veto
over our national security policies in Central America.''
   The Democratic proposal, completed Wednesday, gave the party its
first show of unity on the aid issue in seven years.
   But the step goes only halfway to the goal Majority Leader
Robert Byrd was seeking: a bipartisan accord that will tell Central
America that the United States favors a peaceful solution, and at
the same time blunt the issue's political impact throughout the
fall election season.
   Byrd said his aid package, worked out over two weeks of
discussions with more than a dozen Senate Democrats, would provide
the incentives both the Contras and the leftist Sandinista
government need to achieve success in their faltering peace effort.
   ``This legislation can go either way,'' Byrd, D-W.Va., told
reporters as he announced the agreement at a news conference. It
can reward Nicaragua with aid and trade for making peace and
democratic reforms, or it can provide the fuel for the Contras to
resume their war on the Managua regime, he said.
   Peace talks have been suspended in an atmosphere of growing
tension since the last session between the two sides broke up in
disagreement June 9.
   The Sandinistas have arrested opposition leaders, shut down
opposition media outlets and expelled U.S. diplomats in recent
weeks. The Contras have elected a new, harder-line political
directorate and have been accused of carrying out attacks in the
countryside in violation of an informal cease-fire.
   Appearing at the news conference with Byrd were half a dozen
Democrats all along the spectrum on the Contra aid issue, from aid
proponent Sen. David Boren, D-Okla., to staunch opponents like
Sens. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., and Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.
   ``This is the first time in seven years the Democrats have come
together'' on the issue, Dodd said. But he acknowledged that the
unity was in large measure because the thorniest issue _ whether to
resume sending weapons to the rebels _ is deferred for a later vote
under terms of the proposal.
   The Democratic proposal would provide an additional $27 million
in ``humanitarian'' aid _ food, clothing, shelter and medical
supplies _ to continue current rates of such aid through next March.
   It also promises economic and trade assistance for Nicaragua if
the Managua government goes along with ``a comprehensive final
agreement to provide for peace and democracy in Nicaragua.''
   Conversely, some $16.3 million worth of stockpiled weaponry
could be released to the rebels if President Reagan certifies
before Congress adjourns for the year that two of three conditions
are met:
   _The Sandinistas have continued their recent pattern of
repression of political opponents and otherwise violated terms of
last year's regional peace agreement.
   _Nicaragua continues to receive an ``unacceptable level'' of
weaponry from Soviet-bloc countries, including Cuba.
   _The Sandinistas have launched an ``unprovoked military attack''
on the Contras.
   But the weapons, withheld from delivery to rebel forces since
the two sides entered a cease-fire earlier this year, would not be
released unless both houses of Congress voted to accept Reagan's
certification.
   The House, which traditionally has been more opposed to lethal
aid for the rebels, would have to vote first on the presidential
certification, and that appeared to be high on Dole's list of
objections.
   Dole's aid proposal would provide the same $27 million in
humanitarian aid for the rebels, but also would create a separate,
new $20 million military aid fund that would be held in escrow, to
be triggered by a later vote of Congress if circumstances in
Central America warrant.
   The Democratic proposal would provide up to $2 million to
transport the stockpiled weapons, which are left over from an
earlier $100 million lethal aid appropriation. The transportation
presumably would be handled by the CIA, which handled air drops to
the Contras under the administration's earlier covert aid program.
   Other features of the Democratic plan include up to $10 million
for use in relocating Contra fighters to Nicaragua if the two sides
sign a peace accord providing for democracy there, and $5 million
in medical aid to the civilian population in Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
