<HEAD>Helping Animals See Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. HACKETT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   His patients can't read even the top line
on the chart and they sometimes respond to his examinations by
biting, kicking or stomping, but Dr. Kerry Ketring understands.
   ``It happens now and then because they may not understand that
you're trying to help them,'' said Ketring, an ophthalmologist and
veterinarian who works out of Cincinnati.
   He is called when other veterinarians from Dayton, Ohio, to
Lexington, Ky., have a difficult case to diagnose or need a second
opinion about an eye disease.
   The waiting rooms are usually full and he isn't surprised.
   ``Pets are important to people, as close as relatives many
times,'' said Ketring, who also serves as a consultant for zoos and
research facilities.
   The Louisville zoo recently brought him a young wallaby, a
relative of the kangaroo.
   The wallaby, imported from New Zealand, was still in 90-day
quarantine when the staff noticed she was having trouble moving
around her quarters and was bumping into things.
   Ketring spent at least 20 minutes examining the animal before
announcing: ``She's totally blind. The retina is gone.''
   Ketring wouldn't speculate what caused the condition.
   ``Hopefully, the wallaby can be kept in a controlled environment
and used for breeding purposes. You always try to think15

</TEXT>
<HEAD>AM-BRF--SAfrica-Guerrillas,0118</HEAD>
<HEAD>Police Say Five Suspected Guerrillas Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five men suspected of being
guerrillas were killed by police near the country's northern border
with Botswana and Zimbabwe, authorities said Thursday.
   Police confiscated AK-47 rifles, grenades, pistols and several
land mines after they killed the five in the town of Alldays on
Wednesday, said Gen. Hennie de Witt, commissioner of police.
   There were no casualties among the police, de Witt said, without
giving any more details.
   He did not say if those killed belonged to any guerrilla group.
Police generally link most suspected guerrillas to the outlawed
African National Congress, the main black group attempting to
overthrow the white government.
