<1ST_LINE>u w BC-Congress-Convictions 1stLd-Writethru a0604 08-04 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Congress-Convictions, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0604,0750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Biaggi 12th Lawmaker In Decade To Be Convicted Or Plead Guilty</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to CORRECT Biaggi to Democrat sted Republican</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Biaggi-Wedtech</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Mario Biaggi, D-N.Y., found guilty
Thursday of all but one of 16 counts including conspiracy,
extortion, tax evasion and receiving bribes in the Wedtech
corruption scandal, is the 12th member of congress to be convicted
of criminal charges or plead guilty to them during the past decade.
   Biaggi, 70, also was convicted Sept. 22, 1987, of obstructing
justice, accepting a gratuity, and illegal interstate travel in a
case involving charges he had accepted paid vacations from a former
leader of the Brooklyn Democratic Party. Biaggi was acquitted of
more serious bribery and conspiracy charges.
   The 10-term Bronx congressman was the 15th federal lawmaker to
be indicted over the past decade, and the second one indicted in
1987.
   The other congressman to be indicted in 1987, Rep. Harold E.
Ford, D- Tenn., was charged in April of last year with bank, mail
and tax fraud.
   Other members of Congress indicted since early 1977:
   _Rep. Charles C. Diggs Jr., D-Mich., was indicted in March 1978
and convicted in October 1978 on 29 felony counts of illegally
diverting his congressional employees' salaries to his personal
use. Censured by the House in 1979, Diggs resigned from Congress in
1980 and served seven months of a three-year prison sentence.
   _Rep. Daniel J. Flood, D-Pa., was indicted in the fall of 1978
on 13 counts of bribery, conspiracy and perjury. His trial on 11
counts ended in mistrial in February 1979, and he resigned from the
House in January 1980 for health reasons, after the House ethics
committee had accused him of 25 violations of House rules. In
February 1980, he pleaded guilty to conspiracy, in a
plea-bargaining arrangement, and was given a year's probation.
   _Rep. Joshua Eilberg, D-Pa., was indicted in October 1978 on
federal charges of illegally receiving compensation to help a
Philadelphia hospital get a $14.5 million federal grant. He pleaded
guilty in February 1979 and was sentenced to five years' probation
and fined $10,000.
   _Rep. Claude ``Buddy'' Leach, D-La., was indicted in July 1979
on charges of buying votes in the 1978 elections, and was accused
of violating federal campaign finance laws. He was acquitted of
some vote-buying counts and the others were dropped, and a court
dismissed the charges of campaign finance law violations.
   _Sen. Harrison Williams Jr., D-N.J., was convicted in May 1981
on charges stemming from the FBI's Abscam investigation, including
conspiracy, bribery, conflict of interest, receiving an unlawful
gratuity and interstate travel in aid of a racketeering enterprise.
   Williams resigned from the Senate in March 1982. He was paroled
from a Newark, N.J., halfway house in January 1986 after serving
nearly two years of a three-year sentence at the federal
penitentiary at Allenwood, Pa.
   Six House members also were indicted as a result of the
undercover Abscam investigation, and all served prison terms. They
were:
   Rep. Raymond Lederer, D-Pa., was convicted in January 1981 of
conspiracy, bribery, receiving an unlawful gratuity and interstate
travel to further racketeering; Rep. Michael Myers, D-Pa., was
convicted in August 1980 of conspiracy, bribery and interstate
travel; Rep. John Jenrette, D-S.C., was convicted in October 1980
of sharing a $50,000 bribe.
   Also, Rep. John Murphy, D-N.Y., was convicted in December 1980
of conspiracy, conflict of interest and receiving an unlawful
gratuity; Rep. Frank Thompson, D-N.J., was convicted in December
1980 of bribery, conspiracy and aiding and abetting in the
acceptance of a criminal gratuity; Rep. Richard Kelly, R-Fla., was
convicted in Januery 1981 of taking a $25,000 bribe from an
undercover FBI agent and of taking part in a $250,000 bribery
conspiracy.
   _Rep. George Hansen, R-Idaho, indicted in April 1983 and
convicted one year later on charges of violating the 1978 Ethics in
Government Act by failing to report $333,978 in loans and other
transactions on his financial disclosure forms. He surrendered June
20, 1986, to begin serving a sentence of 5 to 15 months at the
federal correctional facility at Petersburg, Va., and was released
on parole Dec. 19, 1986.
   _Rep. Bobbi Fiedler, R-Calif., was indicted Jan. 23, 1986, along
with aide on charges she tried to buy off an opponent for the GOP
Senate nomination in California. The charges subsequently were
dismissed by a Superior Court judge in Los Angeles, and she lost
the GOP primary.
</TEXT>
