<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 1341EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PeaceCruise     08-04 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peace Cruise,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Citizen Diplomats' Cruise Mississippi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET McCONNAUGHEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A boatload of Soviets and Americans will
steam down the Mississippi River from St. Louis this week in a
cruise organized by peace groups in both countries.
   During a nine-day trip to New Orleans, 50 Soviets and 125
Americans will get to know one another during workshops on
``perestroika, glasnost and democratization'' and ``social issues
and human rights,'' among others.
   ``We're trying to avoid a nuclear holocaust,'' said Lou
Friedman, spokesman for Promoting Enduring Peace of Woodmont,
Conn., the cruise's U.S. sponsor.
   ``The two nuclear superpowers as antagonists destabilize the
nuclear situation in the world terribly. So ... the one thing that
can help this situation is for Americans and Soviets to get to know
each other.''
   The cruise begins Friday in St. Louis and ends in the French
Quarter on Aug. 14, one day before the Republican National
Convention. That is coincidence _ plans for the cruise began a year
before those for the GOP convention, said Friedman.
   A similar group cruised the upper Mississippi, from St. Paul to
St. Louis, in 1986.
   ``We'd come into a dock on the upper Mississippi at 2 o'clock in
the morning 25 miles from nowhere and it was pouring rain,'' he
said. ``There'd be 200 people waiting their to greet the Soviets.
For four hours they'd be waiting in the rain. Grandfathers who'd
fought in the second World War who wanted their grandchildren to
see the Soviets.''
   American participants applied through one of a dozen U.S. peace
groups and the Soviets through the Soviet Peace Committee, which
Friedman said has organized eight similar cruises along the Volga
River since 1982.
   Most of the Americans are paying their own ways; the Soviet
Peace Committee pays airfare, cabin fare _ $1,729 to $3,189 _ and
other expenses for the Soviets, Friedman said.
   This summer's drought may make a stop planned Saturday at Cape
Giradeau, Mo., impossible if the river is still too low. Other
stops are planned Tuesday at Memphis, Tenn.; Wednesday at
Greenville, Miss.; Thursdsay at Vicksburg, Miss.; Friday at
Natchez, Miss.; and Aug. 13 at Baton Rouge.
</TEXT>
