<1ST_LINE>u a PM-UniversitySurgeon     08-04 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-University Surgeon,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Surgeon Steps Aside Temporarily Over Newspaper Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Minnesota's chief
heart-lung surgeon has temporarily stepped down from his leadership
posts amid controversy generated by an article a newspaper now
regrets publishing.
   The Star Tribune today said running the story was a ``serious
lapse in journalistic judgment.''
   The newspaper reported Tuesday that Dr. Stuart Jamieson was
being investigated by the university for allegedly ordering an
associate to perform bypass surgery on a patient considered dead
before the operation began.
   The University of Minnesota issued a statement Wednesday saying
Jamieson was stepping aside temporarily from his positions as head
of cardiovascular surgery and director of the university's Heart
and Lung Institute.
   Jamieson and University Hospital's chief of staff and general
director have ``discussed a set of expectations regarding
compliance with hospital policy and procedure and medical staff
standards,'' the university said.
   In a front-page statement today, Star Tribune executive editor
Joel Kramer said the account of the surgery should not have been
published ``because it was based on sources who did not have
firsthand information to support the account.''
   ``The surgeon who performed the operation, Dr. Jolene Kriett,
has since denied that Dr. Jamieson knew anything about the surgery
until several hours after it was performed,'' Kramer said. ``The
Star Tribune's efforts to reach Dr. Kriett before publication of
the first story were unsuccessful, and Dr. Jamieson had refused to
comment.
   ``Publishing the account of the events, when we had not
confirmed it with anyone having firsthand knowledge of the facts,
was a serious lapse in journalistic judgment, which we regret,'' he
said.
   Jamieson, 40, who came to the university two years ago from
Stanford University, will continue in his academic position as
surgery professor and will continue as a member of the medical
staff of the University of Minnesota Hospital and Clinic, the
university statement said.
   Jamieson could not be reached for comment because he left on a
two-week vacation Wednesday. The statement said hospital
authorities had no further comment.
   However, the St. Paul Pioneer Press Dispatch quoted sources as
saying Jamieson was asked to step down from the leadership roles.
The newspaper said there has been a sharp dispute over his
personality and aggressive management style.
   Kriett told the Star Tribune and the Pioneer Press Dispatch
Tuesday night that she did not consult with Jamieson before
deciding to operate on a 43-year-old woman whose heart had stopped
beating five times before surgery began.
   ``It sure didn't happen as it was reported in the paper,'' the
Pioneer Press Dispatch quoted Kriett as saying. ``I was the one on
call and it was my own decision.''
   Dr. Neal Vanselow, university vice president for health
sciences, said Wednesday that the university is ``looking into some
allegations against Jamieson, and the Kriett surgery is one of
them.''
   Kriett said she canceled the surgery after the patient's heart
stopped beating but decided a few minutes later to proceed with the
operation in a final attempt to save the woman's life.
</TEXT>
