<2ND_LINE>AM-Times Mirror Poll,980</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Embargoed for Release at 6 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Poll Predicts Close Presidential Contest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The West, a graveyard for Democratic
presidential aspirations in recent years, could be the key to
victory for Michael Dukakis this fall, according to surveys
conducted for the Times Mirror Co. by The Gallup Organization.
   Dukakis is currently enjoying a wide lead over Vice President
George Bush across most of the nation, but the American mood is so
divided that it could be a close election come November, said the
head of the Gallup organization.
   ``The numbers have been pretty wide, but the potential to narrow
is very great,'' said Andrew Kohut of Dukakis' lead.
   But, he added, the outlook of westerners appears to have changed.
   For example, ``traditionally anti-government voters in the Rocky
Mountains are now calling for more government action on social
issues than is the average American voter. They are most strongly
in favor of free health care for the needy, national health
insurance and help for the homeless,'' his report said.
   The West holds 111 of the 270 electoral votes needed to elect a
president, votes that have gone mostly to Republicans in recent
years.
   Western voters, while optimistic about their own financial
future, are dissatisfied with the general course of the nation and
they have not found in Bush the anti-establishment leader they once
saw in Ronald Reagan, he wrote.
   In national polls taken shortly after his nomination on July 20,
Dukakis led Bush 54 percent to 39 percent, Kohut said in releasing
the new analysis of the election prospects prepared for the Times
Mirror Co.
   While the attention generated by the upcoming Republican
national convention should help Bush narrow the gap, Kohut said he
expects Dukakis to retain a lead at least through the first debate
between the two men, which will likely set the tone for the balance
of the campaign.
   ``It's likely to be a close election. It's an uncertain
electorate, one that is divided in mood,'' explained Kohut. ``On
the one hand there is short run economic optimism, but that is
balanced in various ways with dissatisfaction with the state of the
nation.''
   ``It's a balancing act for both of them,'' he said, of Bush and
Dukakis.
   ``People clearly don't want radical change. They want some
change, but they are not sure what that change is,'' Kohut said.
   The Iran-Contra scandal has proven a major factor, Kohut said,
seriously damaging the confidence of many supporters of President
Reagan's administration.
   That has been a particular problem in the Rocky Mountain states,
said Kohut. That region was a bastion of support for Reagan and
many people there saw selling arms to Iran as betrayal and are
``really angry.''
   Dukakis led Bush 49 percent to 39 percent in the West in surveys
taken in late June and early July, according to Kohut. The results
reflected Bush's problem of being associated with the Iran-Contra
scandal, but being unable to benefit from economic improvement
because that area has not done as well as other regions, he said.
   In May, Dukakis led 51 percent to 39 percent in the Rockies and
51 percent to 40 percent in the Pacific States.
   Kohut said the regional analyses he released were developed from
8,500 detailed interviews taken between May and July. The margin of
error for a survey of that size is just under 2 percentage points
either way.
   ``I don't think that either candidate can take for granted ...
any state,'' commented Kohut. All of the big states are close
``except maybe New York,'' he said. He showed the Massachusetts
governor leading in the Empire State.
   Dukakis can be expected to do well in the East, he said. Kohut
noted that the East is Dukakis' home area, and he said Easterners
tend to have a stronger interest in an activist government, meaning
they are more likely to lean toward a Democrat. The Eastern states
offer 135 electoral votes, Kohut said.
   His June-July polls showed Dukakis leading 49 percent to 41
percent in the East. A separate study taken earlier gave Dukakis a
54 percent to 34 percent lead in New England and 55 percent to 36
percent in the Middle Atlantic states.
   Dukakis' lead in the East is ``significant, if soft'' says
Kohut. The region is more likely to disapprove of the Reagan
administration and more willing to endorse an activist social
agenda, he said.
   In the Midwest, with 137 electoral votes, Bush faces a problem
with voters the pollster termed ``the disaffected.''
   These people supported Reagan because he campaigned against
government as an outsider, but many are turning toward the
Democratic Party.
   In the nation's center, Dukakis leads Bush 47 percent to 37
percent in the June-July polling, the report said. In May that lead
had been 52 percent to 39 percent in the east central states and 52
percent to 36 percent in the west central.
   Dukakis Midwestern lead is bolstered by economic discontent,
Kohut concluded. ``Still, Dukakis' edge there is `soft' and is as
likely to be fueled by anti-Bush sentiment as by positive support
for the Democratic nominee.''
   Only in the more conservative South, with 155 electoral votes,
does Bush hold a lead, topping Dukakis 47 percent to 40 percent,
according to the June-July survey. Dukakis had held a narrow
three-point lead in the Southeast in M
</TEXT>
