<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 1352EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ThreeStooges     08-04 0695</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Three Stooges,0716</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hey Moe! Fans Woo-Woo-Woo-Woop It Up For Stooges Stamp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fans of three knuckleheads famed for
bopping each other on the head, throwing pies and chortling
``n'yuk, n'yuk, n'yuk'' are writing letters and circulating
petitions to get the government's attention.
   The Three Stooges, they insist, deserve to be honored on a U.S.
postage stamp.
   ``They were the longest-running comedy team in the history of
motion pictures. Laurel and Hardy, Abbott and Costello and the Marx
Brothers pale in significance compared with the Stooges,'' said
Jeff Lenberg, a Southern California writer and Stooge historian.
   Lenberg and other admirers of Moe, Larry and Curly _ not to
forget Shemp, Joe and Curly-Joe _ say the Stooges are part of
modern American culture.
   ``My father always said their comedy was based on the upsetting
of dignity. And I thought of George Washington getting his wig
knocked off. That's what the Stooges would have done to him,'' said
Joan Howard Maurer.
   Maurer, daughter of Moe Howard _ the one with the trademark
bangs and scowl _ launched the stamp campaign last year in her
fifth book on the Stooges.
   After all, W.C. Fields was honored with a stamp in 1980, and
recently the postmaster general said Laurel and Hardy could appear
on a stamp.
   But Stooge afficionados point out that while Fields and Laurel
and Hardy are seldom seen nowadays, the Stooges _ who began with
vaudeville and reached their height in film _ are still seen on
television all over the world.
   ``If you stopped people on the street and showed them a picture
of the Three Stooges, they'd know them right away,'' said Gary
Lassin, president of the Three Stooges Fan Club, with about 2,000
members worldwide.
   Stephanie Salter, a San Francisco Examiner columnist, is
relaying hundreds of pro-Stooge letters to the Postal Service's
Citizens Stamp Advisory Committee.
   ``I just think that it's the fact the world is getting heavier
every day. I just can't emphasize the importance of silliness,''
Salter said.
   The silliness as most people know it began in 1934, when Moe,
brother Curly and a violin player with a receding mop named Larry
Fine made ``Women Haters,'' their first short for Columbia.
   ``The whole concept was that Moe was the brains of the outfit,
supported by Larry the middleman, who was supposed to be a little
less smart than Moe but more intelligent than Curly,'' Lenberg said.
   ``But Moe always came out as not so smart after all. He was as
much a stooge as Curly or Larry,'' he said.
   Curly, the one with the shaved head and high-pitched
``EEE-bee-bee-bee,'' was sidelined by a stroke in 1946 and replaced
by Shemp Howard. Shemp died in 1955 and was replaced first by Joe
Besser, who stayed with the group for three years, and finally by
Joe DeRita, who resembled the original Curly and was known as
Curly-Joe.
   The group kept working until 1970. Moe and Larry died in 1975,
Besser died within the past year, and DeRita, now 79, lives in
North Hollywood, Lenberg said.
   While some dislike the violence of the Stooges' routines, fans
describe the group as a living cartoon.
   ``It smacks of Wile E. Coyote and Roadrunner,'' Maurer said.
``Most children, unless they really have a behavior problem, know
this is not real. You see Curly getting hit with an anvil, but he
just scratches his head and says `OO-ooh!'''
   ``They got away with things everyone wants to get away with but
can't. Wouldn't you like to kick your boss in the rear or throw a
pie in a society matron's face?'' Lassin said.
   But how much chance does the stamp campaign have?
   Many of the 2,000 requests the Citizens Stamp Advisory Committee
receives a month are for Elvis Presley, John Wayne or Marilyn
Monroe, said Dick Rustin, manager of stamp information for the
Postal Service. So far only a few have come from Stooge fans, he
said.
   And even if lovers of the Stooges flood the committee with
letters, the selection process can take several years, Rustin said.
   ``But we choose to believe it can't hurt,'' Lassin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
