<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Paraguay-Protest     08-04 0154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Paraguay-Protest,0159</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>University Students Protest Priest's Expulsion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students and professors boycotted
classes at the Catholic University on Thursday to protest the
expulsion of a Jesuit priest by the government of President Alfredo
Stroessner.
   Authorities said the boycott at the university, the nation's
second-largest with 8,000 students enrolled in Asuncion and four
branches, protested the expulsion of the Rev. Juan Antonio de la
Vega.
   De la Vega, 65, who taught canon law at the university, was
arrested and expelled to neighboring Argentina on July 25.
   The government accused him advocating its violent overthrow. The
church denied the charges.
   Church sources said a ``march of silence'' by priests and the
laity was being organized for Saturday in Asuncion as a further
protest.
   In a message read at all Masses on Sunday, the church charged it
was being persecuted and called on the government to ``respect the
fundamental rights of human dignity.''
</TEXT>
