<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Productivity 1stLd-Writethru a0588 08-04 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Productivity, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0588,390</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf White House comment after 3rd graf pvs,
Productivity had</NOTE>
<HEAD>Efficiency Measure Down First Time Since 1986</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. businesses' efficiency in producing goods
and services decreased in the second quarter, its first decline
since 1986, the Labor Department said today.
   Preliminary data show productivity among non-farm businesses,
responsible for three-fourths of the nation's economic activity,
falling 1.7 percent from April through June compared with the first
three months of the year, the department said.
   Productivity had risen at an annual rate of 3.4 percent from
January through March.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater commented, ``The second
quarter decline in productivity should be a temporary blip related
to the drought. So it shows the economy is still strong.''
   Reflecting the continuing strong economic expansion, output of
goods and services by non-farm businesses rose at an annual rate of
4.7 percent in the second quarter.
   To achieve that, workers put in 6.5 percent more hours, the
largest quarterly increase since 1984 and a reflection of the
14-year low in the nation's unemployment rate.
   Meanwhile, labor costs soared 5.9 percent, the largest gain
since a 6.1 percent increase in the last quarter of 1986, as hourly
wages and benefits rose at an annual rate of 4.1 percent in the
second quarter.
   After taking into consideration a 4.4 percent annual rate of
inflation over the last 18 months, however, workers' purchasing
power actually declined 0.6 percent from April through June, the
department said.
   While businesses as a whole suffered from poorer efficiency in
the second quarter, manufacturers, responsible for a fourth of the
nation's economic output, continued to show improved productivity,
up 3.5 percent from the first quarter.
   Reflecting an ongoing boom in the industrial sector spawned by
record exports, manufacturing output soared 5.4 percent in the
second quarter with only a 1.8 percent increase in the number of
hours worked.
   Manufacturers also were much more successful in holding down
factory wage and benefit increases, allowing annual raises of only
2.9 percent from April through June.
   That enabled employers to actually reduce the labor costs
associated with each item coming off their assembly lines by 0.6
percent, even though it meant their workers took a 1.8 percent cut
in their purchasing power, the government said.
</TEXT>
