<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Vietnam-US 1stLd-Writethru   08-04 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-US, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0471,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Halts Cooperation On Missing U.S. Servicemen, Refugee
Resettlement</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS 2 grafs after 3rd, `Agreements on...' with White
House comment. Pick up 4th pvs, `The Vietnam...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOLLY YONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam's foreign minister today said
his country will no longer help account for missing U.S. servicemen
or cooperate on other humanitarian issues until Washington ends its
``hostile policy against my government.''
   Vietnam announced Wednesday that it has temporarily halted plans
for joint efforts to account for missing Americans and for
resettling former political prisoners in the United States.
   Agreements on the issues had been reached last month.
   In Washington, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said, ``We
are very concerned, because we thought we were making some progress
at getting the investigations going about MIA's and POW's.''
   ``Our position has always been clear,'' Fitzwater said. ``I
guess we're a little surprised and not quite sure what Vietnam is
up to here.''
   The Vietnam News Agency said Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach
wrote a letter dated Sunday to Gen. John W. Vessey, a special U.S.
presidential emissary, saying the decision to halt cooperation was
in response to recent congressional testimony by Assistant
Secretary of State Gaston Sigur.
   Sigur on July 28 argued against a congressional resolution
urging the establishment of ``interest sections'' _ diplomatic
missions below the level of embassies _ in Hanoi and Washington,
saying they would not improve cooperation on humanitarian issues.
   He called for continued U.S. isolation of Vietnam until it ends
it decade-old military occupation of Cambodia.
   Thach spoke with reporters in Bangkok today after holding talks
on Cambodia with Thailand's Foreign Minister Siddhi Savetsila.
   Asked how long Vietnam was suspending cooperation on U.S.
humanitarian issues, he replied: ``I would like to ask Gen. Vessey
this question, how long they will continue such hostile policy
against my government?''
   He said it was not a question of the United States apologizing,
but rather ``a question of hostile policy against my country, to
stop it.''
   Thach and Vessey reached an agreement in August 1987 under which
Vietnam pledged to accelerate its accounting of nearly 1,800
Americans listing as missing in action in the Vietnam war. The
United States pledged to help Vietnam with its humanitarian
problems.
   Thach told Vessey last month that Vietnam will try to resolve 70
top priority MIA cases by the end of the year and welcomed joint
excavations for remains from August to October.
   There have no such excavations since the first one in late 1985.
   Technical experts of the two sides met in Hanoi last week to
work out arrangements and U.S. officials said they anticipated
joint surveys and investigations that would begin soon.
   The two countries held talks in Hanoi last month on America's
offer to resettle former U.S. government employees and officials of
the U.S.-backed South Vietnam government who were put into
``re-education camps'' after the 1975 North Vietnamese victory.
   A joint communique said Vietnam was allowing them to emigrate as
the United States gave assurances it would not encourage them to
conduct anti-Vietnamese activities.
   But the official Vietnamese media later blamed the U.S. for lack
of progress, saying the biggest obstacle was the U.S. refusal to
set up a ``working group'' to organize the emigration of about
500,000 of the former inmates and their relatives.
</TEXT>
