<1ST_LINE>r i AM-FAO-US     08-04 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FAO-US,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Pays $25 Million of Arrears to U.N. Agency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has paid $25 million of what it
owes to the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization to show it is
encouraged by the agency's progress in budgetary reform, a diplomat
said Thursday.
   FAO spokesman Richard Lydiker confirmed the United States made
the payment last week, saying the payment came in the wake of a
compromise agreement on the budgetary process.
   The diplomat said the compromise suggested to the U.S.
government that ``FAO was making progress toward reforms'' sought
by the United States and other nations. He also said the U.S.
government was ``pleased and encouraged by the favorable
developments and therefore decided to release the funds.''
   The United States had withheld payments of its assessments,
which amount to a quarter of the agency's budget, in an effort to
force the organization to make budgetary reforms.
   The Rome-based organization coordinates agricultural projects in
developing countries and is the largest specialized agency in the
United Nations.
   The diplomat, who spoke on condition that he not be identified
by name or country, said United States made the payment July 27 in
Washington and that it will be applied to the arrears of $67.4
million for 1986 and 1987.
   The United States also has not paid its 1988 assessment of $60.7
million and $3.9 million for its share of the working capital and
special reserve accounts.
   The diplomat said the United States has expressed its intention
to pay its arrears and meet its assessment, but that the timing has
not been determined.
   ``Future payments will depend on continued progress by the
organization in pursuing the reforms,'' he said.
</TEXT>
