<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Refugees     08-04 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Refugees,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Agreement Reached At Boat People Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hong Kong and Hanoi have not reached any
solutions on repatriating Vietnamese refugees, but they agreed to
meet again soon, a government statement said Thursday.
   The statement said meetings this week between the two
governments regarding repatriating Vietnamese boat people were
``open and friendly.''
   Both sides agreed the historical and social causes of the
outflow were complex but ``realistic and effective measures to
bring it to an end were urgently required,'' the statement said. It
did not elaborate on when future meetings might be held.
   Earlier Thursday, Vietnamese foreign minister Nguyen Co Thach
told reporters after talks with the Thai government that Vietnam
will take back all people who wish to return home after fleeing by
boat.
   On June 16, Hong Kong started to curb surging arrivals of
Vietnamese boat people by ending its open-door policy. Vietnamese
who cannot prove they are fleeing political persecution are
considered illegal immigrants subject to repatriation.
   About 7,000 Vietnamese have sailed into Hong Kong since the
policy came into effect and the number of Vietnamese staying in
Hong Kong camps is approaching 23,000.
</TEXT>
