<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Locusts 1stLd-Writethru a0611 08-04 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Locusts, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0611,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Call For Increased War Against Locusts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to CORRECT day of week to Thursday, sted
Wednesday.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An agricultural official on
Thursday warned that swarms of locusts in northern Ethiopia will
breed fast because of recent rains and may invade the central part
of the country.
   Hailu Kassa, head of crop protection and control department in
the Ministry of Agriculture, said the Desert Locust Control
Organization of East Africa has provided 100,000 tons of
insecticide, spraying equipment, trucks and a plane to fight the
pests in Tigray and Eritrea provinces.
   The government will provide two more planes. It asked the United
Nations Food and Agricultural Organization for more insecticide.
   The desert locust control organization said five huge swarms
were seen flying near Asmara, capital of Eritrea, on July 21-24.
Some of the swarms contained more than 50 million locusts each and
were capable of eating more than 100 tons of green vegetation in
one day.
   Kassa said the locusts had been blown across the Red Sea from
Saudi Arabia by a hurricane. They invaded Tigray and Eritrea after
farmers started planting crops following a severe drought that
threatened millions with starvation.
   Four years ago, drought and famine in the region killed an
estimated 1 million people and spurred the biggest international
relief operation in history.
</TEXT>
