<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 1358EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan-Floods     08-04 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Floods,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Floods Kill 158 In Pakistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Floods caused by monsoon rains have
swept through three provinces of Pakistan, killing 158 people and
causing extensive damage to property and crops, the minister of
justice said Thursday.
   The disaster began three weeks ago in the provinces of Punjab,
Sind and the North West Frontier, said the minister, Wasim Sajjad.
Most of the victims drowned or were crushed when their houses
collapsed, he said.
   Twenty-four of the victims died Wednesday, including 11 from one
family, when floods and lightning destroyed several homes in
Chugarazai, a village 100 100 miles northwest of Islamabad,
officials said earlier.
   Sajjad said more than 1 million people have been affected by the
floods and by rains nationwide and that 2.67 million acres of land
have been inundated. He said more than 60,000 acres of crops have
been destroyed.
   More than 100,000 people have been moved into temporary
government camps, he said, and the flooding has destroyed 19,000
homes and damaged 31,000.
   Sajjad released the figures in a report to the Senate, where
some lawmakers said the government had failed to take adequate
action to protect people from monsoon rains and flooding in three
rivers: the Indus, Chenab and Jhelum.
   In addition to the seasonal monsoon rains, Pakistan has received
50 percent rain this summer than during the same time last year.
   The death toll and damage to property and crops will continue to
rise as the floods and heavy rains continue in northern Pakistan,
he said.
</TEXT>
