<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 1359EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Italy-Kidnap     08-04 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Italy-Kidnap,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Holding 8 in Boy's Kidnap</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TURIN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have arrested four more people in the
17-month kidnapping of an 8-year-old boy, authorities said Thursday.
   The arrests bring to eight the number of people held in the
abduction of Marco Fiora, who was freed Tuesday in the mountains of
southern Calabria.
   All eight had been arrested before the boy was released, but
news of the new arrests was withheld. They were accused of
complicity in the kidnapping.
   Police said the kidnapping was believed to have been carried out
by members of the `Ndrangheta, the Calabrian version of the Mafia.
   Marco was kidnapped on March 2, 1987, by a gang of masked and
armed bandits as his parents were driving him to school.
   The kidnappers demanded a ransom of about $4 million. Marco's
parents, who run a garage and bakery, said they were unable to pay
such a high ransom.
   Police said the family paid only about $220,000. The gang is
believed to have released the boy out of fear police were closing
in.
   ``It (the abduction) was a mistake,'' said Aldo Faraoni, chief
of Turin's detective squad, adding that the family could never have
met the ransom demanded by the kidnappers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
