<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Walters-Gulf 1stLd-Writethru a0592 08-04 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Walters-Gulf, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0592,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Ambassador Calls Iran's attack on a Norwegian tanker
reprehensible</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts grafs 11-12, His statement.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vernon Walters, the U.S. ambassador to the
United Nations, today called Iran's attack on a Norwegian tanker
reprehensible, but attributed it to ``excessive zeal'' by a local
commander.
   Walters said Iran and Iraq clearly had decided to end their war
in the Persian Gulf and that it would take some time for fighting
to taper off because of `'pent-up hostility'' on the two sides.
   ``After an eight-year war,'' Walters said, ``I don't consider
two weeks an excessive time'' to work out cease-fire terms.
   The U.S. diplomat recalled the protracted negotiations that were
required to end the wars in Korea and Vietnam.
   Iranian gunboats fired at the Norwegian tanker after it had
refused to stop for inspection, shipping executives in the gulf
said. The captain said a few bullets pierced the ship but caused no
injuries.
   Walters, appearing on a U.S.-sponsored telecast to the area,
said ``any attack on neutral shipping is to be reprehended. It is
wrong.''
   He said he was ``quite surprised'' by the attack, and added:
``Attacks on neutral shipping by belligerents are not justifiable
by any circumstances.''
   And yet, Walter said, ``I think this was a case of excessive
zeal by a local commander. I think both countries have maintained
that their national choice is for peace.''
   ``What we are witnessing is some of the bitterness and some of
the hostility of eight years of war manifesting itself.'' Walters
said. ``But in my view the two countries have made the choice for
peace.''
   For the second time this week, the U.S. ambassador supported
Iraq's demand for face-to-face negotiations with Iran.
   ``I don't believe it is possible for two countries to make peace
without face-to-face discussions,'' he said. ``I have never heard
of a peace being achieved entirely through third parties.''
   His statement raised questions about U.S. policy on the issue.
   Phyllis Oakley, the State Department spokeswoman, renewed the
U.S. call for swift implementation of the cease-fire without
``conditions that only prolong'' the delay.
   The United Nations Security Council's cease-fire resolution does
prescribe direct negotiations between the two sides.
   ``But,'' Watlers said, ``it is perfectly obvious that
face-to-face talks must take place between the two parties who have
been at war.''
   On another subject, the U.S. ambassador called for participation
by ``some sort of Palestinian delegation'' in Arab-Israeli peace.
   But a State Department official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said Walters' remarks did not mean a change in U.S.
policy.
   The Reagan administration has called for Palestinian
participation, but not in a separate delegation. The plan forwarded
by Secretary of State George P. Shultz calls for Palestinians to
participate in a joint delegation with Jordan.
   Walters stressed that Jordan must take part in any negotiations
in view of its border with Israel.
   On Sunday, King Hussein announced he was severing legal and
administrative links to the West Bank and surrendering the areas'
future to the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   The territory, with a predominantly Palestinian Arab population,
was held by Jordan from 1948 until 1967 and by Israel since then.
</TEXT>
