<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Afghanistan-Bomb 1stLd-Writethru   08-04 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan-Bomb, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0569,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede MOSCOW</HEAD>
<HEAD>Truck Bomb Kills Four in Kabul</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE casualty toll, include
Shevardnadze visit. Pick up 5th graf, `The Soviet...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A truck filled with explosives blew
up today at a crowded bazaar in the Afghan capital of Kabul,
killing four people and injuring 18, Radio Kabul reported.
   The blast occurred shortly before Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
A. Shevardnadze arrived in Kabul for what was described a ``working
visit.''
   Afghanistan's Radio Kabul, monitored in Islamabad, blamed the
explosion on guerrillas fighting the Soviet-backed government.
   The Soviet news agency Tass, in a report from Kabul, said the
explosion occurred in the Shahrara area of the city. It blamed the
bomb on the ``irreconcilable opposition,'' or Afghan guerrillas.
   The blast occurred a day after Shevardnadze accused Pakistan of
``international terrorism'' for its support of the Afghan rebels.
   The Soviet Union accuses Pakistan of sending massive amounts of
arms to the rebels in violation of an April 14 agreement reached in
Geneva.
   As part of the agreement, the Soviet Union is withdrawing its
more than 100,000 soldiers from Afghanistan. The Soviets entered
Afghanistan in December 1979 to back the government in its war with
the guerrillas.
   Bombings and rocket attacks on Kabul have become increasingly
frequent as the Soviet soldiers withdraw and the Afghan government
forces take on the burden of the fighting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
