<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 1425EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PalmeProbe     08-04 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Palme Probe,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Premier Defends Government in Secret Palme Murder Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Ingvar Carlsson in
testimony Thursday defended the government's role in a secret and
partially illegal private investigation into the 1986 murder of his
predecessor, Olof Palme.
   Carlsson, speaking to a parliamentary inquiry into the
politically explosive affair, shifted responsibility for misconduct
in the investigation to national police chief Nils-Erik Ahmansson.
   But he said he supported the investigation in principle because
it was checking allegations that the security police had failed to
act on a tip received shortly before Palme was shot.
   Palme, prime minister for 13 years, was assassinated Feb. 28,
1986, while walking unguarded in downtown Stockholm. Official
investigations failed to produce a motive or lead to the
prosecution of any suspect, despite a reward of about $8 million.
   Carlsson's testimony ended a week of nationally televised
hearings in the affair, which has become a major issue for the
Sept. 18 general election. The Constitution Committee was to report
on the extent of the government's involvement and whether it broke
the law.
   Critics accused the ruling Social Democrats of exceeding their
authority and sidestepping official investigators. On June 7,
Justice Minister Anna-Greta Leijon was forced to quit because of
her role.
   The secret inquiry was conducted by Ebbe Carlsson, a publisher
linked to the inner circle of the Social Democratic party. He is
not related to the prime minister.
   Ahmansson was under pressure to resign after allegations that he
tacitly approved the use of outlawed surveillance devices. A former
policeman has been indicted for smuggling the equipment.
   The publisher testified earlier that he believed Palme was
killed by members of the Kurdish Workers Party, PKK, possibly
acting on orders from Iran, after Palme threatened to stop the sale
of Swedish weapons to Teheran.
   The Kurdish theory had been discarded by prosecutors in charge
of the case after a year-long investigation.
   Prime Minister Carlsson said the unconventional private
investigation was justified by the overriding importance of
uncovering clues in the 29-month-old murder.
   ``There were important allegations with serious accusations and
serious criticism against a Swedish authority. My reaction was that
this must immediately be checked out,'' he said.
   Carlsson said he was told of the investigation by Mrs. Leijon,
who only learned about it in about two months after it began in
January.
   In earlier testimony Thursday, Mrs. Leijon said she ``had been
under the impression'' that Ahmansson was in charge of Ebbe
Carlsson's search. Ahmansson has acknowledged Ebbe Carlsson acted
on his orders, but he has denied approving any wrongdoing.
   Mrs. Leijon's line of defense appeared aimed at clearing the
Social Democratic party from charges that it acceded to an illegal
operation.
   She quit after disclosures that she wrote a letter of
introduction for Ebbe Carlsson to British intelligence authorities.
Copies were kept secret in her private safe in defiance of required
procedure.
   In her letter written in May, Mrs. Leijon said Ebbe Carlsson was
working ``on my behalf.'' Replying to critics who said the letter
proved her responsibility, Mrs. Leijon said it was ``carelessly
worded'' and it was not meant to imply that she was in charge of
the investigation by Carlsson's team.
   That prompted Center Party committee member Bertil Fiskesjo to
say that ``everybody seems eager to say that Ebbe Carlsson did not
act on assignment, sometimes I ask myself if he exists at all.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
