<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0583 08-04 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0583,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze Arrives in Afghan Capital</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 2nd graf to UPDATE report on explosion. Pick up 3rd, `It
blamed...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet foreign minister, Eduard A.
Shevardnadze, arrived in Afghanistan today on a previously
unannounced visit that followed a sharp meeting with a top
Pakistani official.
   Shevardnadze's arrival in the Afghan capital, Kabul, was
announced by the official Tass news agency in Moscow. Radio Kabul
reported that a truck loaded with explosives blew up in Kabul
shortly before his arrival, killing four people and injuring 18.
   It blamed the explosion on guerrillas fighting Afghanistan's
Soviet-backed government.
   Shevardnandze's visit came a day after he met with Pakistan's
foreign minister, Yaqub Khan, in Moscow. During that meeting,
Shevardnadze accused Pakistan of ``international terrorism'' for
its support of the Afghan guerrillas.
   Tass said in a two-sentence report that Shevardnadze was met at
the Kabul airport by Afghan Foreign Minister Abdul Wakil and other
officials.
   It said nothing about the nature of Shevardnadze's mission
except to say that it was a ``working visit.''
   The Soviet Union is withdrawing its more than 100,000 soldiers
from Afghanistan under terms of an April 14 agreement signed in
Geneva by the Soviet Union, Pakistan, Afghanistan and the United
States.
   The Soviet Union has been increasingly critical of what
Shevardnadze called Pakistan's ``unceasing massive dispatches'' of
arms to the insurgents, and Afghanistan has made scores of
complaints about what it says is Pakistani assistance to the rebels.
   Shevardnadze told Khan that Afghan rebels had recently stepped
up their bombardment of Afghan towns and that hundreds of innocent
people were killed or wounded in the past two months.
   ``Islamabad's support for such actions cannot be described other
than as international terrorism,'' he told the Pakistani official.
   He said the Soviet Union and Afghanistan would find ways to
counter Pakistan's alleged interference, but did not specify them.
   Soviet soldiers entered Afghanistan in December 1979 to back the
government in its war with guerrillas.
</TEXT>
