<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ethiopia-Rebels     08-04 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopia-Rebels,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Says Troops Have Taken Rebel Stronghold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethiopia said Thursday its forces
have captured a strategic rebel stronghold in the mountainous
northwestern Tigray province after ``fierce engagements.''
   ``The area was a strong fortress of the bandits who had also
consolidated their positions in strategic positions in the
surrounding areas,'' the state-owned Ethiopian News Agency reported.
   The term ``bandit'' is used by the government to describe rebels
of the Tigray People's Liberation Front and the seccessionist
Eritrean People's Liberation Front, also fighting the government in
Ethiopia's northermost province of Eritrea.
   Thhe agency did not say when or where the battle took place or
mention casualties on either side.
   The agency said 500 technicians from 91 public and private
organizations were being sent to Tigray and Eritrea where troops
are engaged in ``in a bitter struggle against the bandits to defend
the unity and territorial integrity of the country.''
   Hailu Yimenu, deputy prime minister and chairman of the
government's War Logistics Committee, told the technicians
maintenance of vehicles and other equipment was decisive in
defeating the rebels.
   Rebels of both groups early this year won major battles,
capturing several towns. The government launched a counteroffensive
in May and two months later reported it had recaptured most of the
towns.
   There is no way to independently confirm rebel or government
claims about the war which has been going on for 14 years in Tigray
and 27 in Eritrea, Africa's longest civil war.
</TEXT>
