<1ST_LINE>u a PM-PilotCheating 1stLd-Writethru a0635 08-04 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pilot Cheating, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0635,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Six Indicted In Pilot License-Cheating Scheme</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 8-9 pvs, `The indictment ...' with four grafs to
UPDATE with one pilot relieved of duty by Delta.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Federal Aviation Administration inspector and
five others, including Air Force officers, were indicted today on
charges they helped military pilots cheat on exams to gain
commercial licenses.
   The ringleaders, reserve Air Force Maj. Charles Chinn, an FAA
safety inspector, and squadron commander Lt. Col. Edward King,
helped 15 to 20 F-16 fighter pilots who took the test at Homestead
Air Force Base, then tried to cover up the cheating during an
investigation, said interim U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen.
   The cheating ``did serious damage to the safety of commercial
aviation,'' Lehtinen said. But he added that few, if any, of the
pilots are working for commercial airlines.
   Most the pilots who took the exam cooperated with investigators
when contacted, Lehtinen said.
   The prosecutor said that no money changed hands but that Chinn
and King apparently hoped to enhance their future careers in
commercial aviation following their retirements from public service.
   He said there were no indications the scandal went beyond Chinn
and Homestead.
   The six men were expected to turn themselves in today.
   Delta Air Lines in Atlanta said that one of the men indicted on
charges of cheating on the tests, reserve Capt. Michael Weininger,
a flight engineer on Boeing 727s for the carrier since June 1987,
was relieved of duty today.
   However, Delta spokeswoman Jackie Pate emphasized that Weiningen
had passed a ``rigorous'' Delta training course before flying, and
she added, ``Anybody who didn't know what they were doing would
have been uncovered.''
   The indictment charged that in 1986 and 1987, Chinn and King
supplied test-takers with answers or let other people sit in for
them.
   Others charged were former Air Force officers John Phelps, Paul
Seiler and Kenneth Turano.
   Seiler, Weininger and Turano were accused of cheating on tests
for pilot and flight engineer. Phelps was charged with having
another take the tests for him.
   All six are charged with conspiracy to defraud the United States
in obtaining FAA licenses. Also, all but Turano are charged with
conspiracy to obstruct the subsequent FAA probe. Each count carries
a five-year maximum penalty.
</TEXT>
