<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 1441EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-LandProtest     08-04 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Land Protest,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peasants Reach Agreement on Expropriated Land, End Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peasants demanding
payment for their expropriated land ended a three-day protest that
left one man dead after the government agreed to relocate them and
give them half the money they were owed.
   President Joaquin Balaguer met with representatives of the
farmers Wednesday night in the National Palace and agreed to pay
them $285,000 of the approximately $570,000 they have coming.
   The rest of the money will be paid next month, said an accord
signed by representatives of the government, the peasants and the
Roman Catholic Church, which has served as a mediator.
   The government has bought land near the town of Cotui, 80 miles
north of the capital Santo Domingo, to make way for a partially
built dam. Most of the land will be flooded when the project is
finished.
   Balaguer also agreed to try to speed up the relocation of the
124 families forced from their homes by the dam.
   One man died and several people were injured in demonstrations
this week in which protesters detonated homemade bombs and blocked
roads with tree trunks. Dozens were rounded up by police, and many
were reportedly beaten and jailed.
   In February, five people died during a week-long protest by
peasants in the same region demanding payment for their lands and
protesting the contamination of water from byproducts of the
state-owned Rosario gold mine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
