<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Jordan Bjt   08-04 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jordan, Bjt,0652</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jordan Lays Off, Retires Thousands on West Bank</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jordan said Thursday it will lay off or
retire the 21,200 Palestinian employees at its institutions in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, which effectively turns
over responsibility to the PLO.
   The decision, announced after a Cabinet meeting, was the most
sweeping in practical effect since King Hussein announced Sunday he
was cutting links with the territories, where 1.5 Palestinians live.
   Jordan has paid at least $45 million a year in salaries to its
employees in the West Bank and Gaza. Including expenditures for
hospitals, Islamic institutions, agriculture and education, its
annual outlay has been estimated at $200 million.
   Those working for courts and the authority that controls mosques
and other religious institution are exempt, the announcement said.
   Reaction among Palestinians was mixed.
   ``I don't think it is fair,'' said Jamila Azmi, 55, who has
received a Jordanian salary during 30 years in Bethlehem's school
system. ``Who is going to take care of the fired employees?''
   She said some of those laid off would have to take jobs in
Israel, which leaders of the 8-month-old uprising in the occupied
lands have discouraged.
   Hanna Siniora, a newspaper editor who supports the Palestine
Liberation Organization, praised the move and said: ``Those who
will be hurt can be compensated by the Palestinian side. I assume
that the political vacuum left by Jordan will be filled by the
PLO.''
   Rashad al Shawaa, the deposed mayor of Gaza City and a supporter
of Hussein, said the king's action ``puts the whole responsibility
on the PLO. If the PLO can shoulder it, very good. If not, then the
PLO must go back to Jordan and tell the king: `We need your
cooperation and help.'''
   A senior Jordanian official said privately the government also
is expected to abolish martial law in the West Bank, nominally in
force since the 1967 Middle East war. He said this would ``give the
PLO greater responsibility over West Bank affairs.''
   An end to Jordanian martial law would have comparatively little
effect, since Israel captured the West Bank in the war, but one
result apparently would be dissolution of the 13-member ministerial
committee that supervises Jordan River bridge crossings.
   What impact that would have on movement across the Allenby
bridge, the only open border crossing between Israeli-occupied
territory and hostile Arab states, was not clear immediately .
   The committee also had barred West Bank Palestinians from
dealing with Israel or selling their land to Israeli authorities.
   Jordan radio said the decision to lay off or retire the civil
servants ``is in accordance with the kingdom's decision to cut
legal and administrative links with Palestinians in the occupied
lands. All Jordanian citizens working for official and government
agencies will be retired as of Aug. 16.''
   It said civil servants with less than 15 years of service will
be dismissed with a month's salary for every year of service. A
Jordanian official said 16,000 fell into that category and the PLO
would be responsible for their jobs or welfare.
   Those with more than 15 years and less than 20 will continue
receiving salaries until they retire on pensions at 20 years, the
report said. The official, also speaking on condition of anonymity,
said 5,200 were were in that group.
   Hussein's latest decision also ends the services of an
unspecified number of workers at private institutions and companies
linked to the government, who will receive severance pay according
to their employers' rules, the radio said.
   On Saturday, the king dissolved the lower house of the Jordanian
parliament, 30 of whose 60 members were Palestinians from the West
Bank. He also has canceled a $1.3 billion development program for
education and economic projects in the West Bank.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
