<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Greece     08-04 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Greece,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US to Press Talks for Greece Air Base Despite Closure Threat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States intends to press
negotiations for a new lease for a major air base in Greece,
despite a warning from Athens that the base will be closed, a
senior State Department official said Thursday.
   Assistant Secretary of State Rozanne L. Ridgway told a House
hearing she was surprised by the Greek statement Wednesday that the
Hellenikon base would be shut down. The base is used to monitor
Soviet ship movements in the Mediterranean.
   ``In our view, the subject is still on the table and is not
affected by this announcement,'' she told the House Foreign Affairs
subcommittee on Europe and the Middle East.
   The most recent round of talks which began in November 1987
regarding the future of four major U.S. air bases in Greece failed
to resolve the question of Hellenikon, she said.
   The ninth round of negotiations on new base leases is scheduled
for Sept. 9. The current five-year agreement expires on Dec. 31.
   Ms. Ridgway said the Greek announcement may have been intended
for internal consumption, or made by someone intent on accelerating
the slow-moving negotiations.
   Premier Andreas Papandreou is a Socialist who came to power in
1981 vowing to close American bases on Greek soil. He has since
relented but is under constant pressure from leftist groups to win
U.S. political and economic concessions in exchange for lease
renewals.
   Hellenikon, with its high-profile location near the Athens
airport, has been the site of anti-American demonstrations.
   At the hearing, Ms. Ridgway defended the Reagan administration's
decision to sell Greece 500 shoulder-fired anti-aircraft Stinger
missiles. She said Greece was a vital member of NATO and a loyal
U.S. ally.
   Rep. Donald E. Lukens, R-Ohio, said he was angered by
Papandreou's anti-American positions.
   ``I am fed up with the behavior of this man who can't even
fulfill his obligations to his wife, never mind to NATO,'' Lukens
said. The Greek premier is reported to have had marital problems
with his American-born wife.
   Rep. Lawrence Smith, D-Fla., criticized the Stinger sales in
light of several recent terrorist attacks in Greece, including the
slaying of a U.S. military attache and a bloody assault on a cruise
liner.
   Smith noted that the Stingers are coveted by guerrilla groups
because they are portable and easy to use. Ms. Ridgway said the
State Department did not have any evidence that U.S. military
equipment provided to Greece had fallen into terrorists' hands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
