<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Prices     08-04 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Prices,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Lifts Price Restraints, Sure to Fuel Inflation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Thursday lifted
price controls for many goods and services, including energy and
transport, in a measure likely to fuel inflation and social
tensions.
   The widespread lifting of price controls at a time when
inflation is hovering around 180 percent applies to those on
gasoline, diesel fuel, electricity, cooking gas, coal, rail
transport and postal services.
   These prices, strictly controlled by the state for most of the
post World War II period, will be formed freely by their producers,
the state-run press reported.
   Manufacturers of cooking oil, flour and bread also were allowed
price increases, but the staples still will be under government
control, the reports said.
   The government measure has already hit Yugoslavs with a 39
percent increase in the price of electricity, an average 55 percent
rise in the cost of rail transport and a 66 percent rise in the
price of cooking oil.
   Other producers, including those of fuel and bread, have yet to
announce their new prices.
   Workers have staged several protest marches following the
introduction in May of a government program which allowed
substantial price increases and hefty wage cuts.
   The May measures lifted price controls for about 60 percent of
goods and services, which have been frozen since November.
   The steps are designed to curb the country's inflation and repay
the $21 billion foreign debt by introducing a more market-oriented
economy.
   The government, together with the International Monetary Fund
which has helped in designing the program, have set a target that
Yugoslav inflation should drop to 95 percent by the end of 1988.
   The latest official evaluations, however, show that due to the
wave of price increases, prospects are dim that the target will be
reached. According to the most optimistic estimates, Yugoslavia's
annual inflation rate will be at least 130 percent by the end of
1988.
   The unpopular government measures are likely to contribute to a
further decline in living standards, which have already fallen by
at least one third since 1980. Labor unrest is also expected to
grow.
   Anticipating the price increases, most Yugoslavs have been on a
shopping spree in recent weeks for cooking oil and sugar, causing
shortages of those products.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880804-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 1511EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Seals     08-04 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Seals,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Experts Pinpoint Virus Behind Club Seal Epidemic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swedish and Dutch scientists have
pinpointed the virus behind the sudden death of thousands of North
Sea club seals, an expert said Thursday.
   ``We can now absolutely dismiss the theories about a herpes
virus,'' the Swedish news agency TT quoted virologist Berndt
Klingeborn as saying.
   Klingborn, of the Biomedical Center in the city of Uppsala, said
the virus belonged to a group known as the Picornaviridae. He said
it was only a matter of weeks before scientists develop a vaccine.
   At least 6,700 seals have been killed in northern European
waters in an epidemic that was first detected in Denmark in
mid-April. Dead seals have been found on Swedish, Danish,
Norwegian, West German and Dutch coasts.
   Klingeborn said scientists worked for months to isolate the
virus believed to undermine the seals' disease-fighting immune
system, leading to fatal pneumonia or liver infection.
   Scientists here and in other northern European countries have
discussed a possible link between the deaths and pollution of the
Baltic and North seas.
   Klingeborn said the seals may have congregated in the few areas
where the water remained clean and food was plentiful, ``and in
that way have been exposed to a greater risk of infection.''
   He said different animals could be victims to different strains
of pircorna viruses, which explained why gray seals were not
affected by the epidemic.
</TEXT>
