<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PressCredentials     08-04 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Press Credentials,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Who Gets to Ask White House Questions?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The question about Michael Dukakis' health
that led to President Reagan's flip retort on Wednesday led to
queries on Thursday about just who may attend and ask questions at
White House briefings.
   ``Everyone who wants a credential gets one,'' said White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   ``If you've got a news outlet that reaches the public, it
defines you as eligible for a White House press pass. I'm certainly
not aware of anyone we don't let in,'' he said.
   Reagan touched off a political flap Wednesday when asked whether
he felt Dukakis, the Democratic presidential nominee, should
release his medical records. The questioner, Nicholas Benton of the
Executive Intelligence Review, a publication founded by political
extremist Lyndon LaRouche, also referred to Dukakis' mental health.
   ``Look, I'm not going to pick on an invalid,'' the president
said. A short time later, he said he had just been kidding and
shouldn't have said what he did.
   Fitzwater was asked at Thursday's news briefing whether the
``invalid'' remark was inadvertent or calculated and whether the
White House took a hand in spreading rumors that Dukakis had
psychiatric problems in the past. The spokesman refused to comment
on all questions relating to Reagan's remark.
   Both Dukakis and his doctor denied the candidate had ever
received psychiatric counseling.
   Fitzwater said Thursday the White House does not make value
judgments in deciding whether Benton _ or some 2,000 other
journalists _ are entitled to press passes.
   Those assigned to cover the White House on a regular basis who
work for ``a recognized news organization'' are accredited,
according to White House rules.
   Fitzwater said courts have held it is a violation of free-press
rights protected by the First Amendment to the Constitution to deny
White House credentials based on a reporter's affiliation.
   But sometimes the lines between advocacy and reporting are
blurry.
   In 1977, the Standing Committee of Correspondents, which helps
administer the congressional press galleries, reprimanded the Rev.
Lester Kinsolving and stripped him of his Capitol Hill press
credentials for accepting money from a foreign government.
   The State Department Correspondents Association revoked
Kinsolving's membership in that organization, an action that did
not prevent Kinsolving from attending department news briefings.
   Kinsolving, an Episcopal priest and syndicated columnist,
acknowledged accepting $2,500 in stock and expenses from a law firm
representing South Africa.
   Kinsolving was reinstated by the congressional press galleries
after he quit working for the South Africans.
   Some reporters protested that Kinsolving was the victim of a
double standard. They noted that, for example, representatives of
the Soviet government news agency Tass were accepted by the
correspondents' groups.
   The White House Correspondents Association does not have any
authority to determine who attends presidential news conferences or
who gets White House press credentials. Kinsolving has been a
frequent questioner at White House briefings.
   From time to time, association members have discussed a policy
that would treat reporters who cover the White House regularly
differently from those who are occasional visitors. But the idea is
to guarantee access to newsworthy events that attract a crowd _ not
bar anyone for their political beliefs.
   The problem of access prompted one reporter Thursday to demand
from Fitzwater an explanation of why a representative of a LaRouche
publication can attend presidential news briefings while reporters
from mid-size out-of-town newspapers have trouble getting through
the White House gate.
   Fizwater promised to look into it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
