<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hamadi     08-04 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hamadi,0676</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Address Book Found On Hamadi Led to French Arrests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The arrest of a TWA hijack
suspect in West Germany led French police to a group of suspected
Middle East terrorists allegedly involved in the 1986 bombings in
Paris, a police official testified Thursday.
   The testimony came during the trial of Mohammed Ali Hamadi, a
Lebanese Shiite Moslem who is charged with air piracy and murder in
the June 1985 TWA hijacking.
   The hijackers shot and killed U.S. Navy diver Robert Stethem,
and 39 Americans were held hostage for 17 days after TWA Flight 847
from Athens to Rome was diverted to Beirut.
   Harald Braun, an inspector with the West German federal police,
told the court, ``A telephone number found in Hamadi's address book
led French police to arrest the suspected leader of a terrorist
group.''
   Hamadi was arrested at Frankfurt airport on Jan. 13, 1987, after
customs officials discovered liquid explosives in his luggage.
   Braun said the Paris telephone number found in Hamadi's book
next to the name of ``Ali the Tunisian'' belonged to a man
identified as Fouad Ali Salah.
   Salah was arrested in March 1987 by French police and is
suspected of being the leader of a Hezbollah terrorist cell that
allegedly carried out 10 bomb attacks in Paris in the fall of 1986.
The bombings killed 10 people and injured 270 others.
   Salah and 10 other suspected Hezbollah members are still in
French custody, Braun told the court.
   Hezbollah is a radical Iranian-backed Shiite Moslem group in
Lebanon that is suspected of holding Western hostages. One of
Mohammed Hamadi's brothers, Abdul-Hadi, is Hezbollah's security
chief in Beirut.
   Another Hamadi brother, Abbas, was convicted by a West German
court in Apil of masterminding the kidnapping of two West Germans
in Beirut in an attempt to force the West German government to free
Mohammed. Abbas Hamadi was sentenced to 13 years in prison.
   One West German, Alfred Schmidt, was released in September, but
the second, Rudolf Cordes, remains a hostage.
   During his trial that began in July, Mohammed Hamadi has denied
being a member of Hezbollah. He has also testified that some of the
numbers found in his telephone book had been written by a man in
Beirut at whose home he had left the book for several days.
   Braun also told the court that French police seized seven
bottles of liquid explosives when they arrested Salah.
   ``The explosives were of exactly the same type found in Hamadi's
luggage,'' Braun said.
   After Hamadi's arrest in Frankfurt, more of the same explosives
where found buried in the West German state of Saarland, near the
French border. Hamadi has admitted to smuggling the explosives into
West Germany in January 1987.
   Braun testified that French police also found the telephone
number of Hezbollah headquarters in Beirut when they arrested Salah.
   Earlier Thursday, another witness testified that Hamadi sought
to trade freedom from prison for the two West German hostages in
Lebanon.
   Gabriel Lapite said Hamadi gave him the telephone number of a
sister in Beirut with the request: ``Tell her that my brother
should start to go to work. Both Germans should not be freed unless
I am released.''
   Lapite, a Nigerian who was imprisoned on drug charges in a cell
near Hamadi's for three months in 1987, did not say which of
Hamadi's brothers was to be contacted. He also did not say if he
placed the phone call, and Chief Judge Heiner Mueckenberger did not
ask him.
   Lapite testified that Mohammed Hamadi gave him five letters to
mail to family members and friends. Lapite said he did not mail the
letters and gave them to police.
   Reiner Hamm, a lawyer representing hijack victims and their
families in the trial, said the letters tried to arrange Hamadi's
release from prison.
   The trial will take a four-week recess after a hearing on
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
