<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Foam-Ozone     08-04 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Foam-Ozone,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Foam-Making Process Doesn't Use Ozone-Destroying Chemicals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union Carbide Corp. said Thursday it has found a
way to avoid using ozone-destroying chemicals in making foam used
for furniture padding.
   The technology could eliminate 70 percent of the use of
ozone-destroying chlorofluorocarbons in the flexible foam industry,
which now accounts for 12 percent to 15 percent of the world's
chlorofluorocarbon use, said John Televantos of the company.
   Carbide immediately will start selling the ingredients to make
the new polyurethane foam, company representatives said at a news
conference.
   Chlorofluorocarbons eat away at the atmosphere's ozone layer,
which blocks out harmful solar rays. Scientists say further
thinning of the ozone layer could increase skin cancers.
   Last September, two dozen nations signed a treaty to reduce the
use of CFCs.
   Foam manufacturers use CFCs to make foam softer. They can also
use methylene chloride, but that may also be phased out by federal
regulators because it is suspected of causing cancer, Carbide
officials said.
   Officials declined to give details of the new technology, citing
patent considerations. The new foam, called Ultracel, also provides
improved comfort, support and durability, officials said.
   The foam is not a practical substitute for providing bulk, as in
the armrest of a chair, or for some packaging, said Televantos.
</TEXT>
