<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 1433EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-SocialSecurity Bjt   08-04 0852</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Social Security, Bjt,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Workers Offered New Way to Check Retirement Benefits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Social Security Administration said
Thursday it can provide free, detailed individual financial
statements to workers estimating how large a benefit check they
will get each month when they retire.
   The new ``Personal Earnings and Benefit Estimate Statement''
will also disclose how much a worker and family would get each
month in disability or survivors' benefits.
   The computer-generated disclosure statements will be available
by mail free on written request from anyone who has paid Social
Security taxes, is under 65 years old and is not yet drawing
benefits.
   The statements fulfill a promise that President Reagan made in
his last State of the Union address, and caps a two-year drive by
Social Security Commissioner Dorcas R. Hardy to give the public a
better idea of their personal stake in the huge retirement,
disability and survivors' program.
   Those interested can call a toll-free number _ 1-800-937-2000 _
to request copies of the disclosure form, SSA-7004.
   All they have to do is fill it out, put a stamp on it and the
agency will send back their statement in two to three weeks, Hardy
said at a news conference.
   Social Security pays out more than $200 billion a year in cash
benefits to 38 million retirees, disabled workers and their
families, but ``it is probably the most misunderstood program in
the entire federal government,'' Hardy said.
   She said many people do not understand the survivors' and
disability protection, and others confuse it with ``a private
savings or checkings account.''
   ``By putting a precise dollars and cents value on those
benefits, and individualizing it for the person making the request,
Social Security will no longer seem so mysterious and complex,''
she said.
   Some private companies charge people for making the kind of
estimates that Social Security now will be doing free.
   Hardy said it ``will serve as a viable financial planning tool
and I urge everyone to take advantage of this new, improved
service.''
   Social Security's old earnings statement form has been widely
criticized as hard to read, confusing and skimpy on useful
information. The agency generally provided estimates of benefits at
age 65 only for those 60 or older.
   For younger workers, Hardy said, benefit estimations were
``extremely difficult. We could not have supplied this by mail. We
could do it by hand-calculation if you insisted in a district
office ... but we really were not in the business of providing that
kind of service at all.''
   The new form asks people to list their name, nine-digit Social
Security number, date of birth, actual earnings from last year and
estimated earnings this year, as well as the age at which they plan
to retire.
   The form also asks for a single estimate of future average
yearly earnings, but advises that ``most people should enter the
same amount as this year's estimated earnings.''
   The agency then will mail back a computer-generated booklet
spelling out how much in Social Security-covered wages the person
earned each year since 1951, and estimating how much he or she paid
in payroll taxes. It will give a lump sum for 1937-1950.
   The booklet will tell how many credits a person has earned
toward Social Security coverage. A worker now gets one credit for
each $470 of wages, up to a maximum of four credits a year, and
needs 20 credits to be insured for disability and 40 credits for
retirement benefits.
   Then it will give estimates in today's dollars of how much the
person would get if he or she retires at 62, 65 or 70. For younger
workers, who will be expected to work until 66 or 67 to draw full
retirement benefits, that age is used instead of 65.
   Estimates also are given for payments to widows or widowers and
children under 18 on death or disability.
   The old earnings statement provided only a fraction of this
information. It broke out individual earnings only for the four
most recent years and did not list how much tax was paid.
   Hardy expressed hope that the financial notices would remind
people to plan early for their retirement _ and that Social
Security was never intended as a complete source of retirement
income.
   She said $300,000 in new computer software was required for the
service, and the agency now expects to get 6 million requests a
year for earnings statements, double the 3 million it has been
handling. It will cost 37 cents to fulfill each request, up from 33
cents previously.
   The Social Security Administration expects the program to help
it detect errors in its earnings records. About three percent of
the 1,600 people in a pilot test found mistakes on their earnings
statements.
   Those who detect errors must provide documentation of their
actual earnings to ensure their benefits are in the right amount,
Hardy said.
   Social Security has always encouraged people to check their
earnings record every three years. It says the law only allows it
to correct errors caught within about 40 months of their occurrence.
</TEXT>
