<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-BBC     08-04 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-BBC,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Acts Against Producer of BBC Film On Detainees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Briton who produced a BBC-TV
documentary alleging that detained black youths were maltreated
won't be allowed unrestricted access to South Africa, the
government said Thursday.
   The Home Affairs Department said Nicholas Claxton was no longer
entitled to the exemption that enables British citizens to visit
South Africa without a visa.
   Claxton, a free-lance producer, was commissioned by the British
Boradcasting Corp. to produce ``Suffer the Children,'' a
documentary shown in Britain in June that alleged young blacks had
been tortured and mistreated while in detention.
   Gerrie van Zyl, director-general of home affairs, said one of
the reasons for the punitive action was that government officials
had not been given a chance to view the documentary or comment on
it prior to its broadcast.
   Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok said ``Suffer the Children''
was a ``despicable propaganda film,'' which illustrated how ``lies,
distortions and exaggerations are being used agianst South Africa
to isolate it from the rest of the world.''
   Vlok said police have been investigating the allegations made in
the docuentary and have yet to find any evidence to support the
charges.
   Human rights activists say several thousand black youths have
been detained without charge for varying periods during the state
of emergency declared in June 1986.
   The government says no youths under 16 are in detention, but it
has not disclosed comprehensive figures.
   The Bureau for Information is distributing a booklet defending
the policy of detaining children, saying some of these youths had
committed atrocities.
</TEXT>
