<1ST_LINE>u w AM-AirbusCompensation Bjt   08-04 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airbus Compensation, Bjt,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan's Airbus Compensation Plan Faces Tough Hurdles, Legislators
Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's plan to pay humanitarian
compensation to the families of the 290 people killed in the U.S.
destruction of an Iranian jetliner last month faces serious hurdles
in Congress and may not be approved, House members said Thursday.
   ``I think you're going to have serious trouble selling what
you're trying to sell,'' said Rep. Ike Skelton, D-Mo., told State
and Defense department officials.
   Skelton said the Iranian government bears a heavy burden of
responsibility for dispatching the Iran Air Airbus into a Persian
Gulf combat zone where it was destroyed by missiles from the U.S.
cruiser Vincennes.
   Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services
Committee, told reporters that Congress might be persuaded to
appropriate funds for humanitarian compensation to the families if
it is established that mistakes by the Vincennes crew during combat
caused the downing of the plane.
   Pentagon sources said Wednesday that preliminary findings of an
official investigation show that human error rather than
malfunctioning equipment caused the Vincennes to fire on the
jetliner July 3.
   Aspin told State and Defense department witnesses at the hearing
that they face ``a tough sell'' in obtaining compensation funds
from Congress because ``the visceral reaction against the Iranian
government runs very deep.''
   Aspin said the chances for approval of compensation would be a
lot higher if there is an end to the eight-year Iran-Iraq war and
to attacks on international shipping in the gulf.
   Several committee members said they would oppose paying
compensation unless there were ``absolute guarantees'' that the
money would go only to victims' families and not benefit the
Iranian government in any way.
   ``While we want to be humanitarian, we don't want to be naive,''
said Rep. Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo.
   Aspin added: ``Unless there are absolute guarantees there are
going to be absolute problems.''
   Abraham Sofaer, the State Department's legal adviser, said the
offer to pay compensation flows from a traditional American spirit
of compassion and humanity.
   He said all nations except the Soviet Union have paid
compensation after the destruction of a civilian aircraft because
``civilized nations pay these kind of obligations.''
   Safaer said he believes it would be ``inappropriate'' to link
humanitarian payments to other issues, such as the release of
hostages held by Iranian-backed radicals in Lebanon.
   ``This is not a nation-to-nation deal,'' Sofaer said. ``This is
a nation-to-people deal.''
   He said the United States will make every effort to ensure that
Tehran government does not benefit from the payments.
   ``We are going to pay this money to people or we're not going to
pay it,'' Sofaer said.
   He said, however, that cooperation from Iranian authorities
probably will be essential if the victims' families are to be
identified accurately and appropiate payment made.
   He said that if there were no cooperation and survivors proved
impossible to identify with certainty, that likely would end the
matter.
   Even with the administration's best efforts, Sofaer testified,
``we will need a considerable amount of time to determine how to
assess compensation and to obtain the information necessary from
the families or their governments.''
</TEXT>
