<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CattleGraves     08-04 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cattle Graves,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Homeowners Upset By Property Sinkage Into Cow Graves</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of one neighborhood are
suffering a phenomenon they called ``Cow-geist,'' after the movie
``Poltergeist.'' But their problem isn't ghosts, it's houses
sinking into mass cattle graves.
   ``I just think it's weird,'' said homeowner Ken Zion. ``It makes
me upset. I'm upset I bought a house that might be sinking into cow
trenches.''
   The problem stems form an outbreak of hoof and mouth disease in
the 1920s that wiped out nearly all of the dairy cattle in Long
Beach, said Llewellyn Bixby, chairman of the Bixby Land Co.
   The dead cows were bulldozed into mass graves.
   Some of the burial trenches may be as deep as 18 feet, said
Zion, who said he received a settlement of several thousand dollars
from the previous owner of his house after a corner of his garage
started sinking six years ago.
   Eventually, houses were built over the bovine burial site, as
houses were built over a cemetery in ``Poltergeist.'' As the
carcasses decomposed, the ground settled, real estate agents said.
   One agent said nine lots have suffered subsidence, and one
homeowner estimated that as many as 20 homes may be at risk.
   Land subsidence in Long Beach, which was known in the 1950s as
``the sinking city,'' is not unusual.
   The problem then, however, was caused by oil wells pumping up
crude oil from the western part of the city. Water was eventually
injected into the ground to counter the effect.
   Kay Coop, an agent for JTM Brokerage Corp., said one of her
clients bought in the area without being told of the adverse
effects from the cow cemetery.
   ``It should have been declared,'' said Ms. Coop. ``Who would
ever think to look for dead cows?''
   City Planning Director Robert Paternoster said no one had told
him of of the problem. Senior Deputy City Attorney Arthur Honda
said he also hadn't heard of the problem, but said the city would
not be liable for such an occurrence.
</TEXT>
