<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Angola     08-04 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola,0645</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`On-Track' Angola Talks Extended</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA WATSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S.-mediated negotiations among Angola, Cuba and
South Africa on a peace settlement in southern Africa are ``on
track,'' a U.S. spokesman said Thursday, and the four countries
agreed to extend the talks.
   The negotiators agreed to end the meeting Friday, one day beyond
the originally scheduled closing date, sources close to the talks
said.
   Art Skop, the mission spokesman, said ``the negotiations are on
track and the full agenda of issues is under discussion.'' He
declined to elaborate.
   Assistant Secretary of State Chester Crocker, who mediates the
talks, planned to give a news conference Friday.
   Skop's statement suggested that a controversy which arose
earlier in the week over South African peace proposals had not
derailed the negotiations.
   The proposals were unexpectedly unveiled Tuesday night in
Pretoria by Foreign Minister Pik Botha. They called for a
cease-fire by Aug. 10 in the 13-year-old Angolan war and made
independence for South-West Africa conditional on the withdrawal of
Cuban troops from Angola by next June 1.
   South-West Africa also is known as Namibia.
   The Cuban and Angolan delegations in Geneva rejected the
proposals, with Cuba calling ``preposterous and unrealistic.'' The
two countries have said such a condition amounts to interference in
their affairs.
   Cuba previously offered to pull its estimated 50,000 troops out
of Angola over a four-year period. The troops have helped the
Marxist government fight UNITA, the rebel movement of Jonas
Savimbi, which receives military aid from South Africa and the
United States.
   In South Africa, Botha said Wednesday night that
counterproposals were being discussed in Geneva, but he did not
elaborate.
   South Africa's public announcement of its proposals irritated
Crocker because the negotiating partners had earlier agreed to keep
the talks confidential, according to U.S. sources.
   The southern Africa talks began in May in London and are in
their fifth round. The current round began on an upbeat note after
a previous round July 20 in New York produced for the first time a
joint document in which Cuba, Angola and South Africa accepted a
set of 14 principles as a framework for a settlement.
   On Tuesday, South Africa also proposed to start withdrawing its
estimated 50,000 troops from Namibia on Nov. 1.
   South Africa's mandate over Namibia was terminated by the United
Nations in 1966, but in defiance of several U.N. Security Council
resolutions, it has retained control of the mineral-wealthy country.
   On Thursday in Luanda, Angola, Sam Nujoma, leader of the South
West African People's Organization, or SWAPO, the main guerrilla
group fighting for Namibian independence, charged that South Africa
had reinforced its troops in Namibia recently. He said this raised
questions about the sincerity of the government's offer to withdraw.
   South Africa also called for the dismantling of seven guerrilla
camps which it said were operated in Angola by the African National
Congress, the main black group fighting white rule in South Africa.
   The New York principles did not mention the ANC's role, nor
those of UNITA or SWAPO, which is reported to have bases in Angola.
   In Pretoria, President P.W. Botha met on Thursday with leaders
of Namibia's multiracial interim government and gave assurances
that they would be consulted about developments in the
negotiations. Botha stressed that no agreement on independence for
the territory had been reached.
   Dirk Mudge, a moderate white Cabinet minister who headed the
Namibian delegation, said after the meeting he hoped the
international community would extend support to Namibia if
independence was obtained.
   However, the conservative National Party of South-West Africa _
the territory's largest white party _ reaffirmed its opposition to
any settlement providing for one-man, one-vote elections.
   Only about 70,000 of Namibia's 1.3 million people are white.
</TEXT>
