<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon-US     08-04 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-US,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Envoy Hopes For Smooth Presidential Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assistant Secretary of State Richard
Murphy met with government leaders Thursday in a visit designed to
help ensure smooth presidential elections in a nation torn by years
of civil war.
   There was speculation that Murphy's visit, which was not
announced in advance, might be tied to talks on the nine American
hostages held in Lebanon. But Murphy did not meet with any
officials thought to have direct influence over the fate of the
captives.
   ``The new president will face many challenges,'' Murphy said
after a three-hour meeting with President Amin Gemayel, a Maronite
Catholic.
   ``He will have to achieve constitutional reforms and consolidate
national entente ... The new president must be a symbol and an
advocate of national unity and reconciliation.''
   The new president is to be elected by Lebanon's Parliament.
Gemayel's term expires Sept. 23, and the vote must take place at
least a week before he leaves office.
   Murphy left Beirut for Damascus, Syria, for talks with Foreign
Minister Farouk al-Sharaa.
   The United States and Syria, the main power-broker in Lebanon,
have been trying to bring Lebanon's Moslems and Christians to agree
on political reforms to end a 13 year-old civil war. The war has
killed 130,000 people and wrecked the nation's once-booming economy.
   In south Beirut, a Syrian-backed guerrilla force patrolled
Beirut's two war-devastated refugee camps with orders to prevent
PLO leader Yasser Arafat's loyalists from filtering back.
   The force, made up of 280 men, set up 10 positions inside the
sprawling Bourj el-Barajneh camp on Beirut's southern edge and
seven posts at the nearby Chatilla shantytown.
   The ``Joint Security Force'' comprises three Syrian-supported
Palestinian factions _ the breakaway Fatah-Uprising, the Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command and the
al-Saiqa.
   PLO dissidents of the Fatah-Uprising group evicted Arafat's
supporters from Chatilla and Bourj el-Barajneh after a battle in
June and July that left 127 people killed and 527 wounded.
   Arafat's Fatah supporters relocated in Palestinian refugee camps
in south Lebanon's port city of Sidon.
   In addition to Gemayel, Murphy met with Parliament Speaker
Hussein Husseini, a Shiite Moslem, and acting Prime Minister Selim
Hoss, a Sunni Moslem, in west Beirut.
   It was not known if Murphy raised the issue of the hostages at
the talks.
   Most of the 18 Westerners held hostage in Lebanon are believed
held in Beirut's southern slums by pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem
factions.
   The hostage held longest is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
</TEXT>
