<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHELPS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's no sauerkraut in Phelps' annual
sauerkraut festival this year, but the party's going on anyway so
there won't be a lot of sour pusses around town.
   This upstate New York village lost its once-thriving sauerkraut
industry, and its boast of being the ``Sauerkraut Capital of the
World,'' this spring when one of its two plants closed and the
other company moved its operation out of town.
   ``It's sad about the sauerkraut. But a festival is a festival
and this is the only one we've got to give everybody in the village
a little lift to get through the end of summer,'' said Fran Magill,
co-chairwoman of the 22nd annual Phelps Sauerkraut Festival.
   The festival began Thursday night and continues through the
weekend.
   Until March, Phelps had been producing the pungent, chopped-up
cabbage for 84 years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Your waiter takes your drink order and begins
reciting the day's specials and before he's through, your drink has
arrived.
   A clairvoyant bartender? A waiter faster than a speeding bullet?
No, try radio waves.
   Waiters at the Cafe Roma use a hand-held device equipped with an
electronic keyboard with numbered keys. By punching the appropriate
key, the order is sent via radio waves to computer printers in the
kitchen and bar.
   ``I think in this heat they really appreciate it because they
don't have to go into the kitchen as much,'' cafe co-owner Janet
Sossi Belcoure said. ``They can be more attentive to the
customers.''
   Belcoure, with her father, Hector Sossi, owns and operates the
restaurant, which she said is nearly a century old and is believed
to be the longest continually operating restaurant in Detroit.
   ``We wanted to computerize. As the industry's becoming more
competitive, we needed a system to keep better control over what's
coming and going out.''
   The hand-held units, produced by Remanco Systems Co. of Danvers,
Mass., stay with the waiter _ no floor space is needed.
   The waiters at Roma Cafe have been there an average of 10 years,
Belcoure said, but were ready to accept the new technology.
   ``We had a couple of rough weeks, you know, it's new,'' she
said. ``But waiters caught on quickly.''
</TEXT>
