<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     08-04 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes In Kabul Hours Before Shevardnadze Arrives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A truck bomb exploded and killed at
least three people in a crowded bazaar in Kabul on Thursday,
several hours before Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze
arrived in the Afghan capital.
   State-run Radio Kabul, monitored in Islamabad, said three
passersby and the driver of the truck died and that 18 people were
injured; but the Soviet news agency Tass reported in Moscow that
only three people died and nine were injured. Both blamed the
attack on Moslem insurgents.
   Shevardnadze's visit, which was not announced before Tass said
he had arrived in Kabul, came one day after he sharply criticized
his Pakistani counterpart, Yaqub Khan, during a meeting in Moscow.
   Shevardnadze accused Khan's nation of ``international
terrorism'' for its continued support of insurgents fighting the
Soviet-backed Afghan government. The alleged assistance is
occurring as the Soviet Union withdraws its troops.
   Tass said in a two-sentence report Thursday that Shevardnadze
was met at the Kabul airport by Foreign Minister Abdul Wakil and
other Afghan officials.
   The dispatch said without elaborating that Shevardnadze was on a
``working visit'' and that Khan had left Moscow to return to
Pakistan.
   The Soviet Union has been increasingly critical of what
Shevardnadze called Pakistan's ``unceasing massive dispatches'' of
arms to the guerrillas.
   The Afghanistan government also has made scores of complaints
about what it says is Pakistani assistance to the insurgents.
   Shevardnadze told Khan that Afghan guerrillas recently stepped
up their bombardment of Afghan towns and that hundreds of innocent
people were killed or wounded in the past two months.
   ``Islamabad's support for such actions cannot be described other
than as international terrorism,'' he told the Pakistani official.
   He said the Soviet Union and Afghanistan would find ways to
counter Pakistan's alleged interference, but did not specify them.
   The Soviet Union is withdrawing its force of more than 100,000
soldiers from Afghanistan under the terms of an April 14 agreement
signed in Geneva by the Soviet Union, Pakistan, Afghanistan and the
United States.
   Half the Soviet soldiers are to withdrawn by Aug. 15 with the
remainder out by Feb. 15. Soviet and Afghan officials say 35,000
already have left.
   At a regular news briefing Thursday, Soviet Foreign Ministry
spokesman Vadim Perfiliev said all four parties should abide by the
Geneva agreement.
   ``They have equal rights, and of course if one side would
continue violating the agreements, the Soviet Union can take
appropriate steps,'' he said. ``But I would like to emphasize that
the measures the Soviet Union might take would be aimed at further
implementation of the agreement. We believe that Geneva must work
and that the settlement in Afghanistan should continue.''
   Radio Kabul blamed Afghan guerrillas allied with the
Hezb-e-Islami Party for the truck bomb. Guerrilla leaders and field
commanders have denied planting explosives in residential areas of
Kabul or hitting them with rockets.
   Bombing and rocket attacks on Kabul have increased since the
Soviet troop withdrawl began. Soviet soldiers entered Afghanistan
in December 1979, replaced one pro-Soviet government with another
and remained to fight the insurgents. Soviet officials say more
than 13,000 of their soldiers died in the conflict.
</TEXT>
