<DOCNO> AP880804-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 1925EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Jordan     08-04 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Jordan,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Says Jordan's Actions in Territories Will Not Affect Israel's
Actions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Jordan Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto JRL2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said Thursday
that Israel will block the PLO from taking Jordan's place in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Jordan said it will lay off or retire the 21,200 Palestinian
employees of its institutions in the occupied territories, which
effectively turns over responsibility to the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   The action has the greatest practical effect of any taken since
King Hussein's announcement Sunday that he was cutting links with
the territories, where 1.5 million Palestinians live.
   Shamir said Jordan's decision would put ``pressure on the PLO
and the Palestinian Arabs'' but would not change Israeli policy.
   ``We are still commited to our international obligations. We
will negotiate about peace with Palestinians, but never with the
PLO,'' he told reporters.
   ``King Hussein wants to deliver these Palestinians into the
hands of the PLO terrorists to struggle against Israel for their
so-called liberation.''
   Right-wing Israelis said Shamir should take the opportunity
presented by Hussein to assert Israeli claims to the West Bank.
   ``Long live the king,'' Jewish settler Eliakim Haetzni said in
an interview, saluting with his right hand. ``What happens now
depends on our response. Israel must either turn this over to (PLO
leader Yasser) Arafat or annex it.''
   Israel captured the West Bank and Gaza Strip from Jordan and
Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Legislator Geula Cohen of the right-wing Tehiya Party met with
Shamir to press demands that Israel annex the West Bank to fill the
power void left by Jordan. Shamir rejected the proposal, although
his Likud bloc believes the area is an inextricable part of the
historic land of Israel.
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman said that, if Hussein was trying to
encourage negotiations between Israel and the PLO, ``he must
understand clearly that for this option there is no Israeli
partner.''
   Israel would ``object to the PLO taking Jordan's place and
paying salaries'' in the territories, he said.
</TEXT>
