<1ST_LINE>r w AM-KennedyCenterHonors     08-04 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kennedy Center Honors,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stevens, Burns, Loy Among Honorees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roger L. Stevens, founding chairman of the
Kennedy Center, was among five prominent Americans chosen Thursday
to receive this year's Kennedy Center Honors for lifetime
achievements in the performing arts.
   The other winners are choreographer Alvin Ailey, actor George
Burns, actress Myrna Loy and violinist Alexander Schneider.
   President Reagan will pay tribute to the medalists at a White
House ceremony on Dec. 4. That evening, they will be honored at a
gala performance at the Kennedy Center that will be taped for later
broadcast as a CBS television special.
   Stevens, 78, formally retired as the first Kennedy Center
chairman on July 1, and was succeeded by former Time Inc. executive
Ralph P. Davidson.
   A wealthy real estate speculator and theatrical producer,
Stevens was appointed chairman of the national cultural center in
1961 and masterminded the financing and construction of the Kennedy
Center, which opened in 1971.
   The center's board of trustees, who approved the 11th annual
Kennedy Center Honors list Thursday, also voted Stevens the title
of founding chairman.
</TEXT>
