<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Shuttle-Chronology     08-04 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-Chronology,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chronology of Postponements on Shuttle Flight</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Space Shuttle Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Following are key dates in the continued postponement of the
space shuttle flight:
   Jan. 28, 1986 _ Space shuttle Challenger blows up 73 seconds
after launch, killing crew of seven.
   May 15, 1986 _ Arnold Aldrich, manager of the shuttle system,
tells Congressional committee that target date for next launch, of
Discovery, is July 15, 1987.
   Oct. 3, 1986 _ NASA announces target date of Feb. 18, 1988, for
Discovery launch.
   Jan. 14, 1987 _ National Research Council reports NASA will not
have time to evaluate or incorporate safety changes if it attempts
to meet Feb. 18, 1988, launch target.
   April 21, 1987 _ NASA announces it cannot meet Feb. 18, 1988,
date, and slates additional tests. No new target announced.
   June 2, 1987 _ Rear Adm. Richard Truly says Discovery will be
launched June 2, 1988, if all tests go according to schedule.
   Nov. 23, 1987 _ National Research Council recommends additional
testing of solid-fuel engine, which might require postponing June
launch.
   Dec. 29, 1987 _ NASA announces that June launch date has been
postponed because of failure of booster rocket nozzle during a
test. NASA officials say launch date will be moved back six to 10
weeks.
   Jan. 11, 1988 _ NASA administrator James C. Fletcher says launch
will be between mid-July and mid-August 1988.
   Jan. 27, 1988 _ NASA sets Aug. 4 as launch date.
   April 26, 1988 _ Shuttle manager Arnold Aldrich says launch will
be pushed back at least until Aug. 14 because of unexpected delays
in assembling redesigned booster rockets.
   May 4, 1988 _ Fletcher says Aug. 25 is a possible launch date,
although it might be early September. NASA subsequently selects
Aug. 31.
   June 10, 1988 _ The external fuel tank is joined to the solid
rocket boosters, and astronaut Bob Crippen, deputy director of
shuttle operations, says ``we've got a shot'' at meeting the Aug.
31 target. Test firing of shuttle's liquid-fuel engines is set for
July 18.
   July 15, 1988 _ Discovery springs a small gas leak in one
steering engine, and NASA says there is a possibility of additional
delay in the launch, now set for Sept. 3.
   July 22, 1988 _ NASA announces two-day delay in test firing of
main engines, which had been planned for July 30.
   July 29, 1988 _ NASA postpones test firing again, setting date
of Aug. 4, after discovering leak in a hydrogen line during fueling.
   Aug. 1, 1988 _ Another hydrogen leak is detected, but NASA goes
ahead with the countdown rehearsal; no decision on whether to
postpone the test-firing will be made until Aug. 2.
   Aug. 4, 1988 _ The test firing is aborted when a computer
reports a valve problem and shuts down the engines seconds before
they were to ignite.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
