<DOCNO> AP880804-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 2027EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FedNomination     08-04 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fed Nomination,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Confirms Boston Banker as Federal Reserve Board Member</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Thursday confirmed the
nomination of Boston bank executive John P. LaWare as a member of
the Federal Reserve Board.
   The 90-3 vote approving LaWare's selection means that all seven
seats on the board will be held President Reagan's appointees,
which has concerned congressional Democrats.
   Earlier this year, Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., chairman of
the Banking Committee, hinted that he might try to delay LaWare's
confirmation hearings so the vacancy could be filled by the next
administration. His panel eventually approved LaWare's nomination.
   On Thursday, Proxmire echoed his party's worries.
   ``We hope and pray that Mr. LaWare and the other members of that
board will recognize the importance of showing their independence
of the fact that they were appointed by the same president,'' he
said.
   At the same time, Proxmire praised LaWare, 60, as ``very, very
well qualified.''
   Senators who opposed LaWare's confirmation were Democrats Kent
Conrad of North Dakota and Albert Gore Jr. and Jim Sasser of
Tennessee.
   Reserve board members are appointed to 14-year terms, and
LaWare's term will not expire until Jan. 31, 2002. The job pays
$82,500 annually.
   LaWare, a banker for 35 years, has been chairman and chief
executive officer of the Shawmut Corp., a bank holding company in
Boston, since 1980.
   He was given a $2.5 million compensation package earlier this
year as part of the merger agreement that created the Shawmut
National Corp., a Boston and Hartford, Conn., bank holding company.
   LaWare was named chairman of the company, and given a deal under
which the corporation will continue his annual salary of about
$500,000 until he is 65, even if he leaves the bank.
   In addition, the bank will give him enough to pay a 20 percent
penalty that Congress imposed on the portions of such arrangements
that are considered excessive.
   During confirmation hearings in July, Proxmire called the
arrangement ``an attempt to dodge the tax code.''
   LaWare responded that ``the tax is being paid, regardless,'' and
that the government is not losing money. ``I'm not sure it's a
dodge,'' he said.
   LaWare has agreed to sever all financial connections with the
bank before joining the Federal Reserve Board.
</TEXT>
