<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MedicalMission-Vietnam     08-04 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Medical Mission-Vietnam,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Private Medical Group Going To Vietnam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private delegation planning to arrange what
participants believe is the first postwar U.S. medical mission to
Vietnam is on its way to Hanoi.
   The group, headed by plastic surgeon Dr. William Magee, left
Norfolk, Va., on Wednesday and is scheduled to arrive Friday. Magee
heads Operation Smile, which has operated on 2,000 children in
several countries to correct facial deformities.
   Magee said before his departure that the private, nonsectarian
group hopes to meet with Vietnamese officials and discuss an
Operation Smile mission to the country.
   The group recently sent its first delegation to South America,
operating on 160 children of coffee plantation workers in six days
in Colombia, Magee said. Missions are planned later this year to
Kenya and Liberia.
   Several Vietnam veterans are expected to participate in the
Vietnam project, Magee said. He said the trip was being arranged by
U.S. officials who have been dealing with the Vietnamese over the
search for U.S. soldiers missing in action during the Vietnam War.
   Operation Smile has chapters in 10 U.S. cities, including
several high school clubs set up to get youths involved in private
efforts to help people of less-developed countries.
</TEXT>
