<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0720,0763</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Norwegian Tanker Attacked; Iran Denies Involvement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to recast lede and include attribution,
raise Iran's denial and no injuries reported. PICKS up 2nd graf,
Iran said another... SUBS 7th graf `Gulf-based ...for inspection.'
with one graf to clarify that shipping executives said speedboats
were Iranian. PICKS up 8th pvs `No injuries...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf-Stress, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY24</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian gunboats fired machine guns at a
Norwegian supertanker Thursday, shipping executives said, in the
first reported shooting incident in the Persian Gulf since Iran
agreed to negotiate a truce with Iraq.
   But Iran quickly denied involvement in the ship raid, instead
saying it was probably the work of those who are opposed to peace
in the region. No injuries were reported.
   Iran said another 1,000 civilians were injured in Iraqi chemical
bomb raids, raising the number to 2,700 in two days, and it urged
the United Nations Security Council to condemn such attacks.
   The official Iraqi News Agency, meanwhile, said without
elaborating that Iraqi warplanes raided two Iranian oil pumping
facilities.
   At the United Nations on Thursday, Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar and Security Council members tried to break a
deadlock over a cease-fire resolution Iran and Iraq have accepted.
The talks have bogged down over Iraq's demand for direct talks with
Iran before the cease-fire is set.
   Also Thursday, a leader of the rebels fighting Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini's rule was publicly hanged in Iran and another
surrendered to government forces, the official Islamic Republic
News Agency said.
   The report said the executed man was a leader of the Mujahedeen
Khalq or People's Holy Warriors, an Iraqi-backed rebel group. The
prisoner was identified by the news agency only as a rebel
commander.
   Gulf-based shipping executives said the tanker attack appeared
to be an isolated one and did not mean a resurgence in the gulf's
``tanker war.'' The executives, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said Iranian gunboats opened fire after the tanker, the
Berge Lord, defied demands to stop for inspection.
   No injuries and only minor damage was reported aboard the
284,502-ton Berge Lord, which continued out of the gulf with a
cargo of Saudi Arabian crude oil.
   The encounter, involving an estimated six Iranian gunboats,
occurred near Abu Musa island in the southern gulf, a base for
Iran's speedboats.
   In an unusual move, Iran quickly disavowed the shooting and
suggested that any such attack would be designed to undermine the
current U.N. peace effort.
   The Islamic Republic News Agency said an unidentified military
official at general command headquarters ``refuted reports that
Iranian gunboats had attacked a Norwegian tanker in the Persian
Gulf.''
   IRNA quoted the official as saying Iranian gunboats ``have never
had and do not have such missions,'' and ``probably the attack, if
it really took place, has been carried out by those who are against
a stable peace in the region and are hampering implementation of
U.N. Resolution 598.''
   Iran never has officially acknowledged its gunboat raids on
neutral shipping in the gulf, and veteran observers could not
recall a previous denial.
   Some gulf shipping executives said the Iranians apparently fired
only ``warning shots'' at the Norwegian tanker, which was the
victim of an Iranian gunboat attack in the Strait of Hormuz in
March.
   The ship's master sent a ``mayday'' distress call. It prompted
immediate fears that the ``tanker war,'' in which more than 500
ships have been damaged and 350 seamen killed in the past eight
years, had resumed.
   Iran announced July 18 it would accept a U.N.-sponsored
cease-fire in its 8-year-old war with Iraq. Since then, Iraq, which
accepted the resolution when it was adopted a year ago, has not
conducted air raids on Iranian oil tankers. Iran also has refrained
from attacking commercial tankers during that time.
   Iran, however, has continued to stop and inspect neutral ships
in the southern gulf, in search of Iraq-related cargo. Such
activity by a belligerent is legal under international maritime law.
   Also Thursday, Iran said that 1,700 civilians were now reported
injured in an Iraqi chemical bomb attack Tuesday in the town of
Oshnaviyeh in the northern province of West Azerbaijan. In another
attack Wednesday on villages west of Oshnaviyeh, another 1,000
villagers were injured, the agency reported.
   Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati said in letter to Perez de
Cuellar that his government ``urgently requests unequivocal
condemnation of this heinous Iraqi act of aggression by the
Security Council.''
</TEXT>
