<HEAD>Envoy Says Noriega May Want Talks With Deposed President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panamanian Ambassador Juan Sosa said Thursday
there are indications military ruler Gen. Manuel Noriega may want
to negotiate with ousted President Eric Arturo Delvalle to whom
Sosa is loyal.
   The ambassador said Delvalle, who has been in hiding in Panama,
has received a written message from Noriega but ``no negotiations
are under way.''
   Sosa said Delvalle, whom the Reagan administration recognizes as
president of Panama, has always been willing to negotiate for a
return of democracy to Panama.
   He said he did not believe Delvalle has met with a Noriega
emissary as reported in Thursday's editions of The Miami Herald.
The newspaper quoted sources close to Delvalle and quoted former
Noriega aide Jose Blandon as saying the ousted president was
preparing a document on his willingness to negotiate.
   Sosa said in a telephone interview that Noriega sent a proposal
for a dialogue last month, shortly before Delvalle slipped
temporarily into Miami for a medical checkup.
   Sosa said the embassy in Washington has had no contact with
Noriega's government in Panama City and maintains itself with funds
withheld from Noriega. Sosa said he has a staff of five other
diplomats, a receptionist and a chauffeur.
   Roberto Leyton, the Panamanian ambassador to the Organization of
American States here, is loyal to Noriega.
   Delvalle dismissed Noriega as defense chief Feb. 25, but was
ousted the following day by the Noriega-dominated National Assembly.
