<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 2253EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Psychologists-Dukakis     08-04 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Psychologists-Dukakis,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Psychologists Say Fear of Mental Health Treatment Could Pose
Danger</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negative preoccupation with mental health
treatment could hurt the nation by discouraging public officials
who need help from seeking it, an official of the American
Psychological Association said Thursday.
   ``It makes it impossible for key decision-makers, including the
president whose finger is on the nuclear trigger, to receive
appropriate and preventive psychological care at times of personal
crisis,'' Dr. Bryant L. Welch told a news conference.
   The issue was thrust into the spotlight this week by rumors,
originating with associates of political extremist Lyndon LaRouche,
that Democratic presidential candidate Michael Dukakis had
undergone treatment for depression.
   That has been denied by Dukakis and his personal physician. And
President Reagan said he shouldn't have made a joking comment
Wednesday that Dukakis was ``an invalid.''
   ``All people, including elected officials, no matter how
healthy, are psychologically unstable during times of personal
crisis. These crises can involve the loss of a loved one, a serious
physical illness, or other traumatic event,'' said Welch, the APA's
executive director for professional practice.
   Professional treatment can help people through those events, and
seeking such treatment is not an indication of any underlying
mental illness, Welch said.
   ``Unfortunately, in the current climate there is no question
that (public officials) are being discouraged from seeking
psychological care for fear the very fact of seeking care will
subject them to being labeled `mentally ill' and unfit for public
service,'' Welch said.
   Whether an individual can stand up under pressure is a
legitimate question, Welch said, ``but I don't think having had
psychological care is a good predictor of that.''
   Past presidents have suffered from serious bouts of depression,
notably Abraham Lincoln and Andrew Jackson, Welch said.
   He also expressed concern about the insistence on candidates
releasing raw medical records, commenting that such information
could be subject to misunderstanding and political demagoguery.
   Information on physical and mental condition is important for
voters, he said, but should be explained by physicians rather than
simply making medical records public.
   Asked if merely talking with a friend in times of stress
constitutes treatment, Welch said that could be beneficial, but he
would not consider it to be ``treatment.''
   ``I'm not saying one should always see a mental health
specialist every time they undergo a life crisis,'' he said.
</TEXT>
