<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Burma 1stLd-Writethru a0699 08-04 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0699,0678</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Moves Into Rangoon as Students Demonstrate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3d graf `Diplomats in' to CORRECT time of student riots
to earlier this year</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops moved into Rangoon on Thursday
to stop thousands of masked teen-agers from demonstrating in
defiance of the Burmese government's martial law decree, diplomats
and returning tourists reported.
   Heavy monsoon rains lashed the crowds. Soldiers fired warning
shots but no violence was reported.
   Diplomats in Rengoon described the demonstrations as the largest
against the military-dominated regime since student riots earlier
this year.
   ``Both the students and military seem to be trying to avoid
confrontation, but the situation is fluid, tense and dangerous,''
one diplomat said.
   Protesters, most of them high school students, shouted demands
for democracy, the ouster of President Sein Lwin and freedom for
dissidents the former general has jailed since assuming power last
week. He declared martial law Wednesday after students held
peaceful street demonstrations.
   Separate large protests began simultaneously at midday Thursday,
the diplomats reported, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   They said the total number of protesters was not known but about
10,000 gathered at the Sule Pagoda in the heart Rangoon and
soldiers fired warning volleys into the air. Most in the crowd were
youngsters with their faces covered so authorities could not
identify them, according to the diplomats.
   West European tourists interviewed after arrival in Bangkok said
they saw armored personnel carriers and jeeps armed with machine
guns cruising the streets. Soldiers guarded the city hall, National
Assembly building and other sites.
   Reports from diplomats said the heavy rain thinned some crowds,
but by late afternoon a throng had gathered at Rangoon University,
a center of protest four miles north of the city. They said about
25 truckloads of soldiers were at the campus.
   Italian tourist Otta Violavaggi said about half the stores in
downtown Rangoon closed after Wednesday's demonstrations, which
authorities said led them to declaring martial law in the city of
3.5 million.
   ``Everybody was very anxious. Nobody knows what to do,'' said
Christine Jacobs of Brussels, Belgium. Tourists said they were told
they would be arrested if they took photographs.
   Several Burmese said a general strike would be held Monday, the
tourists said, quoting the informants as saying the date was chosen
because eight is an auspicious number and Monday is the eighth day
of the eighth month of 1988.
   Other Rangoon residents reached by telephone said protesters
dispersed after several trucks full of soldiers arrived at a
government office building near the Sule Pagoda, a shrine said to
be more than 2,000 years old and believed to house relics of the
Lord Buddha.
   Crowds gathered around the colonial-style red brick office
building and shouted anti-government slogans.
   Rangoon radio, monitored in Bangkok, said after martial law was
declared Wednesday that it was necessary to maintain security,
safeguard property and allow students who so desire to study
peacefully. It said directives might be issued for summary trials.
   The diplomats said there was no curfew, but few residents were
seen on the streets after the martial law decree. Tourists said it
was hard to get a restaurant meal Wednesday night.
   Sein Lwin, 64, was elected president of Burma and chairman of
the ruling Socialist Program Party last week, replacing Ne Win, who
stepped down after ruling Burma for 26 years. Pamphlets circulated
in Rangoon call him a ruthless oppressor who must be overthrown.
   Since Sein Lwin assumed power authorities have arrested several
dissidents and others, including the country's most respected and
vocal critic of the system, Aung Gyi, and Associated Press
correspondent Sein Win. They have been accused of ``attacking the
state.''
   Foreign journalists have followed developments by telephone and
by monitoring official media because of restrictions on their entry
to Rangoon, the only legal gateway to Burma for most outsiders.
Foreign reporters usually entered the country in the past on
tourist visas issued at Burmese embassies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
