<DOCNO> AP880804-0116 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 1722EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-EarlyDirty 1st-LdWritethru a0729 08-04 0927</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Early Dirty, 1st-Ld Writethru, a0729,930</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Campaign Turning Dirty, And It's Only August</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Kirk comment, inserting 2 grafs after 6th graf
pvs, ``There's something, and subbing 2 grafs for 23rd graf pvs,
Kohut said</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   These are supposed to be the dog days of the
presidential campaign, when the candidates rest between conventions
and the voters vacation. But in this summer's record heat, the 1988
race is turning mean.
   A month before the traditional Labor Day kick-off for the fall
campaign, Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis has
already taken a hard shot: The news was filled with stories about
rumors that he did _ or didn't _ have psychiatric treatment.
   This was more than just the usual jabbing at your opponent that
is part and parcel of the political wars.
   It was a nasty trick, an effort to raise doubts about the
stability and sanity of a presidential candidate _ without a single
fact to back up the rumors.
   The Democratic presidential nominee and his doctor firmly denied
the rumors on Wednesday, and now the Democrats are pointing the
finger at the Republicans as the ultimate source.
   ``There's something significant about what the Republicans have
done here,'' said New York Gov. Mario Cuomo on Thursday, ``the fact
that they would use Lyndon LaRouche to get this thing started, the
fact that they would get negative, that they would get so
irrelevant so early.''
   Democratic Party chief Paul Kirk said the Republicans are
practicing ``the politics of desperation.''
   ``If there's been any negative campaigning, it's coming from one
side,'' he said Thursday. ``They have nothing positive to say about
the future.''
   The only fingerprints on the rumors are those of LaRouche, a
political extremist, whose supporters have handed out fliers
spreading the Dukakis rumors. But other news organizations have
reported hearing the same sort of talk from Republican sources and
even from White House officials.
   And President Reagan's fingerprints are on the making of the
rumors into news.
   Asked by a LaRouche supporter about the matter, Reagan made a
crack Wednesday about Dukakis as ``an invalid.'' Then he said he
shouldn't have said that, that his joke had fallen flat.
   But what he had said had been enough. The president had dealt
with the issue in front of the cameras, and Dukakis felt he had to
step forward and deny the rumors personally.
   Now the question is: Will the mud-slinging continue or will the
tone of the campaign improve dramatically.
   Bush and his fellow Republicans have the major opportunity in
the next two weeks to set the tone. The indications are their
message will be a tough one.
   His campaign officials have outlined a program through the
Republican convention of sharp attacks on Dukakis and his record.
   Thursday's theme was defense and Bush himself said Dukakis is
for ``unilateral disarmament,'' a favorite charge aimed at painting
a liberal as weak on defense.
   Former presidential hopeful Jack Kemp added his blast in a
Chicago speech, saying Dukakis is ``not a Kennedy Democrat. He is a
liberal Democrat of the McGovern era.''
   These attacks are to continue, with Reagan playing a role in his
appearence on the opening night of the GOP convention in New
Orleans.
   That strategy can hurt Dukakis, said pollster Andrew Kohut of
the Gallup Organization.
   ``They can use the dreaded `L' word,'' Kohut said. ``They can
make Dukakis out to be a liberal.''
   But there are dangers for the Republicans in this strategy.
   One is that voters will find it all too negative and too boring.
   The Democrats tried to avoid that danger at their Atlanta
convention by using humor, making fun of Bush with Sen. Edward
Kennedy asking ``Where was George?'' and keynote speaker Ann
Richards talking about Bsh's being born with ``a silver foot in his
mouth.''
   The other danger is that the American people would never get a
chance to hear the positives about Bush, amid all the
Dukakis-bashing.
   Democratic chief Kirk said Bush has been ``running against the
1970s and trying to apply labels to Governor Dukakis that have no
bearing. ... I haven't heard any ... dialogue about where we go,
about the future of this country.''
   Pollster Kohut said the Republicans have to spend more time
talking about Bush's positives than about Dukakis' negatives. Bush
is widely recognized by the public, but poll after poll has shown
that the voters don't really know much about him.
   The Republican convention _ and Bush's acceptance speech in
particular _ are prime opportunities for Bush to introduce himself
to America and to put forward a positive vision for the country.
   ``He has to do exactly what Dukakis did,'' Kohut said. ``He has
to make himself more human. ... The voters want a leader and a
human being.''
   In Atlanta, Dukakis didn't do any Bush-bashing in his acceptance
speech, taking the time to lay out his own themes and his own ideas
for the nation.
   Cuomo, in poking fun at Bush, made the point clearly that the
Republican nominee has a case to make.
   ``He's a nice man. He's a good American. But there's no
rationale for George Bush,'' said Cuomo. ``There is no case for
George Bush. ... He was a terrific first baseman for Yale. He's
tall. ...''
   In the meantime, the tone of campaign '88 has turned sharp and
sour, perhaps signaling a long and difficult fall to come.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Evans Witt is a Washington-based political
writer covering the 1988 presidential campaign.
</TEXT>
