<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Shuttle-Disappointment     08-04 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-Disappointment,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Engine Test Abort Another Disappointment For Shuttle Launch Team</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Space Shuttle Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Success was within the grasp of the
tired group of space shuttle launch controllers. They had been
frustrated by two less-than-successful practice counts in a week,
and now they were seconds away from a vital test firing of shuttle
Discovery's engines.
   ``8...7...6...5...,'' the clock ticked away. Then stopped.
   A computer had sensed a problem with an engine valve Thursday
and withheld an ignition signal. The test was put off at least
three days.
   Just a month ago, on July 4, the workers at the Kennedy Space
Center had been energized when at long last, after months of delay,
Discovery was transported to the launch pad.
   Several thousand turned out at midnight to cheer Discovery as it
moved in the glare of spotlights. Nearly 20,000, including
families, took advantage of a rare open house to drive their cars
past the launch pad later that day to proudly view the shuttle
sitting majestically on Launch Pad 39B.
   This is what we're here for, they said. To launch vehicles into
space. Now, 2{ years after the Challenger disaster and the death of
its seven astronauts, they had a shuttle on the pad. The launch was
set for early September.
   Since then, it's been one disappointment after another.
   On July 15, engineers detected a small leak in a gas line in a
steering engine compartment. Engineers came up with a scheme to
reach the offending fitting but that would mean about a two-week
launch postponement.
   They would do the repair after the main engines were test fired.
   But before that countdown could begin, they had to conduct a
practice count in which Discovery's external fuel tank was to be
filled with half a million gallons of propellant.
   Fueling began last Friday, but was quickly scrubbed because of a
hydrogen leak in ground support equipment. The leak was fixed and
another count begun on Sunday. Another hydrogen leak cropped up.
NASA decided to complete the test, skipping several planned fuel
tests, with a partial load.
   The countdown was completed, but technicians could not find the
leak. So they changed all the seals and fittings in the suspect
area.
   On Wednesday night, the count resumed for the test firing,
considered critical for certifying Discovery for flight.
   All night long, the count was perfect. Fueling was completed on
time. There were no leaks, and the team was well ahead of schedule.
   Then the bitter disappointment when the valve closed too slowly
or a sensor gave a wrong reading and the computer called a halt.
   It appeared almost certain the launch would slip into October.
   Has the morale of the launch team been shattered?
   ``To tell you the truth, these are professional people,'' said
John Talone, Discovery's schedule flow director. ``There is a
certain amount of frustration because we thrive on doing these
things completely and getting them done. When things don't work as
well, it's just a challenge. But they're ready to come back
tomorrow and I don't see any morale effect of it.''
</TEXT>
