<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 1825EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DrugAgentSlain     08-04 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Agent Slain,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interrogation Tape Played in Torture-Slaying Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The groans of a beaten U.S. drug agent and
his pleas for his family's safety were heard in federal court
Thursday as prosecutors played tapes of the slain agent's
interrogation by his abductors.
   At one point, Enrique Camarena is heard asking if he can bandage
his broken ribs. The request is ignored.
   ``With the beating you have given me ... do you think that I am
going to lie to you?'' Camarena asks at one point.
   The tapes, which run nearly two hours, depict an apparently
exhausted Camarena answering questions in a monotone, disclosing
confidential Drug Enforcement Administration information in an
effort to safe his life.
   ``Don't hit me any more,'' Camarena declares several times.
   ``No,'' the interrogator replies calmly. ``No one will hit you.''
   But later in the tape, Camarena is heard moaning in pain.
   The actual torture the prosecution says he endured was not on
the recordings.
   Camarena was abducted in Guadalajara on Feb. 7, 1985, as he was
leaving the American consulate to have lunch with his wife. His
body and that of his pilot, Alfredo Zavala Avelar, were found
buried at a remote ranch in Mexico several weeks later. They had
been severely beaten and Camarena's skull was shattered.
   Three Mexican nationals are on trial in the crimes which the
government claims were orchestrated by Mexican drug kingpin Rafael
Caro Quintero, 33, who is imprisoned in Mexico. He and two other
men are being tried for the crimes there.
   In testimony following the playing of the tapes, DEA agent Dale
Stinson identified the voices of Camarena's interrogators as Caro
and Sergio Espinosa Verdin, a former Mexican federal police
commander.
   Rene Verdugo Urquidez, 36, and Raul Lopez Alvarez, 28, are
charged with the murders of Camarena and Zavala. Also charged is
Jesus Felix Gutierrez, 38, who allegedly helped Caro escape in
Mexico after the killing.
   Only one defendant, Verdugo, was mentioned in passing on the
tapes, which prosecutors say were made at an estate in Guadalajara.
   The muffled tapes were played in a darkened courtroom with
jurors watching a transcript of the words projected on a screen.
   Most of the interrogation focused on the identity of DEA
informants in Mexico. Camarena named two and gave information on
where they lived. He also gave directions to the home of another
DEA agent in Mexico.
   ``I am saying this to you because, well, don't hurt my family
please,'' Camarena is heard saying in a quiet voice.
   ``No one is going to hurt your family. Forget about that,'' says
the interrogator. ``They are not to blame for anything. ... You
just keep on remembering, that is all. ... I am not going to hit
you or anything. OK?''
   Large portions of the tapes center on the interrogators' efforts
to find out how much Camarena knew about Caro. Camarena claimed he
knew little, that he couldn't find out where Caro lived and was
hampered because American agents were not allowed to carry firearms
in Mexico.
   At that, the interrogator snapped, ``Don't tell me about your
problems, speak of the information you can give us, you can provide
us to finish with this bunch of jerks.''
   ``Yes, sir,'' Camarena said in a weak voice. ``What more can I
tell you sir?''
   Toward the end of the tape, Camarena is heard moaning and crying
out in pain.
   ``I am not going to hit you,'' the interrogator assures him.
   ``No, it was that I am getting sharp pains,'' says the agent,
who is ignored.
   ``Couldn't I ask you to have my ribs bandaged, please?''
Camarena asks. That too is ignored.
</TEXT>
