<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina     08-04 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Financial Markets Respond Favorably to Argentine Austerity Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By OSCAR J. SERRAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banks reopened, stock values
climbed and interest rates fell Thursday in a positive reaction by
financial markets to the government's economic austerity plan.
   President Raul Alfonsin and other officials unveiled the plan
late Wednesday. It is intended to curtail triple-digit inflation,
one of the highest foreign debts in the developing world and a
crippling budget deficit.
   People lined up at banks and foreign exchange houses that were
open fo the first time this week. The government ordered Sunday
that they remain closed while it completed the austerity plan.
   Samuel Glembubogki, executive director of the Federation of
Cooperative Banks, said withdrawals, which signal lack of
confidence, were ``very, very small. The tendency has been to
maintain deposits.''
   Monthly interest rates on loans declined to about 15 percent by
the end of Thursday's business day. A week ago they were 25 percent
and higher.
   The average value of shares on the Stock Exchange rose by 20
percent as investors shifted their money out of bonds and foreign
currencies. The austral, Argentina's currency, traded at a better
rate than the 14.4 to the dollar tentatively set Wednesday night by
Economy Minister Juan Sourrouille.
   Also included in the economic program are cuts in government
spending and voluntary voluntary price controls.
   Argentina's 31 million people have suffered years of inflation.
The cost of living for the first seven months of 1988 rose nearly
150 percent, the current budget has a $3.5 billion deficit and the
$56 billion foreign debt is the third highest among developing
countries.
</TEXT>
