<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0690 08-04 0794</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0690,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Campaigns in South, Hoping to Win Reagan, Jackson
Supporters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Dukakis not mentioning that civil rights workers
bodies found 24 years ago Thursday, inserting 1 graf after 7th graf
pvs, The rural</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis campaigned in rural
Mississippi on Thursday and said his promise of economi change
would deliver opportunity to all, ``no matter who they are or where
they come from or what the color of their skin.''
   Visiting near one of the civil rights battlegrounds of the
1960s, the Democratic presidential nominee made only brief
reference to that struggle for equality for blacks.
   But he did say, ``Here in Mississippi, you know the importance
of equal rights and civil rights. Today I say to all Americans _
not just in Neshoba County but all over America _ we've got to work
together, we've got to work together to bring down the barriers to
opportunity for all our people.''
   Dukakis spoke to a noontime crowd at the Neshoba County Fair,
where a crowd filled a grandstand and many more sat in lounge
chairs on the red dirt of a horse track in front of the covered
podium. The mostly white audience was estimated at 6,000 to 7,000
people by Sheriff Glen Waddell.
   The appearance was loaded with symbolism, as the Neshoba fair
was the place where Ronald Reagan kicked off his campaign as the
Republican presidential nominee eight years ago, nearly to the day.
Dukakis has directed much of his campaign efforts since winning the
nomination at attracting the support of independent and Democratic
voters who supported Reagan in the past two elections.
   At the same time, he was campaigning in a state where he lost
the Democratic primary to Jesse Jackson.
   The rural region of east-central Mississippi was the scene of
one of the dark incidents of the civil rights struggle: the 1964
slaying of three civil rights workers, an episode that Jackson
frequently recalled in his campaign speeches.
   Dukakis didn't note in his remarks that the three men's bodies
were found 24 years ago Thursday. Asked about that later, he said,
``I talked about economic opportunity because that's the most
important single thing that concerns people.''
   Mississippi was the first stop on a three-day campaign trip that
followed a day in Boston spent dealing with news accounts about
rumors that Dukakis had undergone psychiatric treatment. No
substantiation for the rumors has been presented, and Dukakis and
his doctor said Wednesday he had never undergone psychiatric
treatment or counseling of any kind.
   Dukakis received a friendly greeting from the hot and dusty
crowd, although some in the audience waved signs supporting
Republican George Bush. One sign said, ``Liberal Go Home.''
   In his 1980 visit, Reagan declared his support for ``states'
rights'' and a restoration of powers to state and local governments.
   Dukakis, in his remarks, made no reference to Reagan.
   He repeated his broad calls for investment in schools and
industrial revitalization to produce more and better jobs. He
referred to Mississippi as ``a state that's hurting.''
   ``We can settle for what Lloyd Bentsen calls a Swiss cheese
economy,'' Dukakis said, using his running mate's term to describe
a nation marked by pockets of economic hard times.
   ``Or, we can go to work and build an economic future for this
country that will create good jobs at good wages for every citizen
in this land, no matter who they are or where they come from or
what the color of their skin,'' Dukakis said.
   ``We have to work together to see that every citizen and every
child born in this country is an equal shareholder in the American
dream,'' he said.
   Appearing with Dukakis were local officials including Democratic
Gov. Ray Mabus, who was elected last year.
   Dukakis also cited Democratic Sen. John Stennis, who has held
his seat for 40 years, and said, ``You can't tell me that
Mississippi isn't going to vote for Mike Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen
this fall.''
   Dukakis repeated his criticism of the mililtary contracts
scandal, saying, ``We're going to throw the dishonest contractors
and the wheeler dealers out of the Pentagon once and for all.''
   Dukakis met with local elected officials and some former
supporters of Jackson aboard a bus during the hour-long ride from
the Meridian airport to the fairgrounds outside Philadelphia.
   His visit to Mississippi was the first stop on a hurried
campaign swing that takes him to the West Coast and back to Boston
in three days. Aides said much of the trip would be devoted to
stressing the themes of protecting the environment and fragile
coastal areas, highlighted by a scheduled appearance just off the
Pacific Coast Highway at Laguna Beach, Calif.
</TEXT>
