<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Hostage     08-04 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Hostage,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Letter Received From Cordes, Held in Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hamadi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government got a letter Thursday
from kidnapped West German businessman Rudolf Cordes and a panel
monitoring the hostage situation in Lebanon met to discuss it.
   Two other letters from Cordes were delivered to his family
Wednesday. He was abducted in Beirut, Lebanon, on Jan. 17, 1987.
   The West German-Algerian man who delivered the three letters
said he believed Cordes would be freed soon.
   ``The chances look genuinely good,'' said Abdel-Kadar Sahraoui
in an interview with the ZDF television network.
   Government sources confirmed privately that Sahraoui, identified
as a middleman by news media, delivered the letters but they
refused to give details.
   Federal government spokesman Norbert Schaefer announced Thursday
night that the third letter was received and said the government
and family were convinced the letters were authentic.
   ``The government and Cordes' family have received signs that he
is alive through these three letters,'' Schaefer said.
   He said a special panel of government security officials
monitoring the hostage situation in Lebanon met for an hour to
discuss the letters.
   He would not reveal the contents of the letters or details of
the meeting.
   In the ZDF interview, Sahraoui did not say whether he met
personally with Cordes' captors.
   He said Cordes is being treated by a doctor, but that ``his life
is not in danger.'' Earlier West German news reports said Cordes
was ill.
   Days after Shiite Moslem radicals kidnapped Cordes in Beirut,
another West German businessman, Alfred Schmidt, was also kidnapped
in the Lebanese capital.
   Schmidt's kidnappers freed him last September in what they
called a ``goodwill gesture.''
   Last April, a court in Duesseldorf convicted Abbas Hamadi of
masterminding the two abductions in a bid to force West Germany to
free his brother, Mohammed Ali Hamadi.
   Mohammed Hamadi now is on trial in Frankfurt, charged with air
piracy and murder in a 1985 TWA hijacking in which U.S. Navy diver
Robert Stethem was killed.
</TEXT>
