<DOCNO> AP880804-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 2103EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Rampage     08-04 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Rampage,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paper Says 82 Elite Troopers Arrested After Drunken Rampage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper reported Thursday that 82 elite ``blue
beret'' paratroopers were arrested for going on a drunken rampage
after a celebration of a military holiday.
   Moscow police stations resembled a ``war front'' as officers
brought the drunken soldiers in Tuesday night, said the report in
Moskovsky Komsomolyets, published by the Moscow Young Communist
League.
   It was among the worst cases of misconduct by soldiers printed
in the Soviet media and indicates the military is not above
criticism in the atmosphere of Mikhail S. Gorbachev's effort to
open Soviet society.
   The newspaper said the trouble began Tuesday at Moscow's
riverside Gorky Park, where up to 50,000 people had gathered, a
third of them former paratroopers.
   ``Young fellows in blue berets went on a spree,'' it said.
``They conducted themselves outrageously during the holiday.''
   After festivities in the park, many drunken soldiers started
causing trouble in the streets.
   Groups of up to 60 entered cafes demanding vodka. A fight
involving 40 people began in one cafe and spilled into the street,
the report said.
   Seven paratroopers were arrested for beating a passerby, who
suffered a brain concussion, it said.
   Police repeatedly warned rowdy paratroopers but they did not
stop and 82 finally were taken to police stations, Moskovsky
Komsomolyets reported.
   It did not say what charges they faced or give any other details
of criminal proceedings.
</TEXT>
