<DOCNO> AP880804-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 1852EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-YonkersDeseg     08-04 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yonkers Deseg,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Service Suspends City's Bond Rating</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Wall Street credit rating firm suspended
the city's bond rating Thursday, crippling the city's borrowing
power on the third day of fines imposed when City Council rejected
a housing desegregation plan.
   ``We can't borrow money,'' interim City Manager Neil DeLuca said
after Moody's Investors Service Inc. suspended its rating of
Yonkers' bonds. ``No corporation can function without the ability
to borrow money.''
   A federal judge began fining the city Tuesday after City Council
failed to support his plan to build low- and middle income housing
to remedy housing and school segregation.
   The fines began at $100 on Tuesday and double each day.
   In a statement, Moody's said the suspension was ``due to
uncertainties resulting from daily fines imposed by the federal
court. Those uncertainties derive foremost from the potential for
extraordinary disruption of operations.''
   Moody's said the fine schedule would deplete the city's reported
Aug. 3 cash reserve of $66.3 million by Aug. 22.
   Another credit rating firm, Standard & Poor's Corp. said it was
monitoring the situation Thursday and took no action on its
Yonkers' rating.
   Yonkers, the state's fourth-largest municipality with a
population of nearly 200,000, has been in a legal tug-of-war with
U.S. District Judge Leonard Sand since 1985, when he found the city
liable for intentionally segregating housing and schools during a
40-year period. Yonkers is just north of New York City.
   City Council on Monday voted 4-3 against endorsing a package of
bonuses, financial incentives and zoning variances to attract
developers to build the housing.
   ``Everybody seems to be doing the same thing, waiting for the
other guy to move,'' DeLuca said. ``The judge, the council, the
governor, the control board. ... We can't get the City Council to
change its vote and we can't get the judge to change his ruling and
we're going bankrupt.''
   The judge has suggested that Gov. Mario Cuomo step in to help
resolve the crisis, either by removing the four councilmen who
voted against the judge's plan or through the state-run Emergency
Financial Control Board, which oversees city spending. The four
councilmen are paying daily fines of $500.
   The control board, however, postponed a meeting slated for
Thursday and Cuomo said he was reluctant to get involved.
   The governor said, ``I'm not going to allow any damage to occur
that I can prevent.'' But he told New York radio station WCBS-AM
that action ``has to be taken by the City Council in the first
place. ... These people were elected.''
   He said it was ``not the best way to deal with these matters to
have the power come down from the state Capitol to throw an elected
official out of office. ... I don't like disrupting the system.''
   The city has asked the U.S. 2nd Circuit Court of Appeals to
block the contempt finding and the fines while it appeals the
judge's action.
   Secretary of State Gail Shaffer, urging the city council to meet
before Tuesday and get the city out of contempt, outlined possible
actions the control board can take should the city fail to act.
   Those actions include imposition of a wage and hiring freeze, a
halt of discretionary spending and, finally, taking over
disbursement of all city funds, she said in a letter to the council.
   By Tuesday's meeting, the aggregate fines will total $25,500,
she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
