<1ST_LINE>r p AM-SoftMoney 1stLd-Writethru   08-04 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soft Money, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0698,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Common Cause Calls for Strict Campaign Rules on `Soft Money'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 5th graf to UPDATE with comment from
Dukakis campaign and RNC; SUBS 5th and 12th grafs pvs to CORRECT
spelling of Wertheimer.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Common Cause asked a federal court Thursday to
close what it says is a loophole that allows presidential campaigns
to benefit from millions of dollars in indirect contributions from
``fat cats.''
   However, Fred Wertheimer, president of the group which lobbies
for strict government ethics, acknowledged that little more than
``moral force'' could be exerted this year to keep the presidential
campaigns from using so-called ``soft money.''
   Republicans and Democrats have said they plan to raise about $67
million in ``soft money'' for the 1988 presidential campaigns,
which are limited to receiving equal funding from the federal
Treasury.
   The ``soft money'' is donated to state parties, which can use it
to pay for voter registration and get-out-the-vote drives as well
as other activities that could have an effect on the presidential
election.
   ``Soft money allows a presidential campaign to raise campaign
contributions that the presidential campaign finance law was
enacted to ban,'' Wertheimer said at a news conference. ``It opens
the door for `fat cats' and special interest givers to provide
large sums of money to help a presidential candidate and thereby
creates the opportunity for these givers to buy influence with the
president of the United States.''
   Robert Farmer, the Dukakis campaign's fund-raiser who plans to
raise $42 million in ``soft money,'' said he supported closing the
loophole in the law and blamed the Republicans for causing the
circumstances by traditionally outspending the Democrats in this
area.
   ``I refuse to apologize for trying to create a level playing
field with the Republicans,'' Farmer said in a telephone interview
from Miami. ``Until they close the loopholes, I want to compete
with the Republicans dollar for dollar.''
   Albert Maruggi, a spokesman for the Republican National
Committee, said there was no immediate reaction to the Common Cause
action.
   A year ago, U.S. District Judge Thomas Flannery, in a lawsuit
brought by Common Cause, ordered the Federal Election Commission to
draw up rules governing the use of ``soft money.''
   Those rules have not been written, and Common Cause filed a
request with the U.S. District Court on Thursday for an order
giving the FEC a month to produce a draft of the proposed
regulations.
   Even if a hearing were granted immediately and Common Cause won,
it is unlikely that the rules could have more than marginal legal
impact before this November's presidential election, according to
Roger Witten, an attorney for Common Cause.
   FEC spokesman Fred Eiland said the commission's general counsel
has been working on the rules and is sifting through public
comments received last March.
   ``You have a small staff of two people who are doing our rule
making,'' Eiland said.
   He did not know when a draft of the proposed rules would be
ready.
   Wertheimer said Common Cause believes the use of ``soft money''
for presidential campaigns is illegal and if the FEC had drafted
rules to that effect, it could discourage the practice.
   ``This is illegal money,'' Wertheimer said. ``This is money that
was outlawed in response to Watergate.''
   Under questioning, however, Wertheimer acknowledged that while
Common Cause raised the issue of illegality in its arguments before
the court last year, ``the court did not endorse that position.''
</TEXT>
