<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Iran-Contra 1stLd-Writethru a0719 08-04 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0719,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Lawyers Say Judge Unfair for Pushing Speedy Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 6th graf bgng ``Not only'' with four new grafs to INSERT
additional quote from North brief and to UPDATE with Walsh's reply.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for Oliver L. North accused the judge
in the Iran-Contra case Thursday of abandoning fairness in order to
put the former White House aide on trial before the fall
presidential election.
   The attorneys asked U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell to
postpone until January a hearing scheduled for next Monday on the
use of classified information at the trial.
   The defense said a delay is needed because lawyers haven't ``had
time to even review in any detail the hundreds of thousands of
pages of classified and `sensitive' documents'' turned over by
independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh.
   North's lawyers said Gesell had imposed impossible deadlines on
the defense for preparing for Monday's hearing and the trial, set
to begin Sept. 20.
   ``In its frantic rush to trial before the election, the court
seems to have abandoned all sense of what is possible and what is
fair,'' attorneys Brendan V. Sullivan Jr. and Barry Simon said in a
brief pleading filed in U.S. District Court.
   ``The hearing, if it is held on Aug. 8, will be a complete sham,
and the court knows it,'' the defense lawyers said in their
harshest attack on Gesell.
   ``Not only is the court's current schedule totally unreasonable;
it is directly contrary to the court's claim that it is `simply
trying to be fair to both sides,''' the defense said, quoting
Gesell's remarks at a hearing last week.
   In a reply brief filed later in the day, Walsh said North's
request for a delay ``reveals the artificiality of the stream of
demands and complaints to which the government and the court have
been subjected since arraignment.''
   ``In no way should the defendant's failure to cooperate with the
court be rewarded with the interminable delays he seeks,'' Walsh
said.
   North is accused of conspiring with former national security
adviser John M. Poindexter and arms dealers Albert Hakim and
Richard V. Secord to illegally divert the profits of U.S.-Iran arms
sales to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels. Separate trials have been
ordered for the other three men.
   Gesell has ruled that North is entitled to inspect a large
volume of classified documents in order to try to show that he
acted with the permission of higher officials in the Reagan
administration.
   The hearing Monday is scheduled to consider North's proposals to
use classified information at the trial. The Classified Information
Procedures Act sets up a mechanism under which a defendant must
notify the court and the government of his plan to disclose
classified information.
   If government agencies refuse to declassify documents the court
deems relevant to the case, charges could be dropped.
   Walsh, trying to buy more time to deal with the problems of
declassifying the documents, has suggested that Gesell put aside
the major conspiracy counts against North and proced to trial on 13
other charges.
   These counts, which the prosecution contends don't involve
nearly as many classified documents, include allegations that North
lied to Congress, obstructed a presidential investigation of the
Iran-Contra affair and illegally enriched himself.
   He is also charged with illegally using a tax-exempt foundation
to raise money for the Contras.
   The defense also responded to Walsh's charge that it had flouted
the law and Gesell's order by failing to specify which government
secrets it wants to disclose in court. Gesell had ordered North to
file that notice by Aug. 1.
   The defense said it filed its 265-page list of documents because
it was ``faced with the possibility that documents not listed in
the notice could be precluded from use at trial.''
</TEXT>
