<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0758 08-04 0956</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0758,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Charges That Dukakis' Foreign Policy Amounts to `Disarmament'</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: ADDS final graf with Bush comment outside funeral home.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush said
Thursday that Michael Dukakis' views on foreign policy would amount
to ``unilateral disarmament'' and called the Democratic platform
``the black hole of American politics.''
   Speaking to the G.I. Forum, a Hispanic veterans' group, the
Republican nominee-to-be said Dukakis had ``veered far outside the
mainstream'' bipartisan consensus formed after World War II _ a
consensus that believed ``it was America and only America that
could lead the world to freedom and peace.''
   ``His positions ... amount to a rejection of America's role as a
world leader and a repudiation of the Truman doctrine and the
vision of John Kennedy,'' Bush said.
   His speech came in the wake of the vice president's repeated
attempts this week to portray Dukakis as soft on foreign policy _
an area seen by Republican strategists as one in which the
Massachusetts governor is vulnerable.
   Bush cited Dukakis' support for a nuclear freeze, and opposition
to a new MX missile, the Midgetman missile and the Reagan
administration's proposed ``Star Wars'' nuclear defense system.
   Dukakis, campaigning in Mississippi, was asked by reporters if
he still supports a nuclear weapons freeze. ``Sure, and a
comprehensive test ban treaty,'' he said.
   Later, aboard his campaign plane, Dukakis said he originally
supported a nuclear freeze ``because we wanted to stop the
administration from expanding the arsenal.''
   ``Now, it's turned around and we're talking about reduction. I'm
for reductions now,'' he said. ``There are certain weapons systems
whose development I favor ... but there are also serious
negotiations under way. I'm for developing certain weapons systems
and for substantially reducing others.''
   Asked again if he was for a freeze, Dukakis said, ``No, I favor
the development of certain arms systems. I favor deep cuts in
strategic weapons systems.''
   Bush said Dukakis' views add up to no modernization of U.S.
forces ``and no modernization amounts to unilateral disarmament.''
   Dukakis called Bush's disarmament charge ``nonsense,'' and
added: ``We have a massive survivable nuclear deterrent right now,
12,000 strategic nuclear warheads. What we don't have is the kind
of strong conventional defense capability we must have and that is
going to be my top priority as president.''
   Bush said the Democratic platform is no help in trying to
determine where the Democratic presidential nominee stood on
foreign policy issues.
   ``The Democratic platform is the black hole of American
politics,'' he said. ``Issues get sucked into it and lost, never to
reappear again.''
   At an airport news conference, Bush was asked whether members of
his campaign staff had been advancing rumors concerning Dukakis'
mental health.
   ``I assume no one in my campaign is doing anything of that
kind,'' he said. ``I would thoroughly disapprove of it.''
   He also said President Reagan was ``broad-minded'' in retracting
his comment on Wednesday in which he referred to Dukakis as an
``invalid,'' and said the Massachusetts governor's ``response was
fine.''
   Meanwhile, Bush campaign staffers have been told to do nothing
to keep alive the rumors about Dukakis' mental health after Bush
himself wondered whether some of the information was coming from
his campaign, according to his chief of staff, Craig Fuller.
   ``He asked me the question,'' Fuller said. ``I have no reason to
believe we have any of our people behind it.''
   Fuller said Campaign Manager Lee Atwater gathered the Bush staff
together Wednesday ``and admonished everybody to stay out of this
story, stay out of the rumor business.''
   ``George Bush doesn't want us involved in that kind of a
story,'' Fuller said. ``One of the troublesome aspects of a
presidential campaign is that a rumor takes off and has a life of
its own. I don't know what the reality is but I figure it's up to
somebody else besides us to find out.''
   On another subject, Fuller confirmed that Treasury Secretary
James A. Baker III would resign his post to become chairman of the
Bush campaign before the start of the GOP convention on August 15.
   Baker's plans to join the campaign have been widely reported,
and previously confirmed by sources in both the Bush campaign and
the Reagan administration.
   Sources have said that Reagan would nominate New York investment
banker Nicholas Brady to serve out the remainder of Baker's term,
and that the announcement could come as early as Friday.
   However, Fuller said there still ``is no lock'' on the exact day
for Baker's job switch.
   At the news conference, Bush predicted that he would win Texas _
his adopted state _ despite the presence on the Democratic ticket
of vice presidential candidate Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas.
   ``The race is between George Bush and Michael Dukakis in
Texas,'' he said. ``I am going to spend what it takes and be here
as long as it takes to win Texas.''
   He said he hopes to win the Hispanic vote, even though he
doesn't speak Spanish as Dukakis and Bentsen do.
   ``It isn't whether you can speak Spanish, it's what is in your
heart,'' Bush said. ``He (Dukakis) can speak Spanish, but I have
the heartbeat.'' Bush then repeated his often-used reference to his
three grandchildren who are part Mexican-American.
   Bush later traveled to Chicago to attend the wake of the late
Aloysius Majewski, president of the National Polish Alliance,
before returning to Washington.
   ``He was an outstanding example for all of us,'' Bush told
reporters outside the funeral home in northwest Chicago. The vice
president refused to answer political questions, saying: ``I am
here to pay my respects to a great Polish-American. That's all I
want to say.''
</TEXT>
