<1ST_LINE>r p AM-JacksonVideo     08-04 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson Video,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jesse Jackson Testifies In Convention Speech Videotape Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former presidential hopeful Jesse Jackson
testified Thursday that his livelihood is being hurt by a company
selling videotapes of his speech at the Democratic National
Convention.
   Jackson has sued MPI Home Video of suburban Oak Forest to try to
halt sales and distribution of the tape, and he testified in
support of a request that the company be permanently barred from
distributing it.
   ``It has hurt the ability of my family to ... negotiate with a
distributor to sell my own words and image and likeness,'' Jackson
told U.S. District Judge James B. Zagel and about 100 spectators.
   ``It has reduced our ability to make a living off my work,'' he
said.
   The lawsuit charges MPI is exploiting Jackson's name, stature,
and literary, oratorical and creative skills, and it seeks to have
copies of the videotape destroyed.
   As the hearing closed, Zagel renewed a temporary order
prohibiting MPI from selling and distributing more of the tapes
until Aug. 12 and scheduled another hearing for Aug. 11.
   Jackson testified that he reaped $100,000 four years ago from
marketing a videotape of his speech to the 1984 Democratic National
Convention, and that MPI's distribution of this year's speech has
cut into its market potential.
   Lawyers for MPI contend that the convention speech was a news
event unprotected by copyright law and that MPI legitimately
purchased ABC-TV's coverage of the speech from the network for
$6,500.
   ``They are not pirates,'' attorney Robert Breisblatt said of MPI
after the hearing. ``They have a right to that tape.''
   The 60-minute tape, titled ``Jesse Jackson: We Can Dream
Again,'' is uncut ABC coverage, complete with commercials, he said.
   Jaffer Ali, vice president of marketing for MPI, a family-owned
business, has said previously that his company received 25,000
orders for the $14.95 videotape within 24 hours after it went on
the market.
   Ali has said the July 19 speech was ``a very special moment in
history'' and that he and his family decided to market it while
Jackson was delivering it.
   Jackson said he learned about the MPI venture four days later by
reading about it in a newspaper, and he called his lawyer to take
legal action.
   When Breisblatt asked Jackson if he had tried to contact Ali
before instituting legal action, Jackson replied, ``I felt too
insulted by the commercial exploitation of me.''
   During almost an hour on the witness stand, Jackson limited most
of his responses to brief answers, in contrast to his usually
expansive style, but his sense of humor edged in when Breisblatt
tried to place the address in the context of prime-time television.
   ``You understand what I mean by prime time?'' Breisblatt asked.
   ``When I speak,'' Jackson replied, prompting the courtroom to
erupt in laughter and even bringing a smile to Zagel's face.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
