<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Carlucci 1stLd-Writethru a0708 08-04 0781</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Carlucci, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0708,0801</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Defense Chief Says He and US Counterpart Are Friends</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 17th graf `The ship' to CORRECT ship's length to 613
feet, not yards.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOS12</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEVASTOPOL, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Defense Minister Dmitri T.
Yazov said Thursday he and Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci became
good friends during four days of talks and unprecedented tours of
secret Soviet military bases.
   The rotund, red-cheeked 64-year-old Soviet general was the
constant companion of Carlucci, 57, a career foreign service
officer.
   ``We parted not only as colleagues, but as good friends,'' Yazov
told reporters after a 46-mile drive with Carlucci over mountain
roads on the Crimean Peninsula from the navy's Black Sea port in
Sevastopol to an airport in the city of Simferopol.
   Yazov saw Carlucci and his advisers off on a flight over the
Black Sea to Turkey for talks with Turkish leaders and a visit to a
NATO base.
   Yazov, who first met Carlucci in Berne, Switzerland, in March
and then during the recent superpower summit in Moscow, said
increasing U.S.-Soviet military contacts ``contribute to lessening
tensions and strengthening peace.''
   The two discussed U.S. and Soviet military doctrines, imbalances
in each other's forces, and regional conflicts in the Persian Gulf,
Afghanistan and Southeast Asia, Yazov said. He did not elaborate.
   Carlucci said the two sides refined procedures for preventing
dangerous military incidents.
   The Soviets continued Thursday to provide the visiting Americans
access to their latest military hardware.
   Carlucci and accompanying U.S. Navy officers were allowed aboard
a missile cruiser replete with sophisticated electronic
communications and navigational equipment, and capable of carrying
nuclear weapons.
   The American defense chief spent 45 minutes inspecting
anti-submarine, navigational and missile-launching systems aboard
the cruiser Slava (Glory) docked at a civilian sea terminal on the
Bay of Sevastopol, the headquarters of the Soviet Black Sea fleet.
   It was the first time the Soviets have allowed Americans to
board the Slava, which is the prototype for a class of modern
Soviet missile cruisers. The Slava is the pride of the Black Sea
fleet as its most advanced warship.
   The Soviet chief of staff, Marshal Sergei F. Akhromeyev, toured
the aircraft carrier USS Theodore Roosevelt during a visit to the
United States last month.
   Carlucci, Yazov and the Black Sea fleet commander, Admiral
Mikhail N. Khronopulo, emerged from limousines and walked across a
gangway as a 20-member navy band played and 30 honor guards
carrying Kalashnikov submachine guns stood at attention on the
freshly painted deck.
   American and Soviet flags flying on the ship were dwarfed by a
crowded crop of antennas.
   Reporters and photographers were not allowed on the tour, but
watched from the dock as radar antennas twirled around and a 130mm
gun pivoted on its turret before Carlucci.
   ``It's obviously a very capable ship,'' Carlucci, a former
deputy chief of the CIA and ex-White House national security
adviser, told reporters at the Simferopol airport.
   The ship weighs 12,500 tons, is 613 feet long and can cruise at
up to 34 knots, according to Jane's Fighting Ships. It can fire 16
surface-to-surface cruise missiles with nuclear warheads and eight
surface-to-air missiles.
   Carlucci also turned his attention to the bloody military past
of the Crimea, occupied at various periods by the Turks, the
Russians and Nazi Germany. On Thursday, he stopped by a colorful
two-story indoor mural showing a June 6, 1855, battle during the
Crimean War between the Russians on one side and British, French
and Turkish forces on the other.
   He wound up his visit to the seaside city with a ceremony on a
downtown square. Dozens of sailors lined the square in 88-degree
heat as a navy band played ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' and the
Soviet national anthem.
   A few dozen of the town's 230,000 residents waved to Carlucci
and Yazov as their motorcade sped by.
   Carlucci was the first American official to visit Sevastopol
since President Franklin D. Roosevelt and a military delegation
stopped by in 1945 to view the city, which was heavily damaged
during the war. Roosevelt was in the area to attend a summit at the
Crimean city of Yalta with Josef Stalin and British Prime Minister
Winston Churchill.
   Because of the naval base, Sevastopol is off-limits to
foreigners and most Soviets.
   Carlucci told reporters he came away from his visit with new
respect for ``the professionalism of the Soviet military'' and a
better understanding of the Soviet armed forces.
   On Monday, he visited the Kubinka Air Force Base for the first
look at the top-secret Blackjack bomber ever allowed a Western
official, then watched over Soviet war games at the Taman motorized
rifle division base southwest of the capital.
</TEXT>
