<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 2156EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Thailand     08-04 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thailand,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chatichai Becomes New Thai Prime Minister</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOLLY YONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millionaire Chatichai Choonhavan, a
former army man and diplomat, became Thailand's first elected prime
minister in 12 years on Thursday and vowed to seek better relations
with communist Indochina next door.
   The 66-year-old businessman also told reporters he would
generally continue the economically oriented, pro-Western policies
of his predecessor, Prem Tinsulanonda. Chatichai was a deputy prime
minister under Prem.
   Prem, a former army commander in chief, held the prime
minister's post for eight years but belonged to no political party.
The 67-year-old Prem chose not to stay in office.
   Chatichai was nominated for the top government post by five
political parties who won a majority of seats in July 24
parliamentary elections and agreed to form a coalition government.
   The new prime minister said Thursday that a sixth party has been
added to the coalition, giving it 220 of the 357 seats in
Parliament.
   King Bhumibol Adulyadej, Thailand's constitutional monarch,
formally approved the nomination Thursday in a five-paragraph royal
decree, which a parliamentary official delivered to Chatichai on a
golden tray at his home.
   Chatichai said his Cabinet has been completed and will be
announced after Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain ends a
visit here next Tuesday.
   Chatichai leads the Chart Thai (Thai Nation) Party, which won
the most seats. The other coalition partners are the Social Action
Party, Democratic Party, Rassadorn (Citizens) Party, the United
Democracy Party, and the Muan Chon (Mass) Party.
   Asked by reporters about his foreign policy, Chatichai said:
``There will be changes where our neighbors are concerned. We want
Vietnam, Laos and Cambodia to be our markets, not our battlefield.''
   Thailand's relations with the three nations _ known collectively
as Indochina and once a French colony _ have been strained since
communist forces seized power there in 1975.
   Thailand has been in frequent border clashes with Laos and
Cambodia, and has backed guerrillas fighting Vietnamese occupation
of Cambodia. Few calls have been heard from top Thai officials to
soften Thailand's hardline stance.
   Chatichai also said the government will boost the nation's
minimum wage, now about $3 a day, and the incomes of the rural
population.
   Chatichai, a man with wide business experience, served as
ambassador in five countries from 1960-72, then was foreign
minister, industry minister and deputy prime minister. He helped
found Chart Thai and became its leader in 1986.
   Before Chatichai, Thailand's last elected prime minister was
Seni Pramoj in 1976.
   Analysts say Chatichai does not have strong ties with the
military, traditionally a key player in the rise and fall of
governments here.
   Chatichai also may face the same internal bickering and attacks
from increasingly vocal opposition parties that plagued Prem.
   Prem was Thailand's longest-serving civilian prime minister.
During his tenure, the nation experienced dynamic economic growth
and general political stability, despite two military coup attempts
and several changes of Cabinet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
