<DOCNO> AP880804-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 2205EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Guatemala     08-04 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Guatemala,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Detained in Reported Coup Plot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONSO ANZUETO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Vinicio Cerezo on Thursday said
three civilians were arrested in connection with a plot to
destabilize his government.
   In a brief statement, Cerezo said the three tried to involve
government officials in a plot ``to destabilize the democratic
system'' but gave no further details.
   The president identified the three as Guillermo Florian Crorado,
40; Alejandro Guzman Roman, 60; and Jose Martin Recinos de Zepeda,
43.
   Cerezo said the men were detained in Guatemala City, the
capital, and that the case was being referred to judicial courts.
He did not say what charges would be brought against them.
   Cerezo also announced that he would not attend the inauguration
of Ecuadoran President-elect Rodrigo Borja in Quito on Wednesday.
He cited pressing matters of economic policy for his decision to
remain in Guatemala.
   Earlier Thursday, army spokesman Col. Luis Arturo Isaacs
Rodriguez denied there had been any coup plot against the president.
   Rodriguez said in a telephone interview that Cerezo met with
Defense Minister Gen. Hector Alejandro Gramajo Morales on Thursday
but did not discuss any efforts to overthrow the government.
   The newspaper La Hora reported Thursday a coup attempt had been
broken up by the government on July 30. It said three people were
arrested in connection with the plot, but did not cite any sources
for the report.
   Rumors have circulated in the capital that the three civilians
approached several military officers to solicit their help in
overthrowing the government. Reports that the three belong to the
opposition right-ring National Liberation Movement could not be
independently confirmed.
   Army forces loyal to Cerezo's government quashed a coup attempt
on May 11 led by dissident officers in the divided military. Five
civilians and six military officers were charged in the attempt but
were later freed under an amnesty declared by the Congress.
   Cerezo, a lawyer and leader of the Christian Democratic Party,
was elected to a five-year term in November 1985. It was the first
election in 16 years in which the military did not field a
candidate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
