<2ND_LINE>AM-NIreland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0754,0657</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunmen Fire More Than 100 Bullets, Kill Two Maintenance Workers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with IRA claims
responsibility, newspaper says IRA may be trying to boost standing
after botched attacks. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four attackers fired more than
100 bullets at point-blank range and killed two men who worked at a
nearby police station, authorities said. The outlawed Irish
Republican Army claimed responsibility.
   The IRA said the men ignored IRA warnings against performing
maintenance or construction for police or the British army in
Northern Ireland.
   Its statement, sent to news organizations in Belfast, threatened
other civilians who do such work.
   The IRA, which is fighting to expel the British from the
province of Northern Ireland, earlier this week killed four members
of Britain's security forces _ three in attacks in Northern Ireland
and one in the bombing of an army barracks in north London. The
attacks injured 42 people.
   Thursday's victims, aged 60 and 64, had been doing maintenance
work at the Royal Ulster Constabulary station in Belleek, County
Fermanagh, near the border with the Irish Republic, police said.
The victims' names were not immediately released.
   The workers were driving in a van to their homes in County
Fermanagh. They had reached a crossroads about 30 yards from the
border when four men, dressed in combat gear and carrying rifles
and handguns, fired from a stolen car, police said.
   Police said up to 150 rounds were fired.
   The IRA's campaign to stop construction work for British
security forces began in August 1985 when a supplier of portable
structures to replace bombed buildings was shot and killed at his
home in Dublin, the Irish capital.
   Since then, several contractors have been killed.
   A Belfast newspaper said earlier Thursday that the upsurge in
IRA violence could signal the start of a yearlong campaign to mark
the 20th anniversary of the outbreak of sectarian and political
strife in Northern Ireland.
   The Irish News, read mainly by Roman Catholics and considered
authoritative on matters concerning the IRA, said the IRA hopes to
sway public opinion on the British mainland behind demands for
pulling British troops out of Northern Ireland.
   It said that as the 20th anniversary of the so-called
``troubles'' approaches, the IRA is determined to prove that
Britain has not succeeded in bringing peace to the province.
   ``The critical thing as far as the IRA is concerned is getting
the debate going _ the debate that will show the British presence
has failed,'' the paper quoted an unidentified nationalist source
as saying.
   The Irish News also said the campaign may be an IRA attempt to
re-establish its standing in staunchly Catholic areas after botched
attacks left 17 civilians dead since November.
   Edward McGrady, a lawmaker from the moderate Catholic Social
Democratic and Labor Party, suggested that the violence may stem
from an internal split on tactics between militants and more
politically minded members of the IRA.
   ``That may be one of the reasons for the increased violent
activity, the increased killings in England and in Ireland. There
could indeed be a division, an increasing division. The military,
the hawks in the group, are trying to sabotage any movement (toward
political reconciliation) taking place,'' he said in a British
Broadcasting Corp. radio interview.
   Britain ordered troops into the province Aug. 14, 1969, after
violence flared in Londonderry during a civil rights march by
Catholics. Since then, at least 2,665 people have died as a result
of sectarian and political fighting.
   The IRA wants to drive the British from Northern Ireland and
unite the predominantly Protestant province with the overwhelmingly
Catholic Republic of Ireland.
   Northern Ireland Secretary Tom King, the British Cabinet member
responsible for the province, has ordered a review of safety
measures for 17,000 police and part-time soldiers based there.
</TEXT>
