<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Deukmejian-Veep 2ndLd-Writethru a0751 08-04 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deukmejian-Veep, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0751,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deukmejian Says He `Cannot Be Considered' for GOP Veep Spot</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS new second graf to add comment from Bush chief of
staff Craig Fuller that campaign accepted Deukmejian's decision;
picks up 2nd pvs, Kevin Brett...Far East.
^With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California Gov. George Deukmejian said
Thursday in a letter to Republican George Bush that he ``cannot be
considered'' for the vice presidency because winning that election
would mean handing over the state's governorship to a Democrat.
   Bush Chief of Staff Craig Fuller said late Thursday that Bush
would respect Deukmejian's wishes, adding, ``He is going to be very
important to us in winning California.''
   Kevin Brett, Deukmejian's press secretary, said the governor
sent the letter to Bush from Seoul, Korea, the final stop in
Deukmejian's two-week trade mission to the Far East.
   Brett said the letter to the certain GOP presidential nominee
was prompted by a request from the Bush campaign for Deukmejian to
fill out financial disclosure forms that the campaign is seeking
from prospective running mates.
   Brett said Deukmejian also received telephone calls in the Far
East from Treasurer Secretary Jim Baker, who is soon to become
Bush's campaign chairman, and Bob Kimmitt, who is heading the
effort to screen vice presidential prospects.
   ``I am honored and very grateful for your consideration, but I
must tell you that I cannot be considered for the office of vice
president,'' Deukmejian said in his letter to Bush.
   ``As you know, if I were to assume the vice presidency, it would
mean turning the entire executive branch of the nation's most
populous state over to the Democratic Party,'' Deukmejian said,
noting that was something he could not consider doing.
   California Lt. Gov. Leo McCarthy, who is running this year for
the U.S. Senate, and the next four elected officials in the line of
succession for governor should Deukmejian give up the office, are
all Democrats.
   Deukmejian's term ends in 1990. Whoever is governor after that
will be in charge of the state during the congressional
reapportionment based on the 1990 census.
   Reapportionment, done every decade after the census, divides the
state into districts that must be equal in population but are
typically skewed in shape to protect incumbents and members of the
majority party.
   Brett released copies of the Deukmejian letter in Sacramento. He
said in addition to the letter, Deukmejian's chief of staff,
Michael Frost, telephoned Bush aides this morning on Air Force Two
to advise them that Deukmejian was taking himself out of
consideration.
   ``The governor is not going to complete the financial disclosure
forms,'' Brett said the chief of staff advised the Bush campaign.
   The comments in Deukmejian's letter are similar to his
often-repeated public statements that ``even if asked, I would have
to refuse'' the No. 2 spot on the ticket.
   Despite the denials, Deukmejian's name continues to appear on
lists of potential running mates. He is a Republican governor of
the nation's largest state, and has dropped hints that he might be
interested in the vice presidential post.
   Deukmejian first commented on his interest at a Texas GOP dinner
in May, saying that he was ``hoping that somebody might come along
and figure out a way I could be vice president and at the same time
(let) the Republicans hold onto control of the statehouse in
California.''
   Deukmejian fanned further speculation in early June when he
brushed aside a direct question about the vice presidency by joking
that his astrologer told him not to answer. A few days later, he
responded to the same question by saying, ``You should never say
never.''
</TEXT>
