<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Gulf 1stLd-Writethru a0800 08-04 0834</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Gulf, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0800,0853</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Secretary-General Says Iran, Iraq Both Accept Concept of Direct
Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to restore 1st lead and writethru designation.
New grafs 1-19 CORRECT that Iraq cool to plan but hasn't rejected
it, UPDATE with Perez de Cuellar's comments, report to Security
Council Friday, other. Picks up 14th graf pvs, No word .. .</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar said Thursday that both Iran and Iraq accept the concept of
face-to-face peace talks and the big question is when will they
take place.
   The issue of direct negotiations before a cease-fire has created
an impasse in talks aimed at ending the 8-year-old Persian Gulf
war. Iraq had demanded face-to-face talks before a cease-fire. Iran
said they can only take place afterward.
   ``The concept of direct talks is accepted by both sides, and the
matter is when,'' Perez de Cuellar told reporters Thursday as he
left U.N. headquarters. ``That is something on which I am working.''
   Diplomatic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
U.N. chief proposed to both sides that he announce a cease-fire
date and simultaneously invite both Iran and Iraq to hold direct
talks on a comprehensive peace treaty.
   Perez de Cuellar did not spell out his proposals for reporters
and said he has not yet received a formal response from Iraq.
Diplomatic sources have said Baghad is cool but stopped short of
outright rejection.
   Perez de Cuellar said Iran's response, although not formal, has
been ``constructive.''
   ``Unfortunately, from the Iraqi side, I have not received the
comments which I have asked for,'' Perez de Cuellar told reporters.
   The secretary-general received a report Thursday from a U.N.
military team on arrangements for a U.N.-supervised cease-fire in
the war. The contents were not disclosed, but the U.N. chief said
he would make a report to the Security Council in informal
consultations Friday.
   He said that next week, probably on Wednesday, he will deliver a
comprehensive report to the council on the entire situation
relating to declaration of a cease-fire, troop withdrawal, prisoner
exchange and other elements of a U.N. peace plan.
   It was not clear when he would declare what he calls a ``D-Day''
beginning a cease-fire, but he indicated he could make the
announcement next week.
   The cease-fire report was delivered by Lt. Gen. Martin Vadset,
the Norwegian head of the U.N. Truce Supervision Organization in
Jerusalem. He returned from a mission to Tehran and Baghdad, where
he studied arrangements for a U.N.-supervised truce.
   The sources said the secretary-general outlined his ideas for
ending the stalemate over direct talks during in a meeting with the
non-aligned members of the Security Council on Wednesday.
   The plan laid out before Argentina, Algeria, Nepal, Zambia,
Senegal and Yugoslavia, the non-aligned council members, was
disclosed as Perez de Cuellar met for more than an hour with
Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati of Iran. Velayati left without
making a comment.
   Under the secretary-general's plan, direct talks could start the
same day a cease-fire was announced, perhaps in a week or 10 days.
No dates have been set.
   It is one of the compromises Perez de Cuellar has weighed in
trying to close the gap between the Iranian and Iraqi positions.
Iraq says it needs the talks as a guarantee of sincerity from Iran,
which resisted U.N. peace efforts for a year and then suddenly
agreed to them last month.
   The sources said the secretary-general wants to secure the
commitment of Iran and Iraq to a comprehensive, sequential
implemention of Resolution 598, including a cease-fire, troop
withdrawal and repatriation of prisoners of war.
   Iraq also has been seeking the assurance of the five permanent
members of the 15-member Security Council to guarantee a
cease-fire. The five _ United States, Soviet Union, China, Britain
and France _ have been drafting a paper calling for direct talks
and appealing to both sides to bring a swift end to the conflict.
   Iraq says it fears Iran will seek only a temporary truce to
regroup forces, not a permanent peace, and so it wants some kind of
international underwriting of an agreement.
   Earlier Thursday, Iran urged the Security Council to condemn an
alleged Iraqi chemical attack in which it says 1,700 civilians were
injured. Iran says most of the casualties were women and children.
   No word emerged on whether the U.N. chief would send another
chemical weapons team to look into the latest allegation of Iraqi
atrocities in the war.
   A U.N. report released Monday concluded that Iraq had made
repeated and extensive use of the outlawed weapons. Iraq has
admitted using chemical weapons but denies the latest charge.
   In a letter Thursday, Velayati accused Iraq of ``blatant
disregard'' of the appeals made by the secretary-general and
Security Council for an end to chemical weapons use.
   He said that on Tuesday at 2:45 a.m. local time, Iraqi planes
dropped eight bombs containing mustard gas in Oshnaviyah, a town in
West Azerbaijan province.
</TEXT>
