<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 2254EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-Arias     08-04 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Arias,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arias Says Peace Plan Violators Should Be Punished</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Shultz</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Oscar Arias hinted
Thursday that he may seek Latin American support for a new
diplomatic and economic initiative against Nicaragua's leftist
Sandinista government _ ``the bad guys.''
   Speaking to a small group of foreign reporters in his office,
the Costa Rican leader said that Central American countries not in
compliance with his year-old peace plan ``should be punished.''
   Arias said he would not issue his own full assessment of the
peace plan until after he meets with fellow Latin American
presidents at the inauguration of Ecuador's president-elect,
Rodrigo Borja, in Quito next Wednesday.
   But he added, ``My new initiative is to convince the other
democracies that we must put pressure on the Sandinistas'' to
comply with the peace plan signed by Nicaragua and the other four
Central American nations on Aug. 7, 1987.
   Arias declined to elaborate.
   At the time the plan was signed, Arias said he would ask the
Organization of American States and the United Nations to apply
economic sanctions against any country later found not to be in
compliance. The plan was to have taken effect last November.
   The plan calls for talks aimed at ending civil wars in
Nicaragua, El Salvador and Guatemala and measures toward
democratization in all five countries. Arias won the 1987 Nobel
Peace Prize for authoring the plan.
   Arias acknowledged that none of the five countries, including
his own, is in full compliance, but reserved his strongest
criticism for Nicaragua. His words were couched in perhaps the
strongest language he has used against the Managua government to
date.
   ``The Sandinistas today are the bad guys, not the good guys,''
Arias said. ``They have unmasked themselves. They have proven to
the world that there is no political will in Managua (to comply
with the accord). They were not really honest when they committed
themselves to democratize and to advance toward a pluralistic
society.''
   Arias referred to the arrest last month of about 40
anti-Sandinista protesters; the temporary closing of the opposition
daily newspaper La Prensa and indefinite shutdown of the Roman
Catholic radio station, and the expulsion from Nicaragua of U.S.
Ambassador Richard Melton and seven other U.S. diplomats.
   Arias said he opposed any further U.S. military aid to the
rebels known as Contras who have been trying to overthrow the
Managua government for the past seven years. He said he had no
objections to humanitarian aid.
   But Arias said any Nicaraguan government ruled by the Contra
leadership would likely be as bad as the Sandinista regime. The
Contras ``are not part of the solution,'' he said, ``they are part
of the problem.''
</TEXT>
