<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Generally Higher In Thin Trading, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose slightly against all major
currencies except the British pound in late-morning trading today
in Europe. Gold prices were mixed.
   Foreign exchange dealers in Milan said the market remained
essentially bullish on the dollar but predicted no major change in
its position until Friday's release of the U.S. unemployment rate
for July.
   One trader said he expected the unemployment rate to rise to 5.4
percent from 5.3 percent in June, but said that would still
represent a very low jobless rate and proof of the current strength
of the U.S. economy.
   ``Think back to the dire predictions about a recession made in
the October (stock market) crash. It makes you appreciate how well
the U.S. economy is doing now,'' the trader said.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar fell 0.10 yen to a closing 132.75 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted higher at 132.93 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday's
rates, included: 1.8759 West German marks, up from 1.8755; 1.5645
Swiss francs, up from 1.5635; 6.3255 French francs, up from 6.3235;
2.1163 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1150; 1,383.65 Italian lire, up
from 1,382.00; 1.2040 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2020.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.7125 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.7090 late
Wednesday.
   Bullion dealers said gold and silver were trading in a narrow
range with no apparent direction.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $433.60 a troy ounce, up
from late Wednesday's $432.25. At midmorning today, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $433.40.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $433.60, down from $434.00 late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.67 to close at a bid $435.34.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.86 a troy
ounce, down from Wednesday's $6.88.
</TEXT>
