<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged down against the yen today in
Tokyo, while share prices closed lower in moderate trading.
   The dollar opened at 132.75 yen, eased in slack, tight-ranged
dealings before edging up to close at the day's high of 132.75 yen,
down 0.10 yen from Wednesday's finish.
   Spot trading totaled a thin $1.98 billion, down from Wednesday's
$2.72 billion.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost
17.88 points Wednesday, shed 55.79 points, or 0.20 percent, closing
at 28,292.66. Declining issues outpaced advancers 524 to 343, while
177 others remained unchanged.
   Volume in the first section was a moderate 800 million shares,
unchanged from Wednesday's total.
   Share prices firmed in early trading but fell back in the
afternoon when oil shares, higher at the end of the morning session
on a flurry of merger rumors, yielded most of their gains, dealers
said.
   Financial issues also fell, dragging down the index, they added.
   Rumors of tightened margin trading requirements sidelined some
investors, said a dealer at a major securites firm.
   ``If the exchange tightens control on margin trading, prices of
large-capital shares, which have been leading the market in recent
days, are bound to decline,'' he said, speaking anonymously.
   Foreign exchange dealers said they expect the U.S. unemployment
rate for July, scheduled for release Friday, to remain around 5.3
percent, the June level which was the lowest since May 1974.
   If the unemployment figure falls, it would boost the dollar,
they said.
</TEXT>
