<HEAD>London Shares Slightly Higher At Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were slightly higher on London's
Stock Exchange around midday Thursday in narrow, featureless
trading, with many players absent due to the summer holiday season.
   Dealers said the market's near-term direction was uncertain,
with the few players left in the market adopting a wait-and-see
attitude, probably until Friday's release of U.S. jobless data for
July.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 3.1
points, or 0.2 percent, at 1,868.2 at about 12:15 p.m., its best
level for the day.
   The index opened little changed and then moved down as much as
1.5 points to its lowest level of the day before climbing into
positive territory.
   Volume was a scant 269.8 million shares, compared with 244.8
million shares at the same time Wednesday.
   Dealers said the New York market's performance Wednesday, which
saw the Dow Jones industrial average advance only 2.85 points to
2,134.07, gave little direction for the London market.
