<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 0923EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Racketeering-WallStreet     08-04 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Racketeering-Wall Street,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspapers Report Wall Street Indictments Near</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government is on the verge of
issuing racketeering indictments against a senior employee and a
former employee of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., as well as several
employees of a New Jersey investment firm, according to published
reports today.
   The reports in the Wall Street Journal and the Baltimore Sun
said attorneys for the likely defendants characterize the charges
as largely technical and based on an unprecedented use of the
Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act.
   The attorneys told the Sun that prosecutors are trying to coerce
testimony against ``bigger fish'' at Goldman Sachs & Co. and
Drexel, firms with which the New Jersey firm, Princeton-Newport
Partners L.P., had dealings.
   Princeton-Newport, based in Princeton, N.J., and Newport Beach,
Calif., specializes in hedge transactions, aimed at profiting from
the spreads in the prices of convertible stocks and debentures.
   The Journal identified one of those expected to be indicted as
James Sutton Regan, a general managing partner of
Princeton-Newport, along with three or four general partners. It
quoted Regan's lawyer, Theodore Wells, as saying his client is
innocent and will vigorously contest any charges that may be filed.
   The Journal said two people employed at Drexel at the time of
the transactions are also expected to be charged: Bruce Newberg, a
former trader in Drexel's Beverly Hills, Calif., office who
recently left the firm, and Cary Maltausch, a current employee of
Drexel's New York office.
   Spokesmen for Princeton-Newport and Drexel were said to be in
meetings Thursday morning and not immediately available for comment.
   If the grand jury votes an indictment, Princeton-Newport would
be the first securities firm ever charged as a racketeering
enterprise, but would probably not itself be named as a defendant,
the Journal said.
   Drexel itself is not expected to be charged with any wrongdoing,
the Journal said. Drexel's junk bond division, which has
revolutionized Wall Street in the 1980s by dramatically increasing
the reach and implications of corporate debt, has been the focus of
extensive government probes.
   The indictment reflects a significant escalation in tactics used
by the government to prosecute Wall Street executives.
   Under the criminal RICO law, passed in 1970 to combat organized
crime and drugs, a person or business that commts two or more
felonies as part of a pattern can be charged with racketeering.
   The law carries severe penalties, including as much as 20 years
in prison and the confiscation of property and earnings, even if
they are unrelated to wrongdoing.
   ``The Department of Justice is threatening to chop off feet to
get what they want, regardless of whether it's true,'' Paul Grand,
attorney for Charles Zarvecki, general partner and head of trading
of Princeton-Newport, told the Sun.
   ``Rudolph Giuliani (the U.S. attorney for the Southern District
of New York) believes the threat of racketeering charges is so
potent that its use will bring anyone to his knees.''
   The Sun said the case centers on three charges.
   The first involves complex tax issues arising out of the hedging
techniques used by Princeton-Newport. Specifically, it concerns how
losses were recognized.
   The second revolves around alleged ``parking'' in Mattel stock.
In 1984, Princeton-Newport bought a position from Drexel of between
0.5 percent and 1 percent of the Southern California toymaker's
stock, which it sold back to Drexel in 1985. Stock parking is when
one holds a stock for another to conceal the true ownership.
   The third charge is likely to be based on the contention that at
the behest of Drexel employees, Princeton-Newport tried to
manipulate the price of C.O.M.B., a company that deals in
distressed merchandise.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880804-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 0951EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-FordSpending     08-04 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ford Spending,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Official Says Automaker Modernizing 15 Plants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRAVERSE CITY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. will spend nearly
$3.5 billion to modernize 15 North American assembly and
manufacturing plants and may build new plants as part of an
expanded product investment plan, Ford Vice Chairman Harold A.
Poling says.
   ``We are building on our product successes and following a
strategy of step-by-step improvements at existing facilities,''
Poling said Wednesday at the University of Michigan's Management
Briefing Seminars.
   He said the company will decide by the end of the year whether
demand for its vehicles justifies adding new plants.
   Ford has sought to conserve cash and cultivate employee goodwill
in the past five years by renovating existing facilities rather
than building at new, empty, ``green field'' locations.
   ``But when you've reached a point where you see a sustained
demand for your products above that which you could provide on the
basis that we've been providing, then you've got to consider a
green field site,'' Poling said. ``And we will; we're looking at
it.''
   The improvements are part of a worldwide five-year investment
plan that will see the automaker spend significantly more than the
$16.6 billion spent during the previous five-year period, Poling
said.
   Eight of the 15 improvements under way or scheduled to begin
this year are at plants in Michigan. Scheduled to be modernized
are: Livonia transmission; Dearborn assembly, Romeo engine; Wayne
stamping, assembly and the truck plant; Wixom assembly; and
Ypsilanti.
   Other plants to be updated are: St. Louis assembly; Louisville
assembly; Buffalo, N.Y., stamping Plant; Lorain, Ohio, assembly;
Walton Hills, Ohio, stamping; Sharonville, Ohio; and Connersville,
Ind.
   ``We believe our modernized plants are state-of-the-art, and we
are gaining productivity advantages with very efficient
investment,'' Poling said.
   Since introducing its 1985 models, Ford has increased its annual
North American assembly capacity by 500,000 units. Greater line
speeds, additional work shifts and the upgrading of equipment
contributed to the increase in productivity, Poling said.
   Ford reported record profits of $1.66 billion in the second
quarter of 1988, company officials said.
   Poling said investment alone is not the way to make sure profits
increase, adding that the automaker must also follow a three-part
agenda.
   ``One, and this can never be overemphasized, we must continue to
focus on the basics. Two, we must accept change and deal with it in
new, more imaginative and more efficient ways. And three, our
industry and government must work more cooperatively and
effectively to achieve mutual goals,'' Poling said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
