<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-BritishAirways 1stLd-Writethru   08-04 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-British Airways, 1st Ld-Writethru,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Airways Profit Down 9 Percent in First Quarter</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS lede to ADD time element; picks up 2nd graf pvs bg'ng,
British Airways' ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Airways PLC said Thursday its
first-quarter profit fell 9 percent from a year earlier, hurt by
its acquisition of loss-making British Caledonian Airways.
   British Airways' net profit for the first quarter of its fiscal
year, ended June 30, fell to 53 million pounds, or about $91
million, from 58 million pounds, or about $99 million. Per-share
profit declined to 7.4 pence, or about 13 cents, from 8.1 pence, or
14 cents.
   Revenue rose 13 percent _ to 1.02 billion pounds, or around $1.7
billion, from 900 million pounds, or $1.5 billion.
   The results, while lower than those for the previous fiscal
year, exceeded most analysts' expectations.
   British Airways shares were trading at 159 pence, or $2.72, up 2
pence, on the London Stock Exchange at mid-morning.
   Results for British Caledonian, which British Airways acquired
for 253 million pounds, or around $433 million, in April, were
included in the latest quarter's figures, but not in those of the
previous year.
   British Caledonian posted losses in its final years as an
independent airline. British Airways, which was recently privatized
by the government, is expected to take some time to return those
operations to profitability.
   Passenger loads on former British Caledonian flights are still
well below British Airways' standards, said Lord King, chairman of
British Airways.
   For the combined company, average passenger load factor, or the
percentage of seats filled, dropped to 66.2 percent from 71.4
percent.
   ``British Airways' performance has been close to target and
within the (former British Caledonian) operational area we have
taken a firm control of costs,'' King said.
   Analysts said they expect the benefits of acquiring British
Caledonian's routes to be reflected in British Airways' earnings
next year.
</TEXT>
