<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Toyota-Philippines     08-04 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Toyota-Philippines,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toyota in Joint Venture in Philippines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toyota Motor Corp., Japan's largest automaker, said
it has set up a joint venture in the Philippines that will produce
6,000 passenger cars a year by 1990.
   A Toyota official said Thursday that Toyota Motor Philippines
Corp. has been created in Manila, the Philippines capital. The new
company has total capital of 220 million Philippine pesos, or about
$9.8 million. It is owned 60 percent by a group led by Metropolitan
Bank and Trust Co. of the Philippines, 25 percent by Toyota and 15
percent by Mitsui and Co., a leading Japanese trading company.
   ``An early production start-up date is hoped for, however at
present it has not yet been set,'' the Toyota official said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The new company has purchased an idle plant of the former Delta
Motor Co., a Philippine automaker, from the Manila government for
130 million pesos, or about $5.9 million. It plans to equip the
facility with Toyota's modern production equipment, the official
said.
   He said the joint venture has a production target of 500
passenger cars a month by 1990 and plans eventually to make
commercial vehicles at the Manila plant.
</TEXT>
