<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ChryslerContract     08-04 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chrysler Contract,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler Contract Called Precedent-Setting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A union leader says the International Union
of Electronics Workers and Chrysler Corp.'s Acustar Division have
reached a precedent-setting contract that calls for job security
and a new plant in the Dayton area.
   The statement released this morning by Wes Wells, president of
IUE Local 775, provided few details. It said the five-year contract
would be signed later today, subject to ratification by the local's
members Friday.
   The Dayton Acustar plant, which makes heating and cooling
products, employs approximately 2,000 people.
   Wells said that if the contract is ratified it will provide for
the future job security of the Dayton plant.
   His statement said the Dayton plant would receive ``preferential
provider corporate status'' that would give it the edge over other
suppliers in providing new parts for Chrysler.
   The agreement also calls for a second Acustar plant to be
located in the Dayton area, the statement said. No details were
provided on possible employment or production capabilities for such
a plant.
   Local 775 will have exclusive bargaining rights at the new
plant, the statement said.
</TEXT>
