<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Sharply Higher On Dry Forecast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened sharply higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade in reaction to the National
Weather Service's forecast for hot, dry conditions in the Midwest
during most of next week.
   Reports of some new wheat sales to China and India added support
to the wheat market in early trading, analysts said.
   Traders shrugged off predictions of scattered showers today and
Friday in the Farm Belt, where drought-stressed soybean crops are
struggling to produce and fill bean pods.
   The precipitation is expected to come from the same storm system
that dropped widely varying amounts of rain Wednesday in southern
Minnesota and northern Iowa.
   ``It's not going to rain all that much, maybe a quarter-inch to
an inch with about 40 percent coverage, so most places won't get
any rain,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader for Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc.
   Traders focused on the weather service's latest 6-to-10 day
forecast for above-normal temperatures and below-normal rainfall in
the Midwest during the five days beginning Tuesday.
   In early trading, wheat was 5{ cents to 7 cents higher with
September at $3.86 a bushel; corn was 3{ cents to 6{ cents higher
with September at $3.03{ a bushel; oats were 5{ cents to 7 cents
higher with September at $2.90{ a bushel; soybeans were 11 cents to
19{ cents higher with August at $8.55 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .20 cent lower to .20 cent higher with August
at 66 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .35 cent lower
with August at 78.30 cents a pound; hogs were .55 cent lower to .08
cent higher with August at 44.70 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .15 cent to 1.62 cents lower with August at 31.85 cents a
pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on Wednesday.
Only hog futures were lower.
</TEXT>
