<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 1240EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Bonds     08-04 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bonds,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices were higher in mostly quiet trading
early today, as the market awaited Friday's government report on
the nation's unemployment in July.
   The Treasury's closely watched 30-year bond was up ] point, or
$3.75 for every $1,000 in face value, by midday. Its yield, which
moves inversely to its price and is often an indicator of interest
rate trends, fell to 9.04 percent from 9.06 percent late Wednesday.
   Analysts said bond prices were lifted on a wave of buying early
in the trading session.
   ``We had a big flurry for the first 10 minutes and we've been
asleep ever since,'' said Jay Goldinger, a principal of Capital
Insight Inc., an investment firm in Beverly Hills, Calif.
   Many investors were caught short after selling bonds Wednesday
on speculation that the jobless report for July would show a strong
growth in the number of employed, analysts said.
   Higher employment tends to depress bond prices because it
implies a stronger economy, rising wages, greater demand for credit
and inflation, which erodes the value of fixed-income securities.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
government issues edged up 1-32 point to 1-16 point, intermediate
maturities rose 1-16 point to 5-32 point, and 20-year issues gained
5-16 point, according to data provided by Telerate Inc., a
financial information service.
   The movement of a point equals a change of $10 in the price of a
bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, was up 1.59 at 1,143.05.
   In corporate trading, industrial bonds rose. Moody's Investment
Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures price movements on 80
corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, edged up
0.71 to 285.04.
   Three-month Treasury bills, meanwhile, slipped 1 basis point to
a discounted rate of 6.86 percent and a yield of 7.07 percent.
Six-month bills declined 2 basis points to a discounted rate of
7.07 percent and a yield of 7.42 percent, while one-year bills were
down 1 basis point at 7.29 percent to yield 7.81 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted at 7} percent, up from 711-16 percent late
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
