<DOCNO> AP880804-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 1452EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Chubb-DroughtInsurance Bjt   08-04 0708</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chubb-Drought Insurance, Bjt,0727</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chubb Buys Newspaper Ad in Drought Insurance Controversy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELANIE MADER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chubb Group of Insurance Cos. purchased
newspaper advertising space across the nation Thursday to repeat
its denial that it reneged on a drought insurance offer to farmers
in the parched Midwest.
   Chubb said it is cooperating with state officials investigating
complaints stemming from a dispute in which its Warren-based
subsidiary, Federal Insurance Co., is accused of backing off a
promise tn issue policies that pay off if rainfall is below a
certain level.
   ``Recently, because of issues related to the `rain insurance'
controversy, our reputation has been under public attack for the
first time in our history,'' said Chubb's full-page advertisement
that ran in more than 30 newspapers and various publications around
the country.
   Chubb says the policies were sold through an agent for Federal
Insurance, and expected they would offer about $30 million in total
coverage. But the agent, Good Weather International, received more
than 8,700 applications for drought coverage totalling $370 million.
   Chubb's ad details how the controversy developed and said a
flood of 6,000 applications in the final days of the enrollment
period exceeded the amount of policies it wanted to sign. As a
result, the company said it could not fill all the applications.
   ``We said that applications were not binding on Chubb until
accepted, and that premiums must be submitted with applications
because of the short-term nature of the policy,'' Chubb's ad says.
   ``It's not unusual in the agricultural business for applications
to accompany a premium check because of the short duration of the
coverage,'' said Mary Lu Korkuch, a company spokeswoman. ``It's not
like homeowners insurance, which is a continuous renewal type of
policy.''
   Farmers in 10 states _ Ohio, Minnesota, Indiana, Iowa, Illinois,
Kentucky, Michigan, Missouri, Tennessee and Wisconsin _ applied for
the insurance as they contend with one of the worst dry spells in
history. Some have filed lawsuits against the company over the
disputed insurance, and state officials also have threatened legal
action.
   ``Unfortunately, much of what you may have read or seen about
Chubb and `rain insurance' in recent weeks is misleading and a lot
is simply wrong,'' the ad says. ``Because that information goes
directly to our reputation for keeping our word, which is
fundamental to the product we sell, we must set the record
straight.''
   Chubb had spoken with 5,000 farmers as of early Thursday and had
plans to talk with the other 3,711 who applied for the insurance by
the end of the week, Ms. Korkuch said.
   ``Out of 5,000, there have been five people who have refused to
deal with us. ... Of course, we're very encouraged by that,'' she
said.
   After talking with state insurance commissioners, Chubb
announced in mid-May that it would issue a total of $40 million in
drought coverage, $10 million more than it had initially planned.
   But that was expected to cover only 10 percent, or about 800, of
the farmers who had applied, the company said. Six-thousand others,
who did not receive coverage, would get twice the amount of their
premium returned, Chubb has said.
   So far, 600 policies have been issued, and 70 farmers have asked
for the double premium payment, Ms. Korkuch said.
   G. Terry Van Gilder, deputy chief underwriting officer for the
group, told a state insurance hearing Wednesday in Ohio that Chubb
didn't realize Good Weather oversold Chubb's drought insurance
until one day before the deadline for applications.
   Chubb said in its newspaper ads that its decision to return
premiums ``was made as soon as we knew how oversubscribed Good
Weather's program was.''
   The advertisement offered no new proposals from the company, but
said, ``We intend to continue to deal fairly and responsibly with
the farmers involved.''
   Ms. Korkuch said the company based this year's total coverage
estimate on last year's application response. Chubb received 1,000
applications and issued $5 million in coverage in 1987, the first
year the drought insurance was offered, she said.
   Chubb had sold $15 million in drought coverage _ one-half of its
maximum for the insurance _ by June 12, but the amount applied for
had risen to $370 million three days later, Van Gilder said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
