<DOCNO> AP880804-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 1610EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FCC-Cable-Networks     08-04 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FCC-Cable-Networks,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FCC Proposes Eliminating Network-Cable Cross-Ownership Ban</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission on
Thursday revived a proposal to allow national television networks
to own cable TV systems.
   The FCC originally proposed eliminating the network-cable
cross-ownership rule in 1982, but never acted on the plan.
   The rule was adopted in 1970, when the cable TV industry was in
its infancy, because of fears that the TV networks would buy up
cable systems and control their programming.
   The FCC noted that a report by the Commerce Department's
National Telecommunications Information and Administration in June
recommended the rule be abolished. The report said the TV networks'
influence has diminished significantly since the rule was adopted.
   The agency's three sitting commissioners voted unanimously to
seek comment again on the proposal to update the record so the
agency can consider eliminating the rule. But one commissioner
expressed reservations.
   Commissioner James H. Quello said he feared that without rules
requiring cable systems to carry local broadcast signals, a
network-owned cable system could disadvantage the local competition
by dropping the stations from its cable menu.
   Chairman Dennis R. Patrick said he doubted that a network-owned
cable system would risk alienating viewers by dropping a popular
channel from its line-up. ``It would be an economic disincentive,''
he said.
   James P. Mooney, president of the National Cable Television
Association, said the commission's proposal to eliminate the rule
is ``reasonable'' because conditions have changed so much since
1970.
   The FCC also proposed scrapping a rule that limits the term of
affiliation agreements between networks and stations to a maximum
of two years.
   This rule was adopted nearly 50 years ago for the radio industry
and then applied to TV in 1945 as a way to assist new networks in
gaining access to broadcast outlets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880804-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 1515EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-TradeBill-Reax 1stLd-Writethru   08-04 0743</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade Bill-Reax, 1st Ld-Writethru,0769</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Partners Say New Bill Will Harm International Trade</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Grafs 1-5 new to specify differences from previous trade bill
and add U.S. accusations of protectionism; picks up 4th graf pvs,
In the ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM COHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A major trade bill awaiting President Reagan's signature was
labeled protectionist on Thursday by several of America's leading
trade partners, who warned that the legislation could harm
international relations.
   The Senate approved the bill Wednesday by an 85-11 vote. The
measure, aimed at reviving U.S. competitiveness abroad, cleared the
House of Representatives earlier, and President Reagan has
indicated he will sign it.
   Reagan vetoed a previous version of the bill in part because it
contained a controversial plant-closing notification requirement.
Earlier this week Reagan decided not to veto a separate
plant-closing bill.
   Major U.S. trading partners stated their opposition to the trade
bill's provision that would make it easier for the U.S. government
to impose import curbs in retaliation for alleged unfair trading
practices by other nations.
   Many of the nations that complained the bill is protectionist
are accused by the United States of being protectionist themselves
for using high tariffs, quotas or other barriers to imports.
   In the Far East, where the reaction was mostly negative, the
leaders of Japan and South Korea urged Reagan to veto the bill.
   Japanese Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita said, ``I think it's
unfortunate, because (the bill contains) protectionist overtones.''
   Trade Minister Hajime Tamura said Japan would monitor
implementation of the bill to ensure it did not violate
international trade regulations.
   Although the United States has registered trade deficits with
each of East Asia's most powerful economies _ Japan, South Korea,
Taiwan and Hong Kong _ its biggest concern lies with Japan. Last
year, $60 billion of the $170 billion U.S. trade deficit lay with
Japan, which has been the target of previous retaliatory sanctions.
   South Korea's Foreign Ministry issued a statement saying it
deeply regretted the bill's passage and called for its elimination.
   ``It is the strong hope ... that the U.S. administration will
once again demonstrate its firm commitment to free trade by taking
appropriate measures not to allow such a protectionist bill to be
enacted,'' the ministry said.
   Taiwan's Board of Foreign Trade said it was ``gravely
concerned'' because the bill ``indicates the United States is going
to move away from free trade and move to the practice of
protectionism.''
   The bill extended the definition of unfair trade to the areas of
exchange rate, trade surplus, labor rights and copyright
violations, the statement said.
   In Europe, West Germany's economics minister, Martin Bangemann,
said the bill ``could turn out to be a strong burden on free
international trade.''
   He appealed to the Reagan administration to implement the
policies outlined in the trade bill ``with as much restraint as
possible.''
   Even before the Senate vote, Britain's Financial Times said in
an editorial that ``trading partners of the United States have
reason to be nervous.''
   ``In their future dealings with the U.S. administration, they
will almost certainly have to accept that it is armed with a tough
new mandate to promote U.S. exports by systematically forcing open
foreign markets under threat of sanctions,'' the newspaper said.
   The British government had no immediate comment.
   Only officials in Hong Kong officials took a more positive view.
   Tony Miller, Hong Kong's acting trade director, said the British
colony welcomed the bill ``to the extent that (it) will reduce some
of the pent-up protectionist pressures in Congress.''
   But Hong Kong officials also expressed concern about a provision
calling for an investigation into unfair trade practices by foreign
nations.
   The bill also would bar Japan's Toshiba Corp. from selling goods
to the U.S. government for three years as a penalty for a
subsidiary's export of high-technology milling machines to the
Soviet Union.
   The 50 percent-owned subsidiary, Toshiba Machine Co., also would
be prohibited from selling products commercially in the United
States for the same period.
   Joichi Aoi, president of Toshiba Corp., said it was unacceptable
that the U.S. government planned to punish a foreign company that
had not violated any American laws.
   A company spokesman also quoted Aoi as saying it was improper
for the United States to impose a punishment for a past event with
a new law.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, estimated
Toshiba Corp. would suffer direct losses of about $50 million a
year, while indirect damage would be ``substantial.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880804-0183 </DOCNO>
