<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybean Futures Close Sharply Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures closed sharply higher
Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade on prospects for continued
hot, dry weather in the drought-stricken Farm Belt.
   Wheat and oat futures also advanced but not as strongly as corn
and soybeans, which soared their permitted daily limits late in the
session before profit-taking trimmed the gains, analysts said.
   The markets had opened higher in reaction to the National
Weather Service's 6-to-10-day forecast for above-normal
temperatures and below-normal rainfall next week in the Midwest,
where stunted soybean plants are struggling to produce and fill
bean pods.
   Morning forecasts for scattered showers late Thursday and Friday
had kept tight reins on the early rally.
   But at midday some private meteorologists reduced the amount of
rain in their near-term forecasts, triggering an explosion in
demand for corn and soybean contracts.
   ``The main influence was those weather forecasts for the next
few days,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader for Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc.
   At the close, wheat was 1 cent to 4\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.82{ a bushel; corn was {
cent lower to 7 cents higher with September at $3.04{ a bushel;
oats were 2{ cents to 4 cents higher with September at $2.86 a
bushel; and soybeans were 7{ cents to 27{ cents higher with August
at $8.63 a bushel.
</TEXT>
