<1ST_LINE>u f AM-PCSoftware     08-04 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PC Software,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Personal Computer Software Business Booming, Survey Finds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of personal computer software roared ahead
50.3 percent in the second quarter of 1988, belying beliefs that
the industry's growth is dwindling, according to an industry
group's survey released Thursday.
   Sales in North America totaled $922 million in the three-month
period, up from $614 million in the same period a year earlier,
said the Software Publishers Association.
   ``People have alleged that the PC software industry is maturing,
but this data, which surprised ... me, shows that it's nowhere near
maturing,'' said Kenneth Wasch, executive director of the
Washington-based trade group.
   For the first six months of 1988, sales rose 50.5 percent to
$1.82 billion from $1.21 billion a year earlier.
   The results are based on an analysis of confidential sales
figures submitted voluntarily to the accounting firm of Arthur
Andersen & Co. by most of the major companies in each market
segment. Sales of some medium-sized and smaller companies are
estimated.
   Sales of software for Apple Computer Inc.'s Macintosh grew most
rapidly, nearly tripling to $109 million from $39 million a year
earlier. In contrast, sales of software for the Apple II fell 5.4
percent to $37 million from $39 million.
   In the biggest segment, software for both generations of
International Business Machines Corp.'s personal computers and
compatible machines, sales rose 40.8 percent in the second quarter
to $702 million from $499 million a year earlier.
   There was a 10.6 percent decline in sales of software for
Commodore Ltd.'s 64 and 128 computers, to $20.6 million from $23.1
million.
</TEXT>
