<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     08-04 0779</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybeans, Corn Soar On Dry Weather Forecasts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices rose sharply Thursday on the
Chicago Board of Trade on prospects for continued hot, dry weather
in the drought-stricken Farm Belt.
   Wheat and oat futures also advanced but not as strongly as corn
and soybeans, which soared their permitted daily limits late in the
session before profit-taking trimmed the gains, analysts said.
   On other markets, cattle futures were up sharply while pork
futures were mixed; orange juice futures surged; coffee sank;
precious metals and energy were mixed; and stock-index futures
retreated.
   The grain markets opened higher in response to the National
Weather Service's 6-to-10-day forecast for above-normal
temperatures and below-normal rainfall next week in the Midwest,
where stunted soybean plants are struggling to produce and fill
bean pods.
   The rally was held in check, though, by morning forecasts for
scattered showers late Thursday and Friday.
   But at midday some private meteorologists reduced the amount of
rain in their short-term forecasts, triggering a buying explosion
in the corn and soybean pits.
   ``Everything took off with a big bang,'' said Jerry Gidel, an
analyst with the G.H. Miller Division of LIT America Inc.
   ``The main influence was those weather forecasts for the next
few days,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader for Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc.
   Lespinasse said the trading floor was abuzz with talk of reduced
harvest prospects for soybeans, and Gidel said field observers were
reporting further deterioration in the hard-hit corn crop after
five straight days of hot, dry weather.
   An Agriculture Department crop production report scheduled for
release next Thursday is expected to confirm that crop conditions
worsened during July.
   Wheat settled 1\ cents to 2 cents higher with the contract for
delivery in September at $3.82{ a bushel; corn was { cent lower to
7\ cents higher with September at $3.04{ a bushel; oats were 3
cents to 4 cents higher with September at $2.86{ a bushel; and
soybeans were 5 cents to 27 cents higher with August at $8.62{ a
bushel.
   Cattle futures surged on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange with
the October live-cattle contract up the 1.50-cents-a-pound daily
limit in reaction to strong cash prices for fed cattle, analysts
said.
   ``The packers would certainly like to be able to buy cattle
cheaper, but the feedyards are really digging in their heels and
not wanting to sell cattle at lower prices,'' said Charlie
Richardson, an analyst in Denver with Lind-Waldock & Co.
   Further support stemmed from expectations that the USDA's
monthly cattle-on-feed report will show heavy marketing activity
and a slowdown in feedlot placements last month, Richardson said.
That report will be released Aug. 15.
   Hog futures were narrowly mixed while frozen pork bellies swung
lower.
   Live cattle were .40 cent to 1.50 cents higher with August at
67.27 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .70 cent to 1.32 cents
higher with August at 79.50 cents a pound; hogs were .50 cent lower
to .45 cent higher with August at 44.77 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were unchanged to 1.55 cents lower with August at 31.92
cents a pound.
   Frozen concentrated orange juice for September delivery soared 6
cents a pound on the New York Cotton Exchange in a technical rally
sparked by the contract's opening at $1.905, three-tenths of a cent
above the previous contract high of $1.902, analysts said.
   Tight supplies of Brazilian orange juice continue to provide
fundamental support to the market, said Judith Ganes, an analyst in
New York with Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
   The September orange juice contract settled at $1.950.
   Coffee futures retreated in profit-taking on New York's Coffee,
Sugar & Cocoa Exchange, said Bert Ruiz, coffee broker for Balfour
Maclaine Corp. in New York.
   Coffee for September delivery settled 1.63 cents lower at
$1.1657 a pound.
   Gold futures were nearly unchanged while silver prices rose
slightly in quiet trading on New York's Commodity Exchange.
   Gold settled 50 cents lower to 10 cents higher with August at
$433.40 a troy ounce; silver was 1.4 cents to 2 cents higher with
August at $6.855 a troy ounce.
   Energy futures finished mostly lower on technical factors on the
New York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 11 cents to 23 cents
lower with September at $15.03 a barrel; heating oil was .24 cent
to .50 cent lower with September at 42.46 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .29 cent lower to .30 cent higher with September at
44.95 cents a gallon.
   Stock-index futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for September delivery of the Standard
& Poor's 500 index settled 1.20 points lower at 272.85.
</TEXT>
