<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 1817EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-InsiderTrading     08-04 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Insider Trading,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Approves Insider Trading Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel approved legislation Thursday
increasing the penalties for insider trading, holding securities
firms liable in some cases for their employees' violations and
offering a bounty to whistleblowers.
   ``This bill ... represents a powerful congressional assault on
insider trading, a pernicious practice which has undermined the
public trust in the fundamental fairness and integrity of our
securities markets,'' said Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., the
sponsor of the bill and chairman of the finance subcommittee of the
House Energy and Commerce Committee.
   Securities firms had been fighting the measure but dropped their
objections after Markey agreed in talks late Tuesday to soften some
of the bill's provisions.
   The Securities Industry Association, at a hearing last month,
objected to making companies liable when their employees use
non-public information to profit by trading securities.
   The bill as passed requires companies to have systems designed
to detect insider trading, but it limits their liability to
violations in which they either knew or ``recklessly disregarded''
the facts.
   Brokerage firms were also worried about the bounty provisions,
arguing that they would give in-house compliance officers an
incentive to withhold knowledge of wrongdoing from the firm in
hopes of collecting a bounty later.
   However, according to a Securities Industry Association official
who spoke on condition of anonymity, Markey has agreed to limit the
situations in which a brokerage firm employee could collect the
bounty, which would be capped at 10 percent of any penalty levied.
   Rep. Matthew J. Rinaldo of New Jersey, the ranking Republican on
the committee, said the compromise ``provides a substantial
deterrent on insider trading ... without placing an undue burden on
the securities industry.''
   In other provisions, the legislation would:
   _Increase the maximum criminal insider trading fine from the
current $100,000 for individuals and $500,000 for corporations and
partnerships to $1 million for individuals and $2.5 million for
firms.
   _Boost the maximum jail term from five years to 10 years.
   _Create a legal basis for private investors to sue to recover
money lost because of inside trading.
   _Give the Securities and Exchange Commission power to issue
subpoenas and take sworn statements on behalf of foreign agencies
pursuing securities violations. The SEC intends to ask foreign
countries to return the service.
   The bill, adopted by the finance subcommittee on a voice vote,
avoids a controversial question that has held up insider trading
legislation for more than a year: how broadly or narrowly to define
insider trading.
   The offense is currently defined by court and regulatory
interpretation. Securities firms had been seeking a better guide
for determining if a particular activity were illegal. Others
argued that a definition would simply provide ``a roadmap for
evasion.''
   The Senate Banking Committee last week passed a much narrower
insider trading bill, including only the provisions on
international cooperation.
   Markey said he hoped the full Energy and Commerce Committee
could act as soon as next week. If the bill passes the full House,
he said he would seek to include its provisions when the House and
Senate versions are reconciled.
   An aide to Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., chairman of the Senate
Banking Committee, said the senator is inclined to favor Markey's
broader legislation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880804-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 1825EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-US-EuropeTrade     08-04 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Europe Trade,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Treasury Warns Europeans Against Protectionism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top U.S. Treasury official warned Western
Europeans Thursday that increased protection of European business
against U.S. competition would bring counteraction from the U.S.
government.
   ``The intensification of protectionism in Europe would certainly
evoke a response from the U.S. government,'' M. Peter McPherson,
deputy secretary of the Treasury, told the Institute for
International Economics.
   McPherson will take the place temporarily of Secretary James A.
Baker III if Baker _ as expected _ resigns to run the presidential
campaign of Vice President George Bush.
   McPherson has appeared little in public since he took his job a
year ago. He was previously administrator of the U.S. Agency for
International Development. His speech Thursday was the first major
U.S. government statement on plans for the 12 countries of the
European Economic Community to put an end to all trade barriers
among them by 1992.
   The countries are: West Germany, France, Britain, Italy, the
Netherlands, Belgium, Denmark, Spain, Portugal, Greece, Ireland and
Luxembourg.
   ``Some (Europeans) feel that the pressure of greater competition
within Europe should be mitigated by limiting competition from the
rest of the world,'' McPherson said.
   ``This is the sentiment behind suggestions, such as that made by
one prominent industrialist, that a `protective curtain' be erected
around the the internal market.''
   He did not name the industrialist.
   McPherson's speech was made the day after Congress sent
President Reagan the first big overhaul of U.S. trade policies in
14 years. Reagan is expected to approve it.
   Europeans have criticized the new U.S. trade rules as
protectionist. Among the critics is Sir Roy Denman, the EEC
ambassador in Washington. He attended Thursday's meeting of the
Institute for International Economics, a private group that studies
world issues.
   ``There's a tendency in this country to think of a dear old
kindly Uncle Sam being led by guileful Europeans into a deep pit,''
he told the audience of economists.
   He denied that the Europeans want to freeze the United States
out of their markets.
   McPherson said the Reagan administration favors equal treatment
among all trading partners, rather than deals between pairs of
countries, which is known as reciprocity.
   ``This standard of reciprocity could be applied in a manner that
would discriminate against firms in the United States seeking
entrance into the EEC and against U.S.-owned firms already
operating in Europe,'' McPherson said.
   He suggested that instead of ``reciprocity'' the Europeans adopt
the principle of ``national treatment'' _ giving U.S. firms the
same legal rights that they give firms from one another's countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
