<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AutoRecall     08-04 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Recall,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Recalls 15,000 Ambulances</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. said Thursday it is recalling
15,000 ambulances to replace faulty engine heater hoses that could
leak or burst and cause a fire under the hood.
   The ambulances to be recalled are mounted on 1983-87 Econoline
E-250 and E-350 chassis and vans, Ford said in a statement.
   ``Because of the high operating temperatures sometimes
encountered in ambulance service, failure of the heater hose could
result in an underhood fire,'' said John P. King, a manager in
Ford's parts and service division.
   ``The likelihood of a fire is increased if the engine coolant
mixture is not properly mixed with water,'' he said.
   Ford will notify the owners of the defective vehicles and make
all needed repairs free of charge, King said.
   Ford also said it will replace radiator caps and mufflers on
ambulances made from mid-1985 through 1987.
   Ford spokesman Chuck Snearly said 21 fires have been linked to
the faulty heater hoses and six fires to the muffler problem. Ford
is not aware of any injuries that have been caused by defects in
the ambulances, Snearly said.
   The Washington-based Center for Auto Safety has said the
ambulances are fire hazards.
   Last year, in response to reports of fuel-system problems that
caused fires, Ford recalled 193,000 1983-87 E-250 and E-350 model
Econoline vans and 16,000 1983-87 ambulances built on the E-350
Econoline chassis.
</TEXT>
