<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld - Writethru,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher In Quiet Trading; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 9th graf pvs Other late... to UPDATE with West German
mark quotes. Picks up 10th graf, Other late...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against major foreign currencies
Thursday in quiet trading in advance of Friday's scheduled release
of the U.S. unemployment rate for July.
   Gold prices were mixed. Republic National Bank of New York said
gold was bid at $432.95 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down from
$433.25 an ounce late Wednesday.
   The civilian jobless rate fell to 5.3 percent in June, and many
traders expected it to remain at about that level.
   A decline in the U.S. jobless rate could lift the dollar by
providing evidence of strong growth in the U.S. economy, they said.
But they said central banks would probably sell dollars in that
case to slow the currency's rise.
   In the meantime, Thursday's dealings remained dominated by
technical factors and guesses about the intentions of West
Germany's central bank, which continued to sell dollars.
   ``We're becoming like the stock market. This is summer doldrums,
plus,'' said Garrett Glass, a vice president for foreign exchange
at First National Bank of Chicago. ``We're all just sitting waiting
for inspiration tomorrow during the release of the unemployment
numbers.''
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound, which was
quoted at $1.7105, compared with $1.7090 late Wednesday. Later in
New York, the dollar rose against the pound. It cost $1.7088 to buy
a pound, cheaper than $1.7123 late Wednesday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.10 yen to a closing 132.75 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted higher at 132.97 yen. At the end of the
trading day in New York, the dollar rose to 132.98 yen from 132.79.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.87925 West German marks, up from
1.87465; 1.5675 Swiss francs, up from 1.5622; 1.2054 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.2036; 6.3390 French francs, up from 6.3215; and
1,386.50 Italian lire, up from 1,382.75.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.8795 West German marks, up from
1.8755; 1.5635 Swiss francs, unchanged; 6.3365 French francs, up
from 6.3235; 2.1230 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1150; 1,387.25
Italian lire, up from 1,382.00; and 1.2055 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.2020.
   Gold prices fluctuated in a narrow range.
   At the beginning of the trading day in Hong Kong, gold rose
$1.67 a troy ounce to close at a bid $435.34 an ounce.
   Gold was quoted in London at a late bid price of $433 a troy
ounce, up from late Wednesday's $432.25. In Zurich, the bid price
was $433.50 an ounce, down from $434 late Wednesday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery rose to $433.40 an ounce from $433.30 Wednesday.
   Silver was quoted late Thursday in London at a bid price of
$6.86 a troy ounce, down from Wednesday's $6.88. On New York's
Comex, silver bullion for current delivery rose to $6.855 an ounce
from $6.835 Wednesday.
</TEXT>
