<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ArgentinaLoan     08-04 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina Loan,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Treasury Arranging `Bridge' Loan For Argentina</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury Department said Thursday it is
working with debt-troubled Argentina to arrange a short-term loan
of up to $500 million from the United States and other creditor
nations.
   The so-called ``bridge'' loan would allow Argentina to meet
interest payments on its foreign debt, much of it owed to private
U.S. banks, while it negotiates with the International Monetary
Fund and the World Bank.
   But, according to a department statement, funds from the
short-term loan, won't become available until Argentina meets
certain requirements under the World Bank's lending program.
   Argentina, which is more than 90 days past due on more than $300
million in payments, has said it cannot afford to make its overdue
interest payments.
   Recently, it has taken measures to cut its budget deficit and
check inflation, running about 20 percent a month. This week, it
declared a three-day bank holiday and devalued its currency.
   ``United States willingness to participate in this effort
reflects support for Argentina's economic reform efforts and the
determination of the government of Argentina to address its
international financial relations in a constructive manner,'' the
Treasury statement said.
   It said the United States is working with other creditor
governments through the Bank for International Settlements, a
clearinghouse in Switzerland for central banks, to formulate the
bridge loan.
   ``These efforts will be fully supported as well by the World
Bank and we expect that they will be supported as well by the
international financial community,'' it said.
   The IMF, in its own statement, said it was ready to start
negotiations with Argentina for a $1.2 billion loan.
   The United States last month offered a similar bridge loan to
Brazil, which is seeking to restore its standing in the
international financial community after declaring a moratorium on
its debt payments last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
