<DOCNO> AP880804-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 2126EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Venezuela-Debt     08-04 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Venezuela-Debt,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Venezuela Demands Banks Restore Financial Flow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAROLD OLMOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Venezuelan President Jaime Lusinchi
said Thursday he was sending a mission to the United States to
press for new loans to aid the Venezuelan economy, which is
laboring under the burden of its $34 billion foreign debt and the
drop in world oil prices.
   Lusinchi said the mission headed by Finance Minister Hector
Hurtado was aimed at negotiating the restoration of capital flow
into Venezuela, including new loans.
   The continuing weakness in the market for oil, the nation's
chief export, severely has limited Venezuela's ability to fight an
economic crisis that keeps over 40 percent of the labor force
deprived of full employment.
   ``We understand that the Gordian knot (tying up the Venezuelan
economy) is the foreign debt problem and we have decided to cut
it,'' Lusinchi said in a nationwide television address.
   The mission was expected to meet representatives of creditor
banks early next week in Washington and New York and request up to
$3 billion in loans, an amount intended to offset the balance of
payments deficit calculated for this year.
   Lusinchi spoke in the wake of a record fall by the Venezuelan
currency, the bolivar, triggered by officially denied reports that
the nation was ready to declare a unilateral moratorium on payments
on $20.3 billion of its foreign debt.
   The news was denied emphatically by Hurtado, who labeled as
``irresponsible'' the debt moratorium story printed Thursday by El
Universal, one of the country's most influential newspapers.
   ``This is a totally groundless information,'' Hurtado told a
news conference. ``I want to reiterate that Venezuela, as a serious
nation, will continue abiding by its international commitments as
much as with its plans to look for new loans.''
   Lusinchi said, ``As to this matter (debt) we have not rushed and
will not rush to measures which are not well supported.'' But he
warned that as the oil market goes, so will the country's ability
to repay its creditors.
   Venezuela is Latin America's fourth-largest debtor, after
Brazil, Mexico and Argentina.
   Venezuela's financial difficulties have worsened in the past few
months. International monetary reserves at the Central Bank have
been steadily declining from over $9.3 billion in December to $8.5
billion as of June. Of this total, only $2.5 billion are liquid
reserves.
   Lusinchi said Venezuela had agreed on a refinancing scheme with
creditor banks only on condition that the banks grant new loans to
Venezuela. It is widely acknowledged that efforts in that direction
have been almost fruitless.
   Servicing its foreign debt will cost Venezuela over $5 billion
this year. The amount includes more than $4 billion in interest
payments, or nearly 50 percent of the nation's projected total
export revenue for 1988.
   In February 1987, the government signed with creditor banks a
second accord extending up to 15 years, through 1999, the repayment
of the nation's $20.3 billion public sector debt at a lower rate of
interest from the previous accord signed in 1986.
   Lusinchi is expected to confer on the debt issue next week in
Quito with some of his Latin American colleagues scheduled to
attend the inauguration of Equador's new president, Rodrigo Borja.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880804-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 2132EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-DroughtRelief 1stLd-Writethru f0310 08-04 0907</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Relief, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0310,0928</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farm Lawmakers Produce $3.9 Billion Compromise Drought Package</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 4th graf bgng ``President Reagan ... '' to CORRECT
figure to $3.9 billion, sted million.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farm lawmakers approved a $3.9 billion aid
package for drought-stricken farmers Thursday night, including a
three-month dairy price-support increase but limiting feed
assistance to livestock producers.
   ``We have moved in record time and we have developed a good,
fair bill,'' Senate Agriculture Committee Chairman Patrick J.
Leahy, D-Vt., said after the House-Senate conference committee
approved the compromise package.
   Plans call for bringing the bill to the floor in both the House
and Senate by next Wednesday at the latest, and most lawmakers
believe that the election-year package will find overwhelming
support in both chambers.
   President Reagan is expected to sign the measure, whose $3.9
billion cost estimate is well below the $6 billion level at which
the measure could have nasty budgetary repercussions.
   Major provisions would provide farmers with 65 percent of crop
losses beyond 35 percent of the expected harvest. That feature
already was cemented when the conference committee went into
session.
   Farmers very severely hurt by the drought would get even more.
The bill would furnish producers with 90 percent of losses over 75
percent of their expected harvest. That represented a compromise
between the 95 percent level in the House version and the 85
percent level passed by the Senate.
   House and Senate negotiators were unable to agree on much in
sessions Thursday morning and early afternoon. Leahy and House
Agriculture Committee Chairman E. ``Kika'' de la Garza, D-Texas,
finally went behind closed doors, joined by senior Republicans.
They produced a compromise that was swiftly adopted when the
conference committee met Thursday night.
   They dropped a Senate-passed provision that would provide
government feed assistance to farmers who would not ordinarily be
producing their own feed even if not for the drought. Agriculture
Secretary Richard Lyng said Wednesday he would have trouble
recommending the feature to President Reagan because the price tag
was $2 billion.
   The compromise version retained a House-passed provision that
would provide assistance to livestock producers who also produce
their own feed. The price tag would be $800 million by
administration estimate.
   The decision to narrow the feed benefits went a long way toward
dropping the price tag to $3.9 billion, well below earlier
estimates of what the final price tag would be.
   Livestock feed has become a key to the drought issue. Heat and a
lack of rain have scorched a substantial quantity of hay and feed
grains in the midcontinent, causing feed prices to shoot up.
   The compromise retained the one major dispute that the conferees
had resolved in their otherwise futile sessions earlier _ a House
provision that would raise the dairy price-support level in April
through June next year by 50 cents to $11.10 for each 100 pounds of
milk.
   In accepting the House plan to raise the support level, Leahy
voted ``aye'' while all of the other Senate conferees remained
silent. The Senate chairman's home state is a major source of the
East Coast's milk supply.
   ``The Senate recedes to the House by one weak aye,'' announced
de la Garza as laughter passed over the scores of agribusiness
lobbyists and congressional staffers in the room.
   But the compromise made substantial modifications in a
Senate-approved provision that would constitute a major benefit for
American manufacturers of ethanol _ ethyl alcohol made from farm
products and mixed with gasoline to form the fuel gasohol.
   As passed by the Senate, the measure would have allowed ethanol
makers to buy 2 million bushels each of surplus corn, or other
crops, each month at 110 percent of the goverment-owned Commodity
Credit Corporation's acquisition price _ well below current,
drought-inflated prices. The total available would have been
limited to 16 million bushels a month.
   Proponents said the plan was designed to boost a number of small
ethanol manufacturers but it could also have turned into a sizeable
subsidy for the Archer Daniels Midland Co. of Decatur, Ill., a
major corporation with a politically active management.
   The final product of the conference committee, however, would
make the program optional and leave the final say-so up to the
secretary of agriculture. ``I don't think it will be put into
effect,'' said Rep. Edward R. Madigan, R-Ill., the ranking House
Agriculture Committee Republican.
   The bill also would exclude participation by ethanol producers
that use more than 30 million bushels of corn a year.
   House provisions that would make disaster payments available to
farmers hit by disasters other than the drought, including some
that happened in 1987, also were adopted by the conference
committee. The payments would be for ``drought, hail, excessive
moisture or related condition.''
   The related condition ``includes hurricanes, because they come
with moisture,'' de la Garza said. That resolved a concern of Rep.
Jerry Huckaby, D-La., who raised the issue several times. Hail
payments were designed to compensate cotton growers in the district
of Rep. Larry Combest, R-Texas, for damage in a storm that struck
last year.
   Administration officials had been opposed to the provision.
   The two houses compromised on a House requirement that farmers
would have to buy federal crop insurance in 1989 and 1990 to
receive disaster payments. Under the legislation, they would have
to buy one year of the insurance if their disaster loss exceeded 65
percent of normal yield.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
