<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Sun-Times-Page 1stLd-Writethru f0307 08-04 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sun-Times-Page, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0307,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chicago Sun-Times Publisher Resigns</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS x new grafs to UPDATE with further background.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Page, president and publisher of the
Chicago Sun-Times, has resigned, two years after spearheading a
buyout of the newspaper from Australian publisher Rupert Murdoch,
the paper announced Thursday.
   Page's resignation was announced by Sun-Times Chairman Leonard
P. Shaykin in a two-page press release that also said the company
had repurchased Page's shares in the corporation.
   Shaykin is managing partner of Adler & Shaykin, a New York
investment firm that was one of the principle investors in the
group Page lined up to buy the Sun-Times for $145 million in June
1986.
   ``Bob Page has contributed much to the Sun-Times,'' Shaykin said
in the statement. ``He has now decided to pursue other interests.
All of us at the Sun-Times wish him well in whatever he chooses to
do.''
   The paper also released a two-page statement by Page.
   ``I leave the Sun-Times with regret but with a strong management
team and staff that as a newspaper is well positioned to continue
its vital role as a unique and important Chicago institution,''
Page said in the statement.
   Page had been president and publisher of the Sun-Times since
1984, when Murdoch's News America Publishing Corp. bought the paper
from its long-time owners, the Field family of Chicago.
   The press release made no mention of a possible successor and
the Sun-Times planned no further comment, said spokeswoman Marie
Mariorca.
   The Sun-Times is second in circulation in the metropolitan
Chicago area to the Chicago Tribune, with 625,000 daily.
   Rumor of Page's departure was reported Sunday in the Chicago
Tribune. The newspaper, citing unnamed sources, said Page had been
at odds with Shaykin over the financial performance of the
Sun-Times. But spokesmen for Sun-Times refused to comment on that
report Thursday.
   When the paper was purchased from Murdoch, Page promised a
``more serious, more purposeful'' look. At the time, it was the
nation's 11th largest daily.
   During Page's tenure, the newspaper hired several top
journalists from the competing Chicago Tribune, including current
managing editor Raymond Coffey. One of the biggest defectors was
columnist Ann Landers, who jumped to the Tribune.
   Page was in the newsroom Thursday when word of his resignation
broke, but slipped out of the building without talking to reporters
waiting outside.
   Sun-Times columnist Irv Kupcinet called Page a ``good friend.''
   ``I think he lifted us up out of the morass of the Rupert
Murdoch era,'' Kupcinet said. ``I think we have a very solid
future.''
   But one reporter, who asked that his name not be used, said:
``Let's just say (Page) won't find too many broken hearts here.''
   Page came to Chicago after overseeing the revitalization of
Murdoch's Boston Herald.
</TEXT>
