<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-88 2206EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Economy     08-04 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Economy,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Economic White Paper Confirms Trend Away From Exports, Toward
Spending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI TAKETA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Japanese are abandoning their successful
sell-overseas, save-at-home formula and pumping more yen into their
own markets, boosting imports and their taste for upscale consumer
goods, according to a government study released Friday.
   The Economic Planning Agency, broadly summarizing trends in the
1987 fiscal year that ended in March, said booming consumption
among the once-frugal Japanese had pulled the economy through a
brief crisis triggered when the soaring yen battered Japanese
exports.
   The agency's white paper also said the long-term picture
indicates the trend should continue.
   ``When we look at the Japanese economy now, it is very close to
an ideal state of affairs,'' said Shunji Fukinbara, head of the
agency's Research Bureau. ``Japanese corporations have shifted the
emphasis from export-led development to domestic sales.
   ``In line with their catch-up efforts with the Asian newly
industrialized economies, Japanese corporations shed some business
activities that don't pay and encouraged new businesses and
products,'' he said.
   The corporate self-scrutiny, together with cheaper prices of oil
and imports and lower lending rates, helped stabilize the economy
and ease a jobless rate that peaked at a postwar high of 3.2
percent early in 1987, the report said.
   Japan's currency nearly has doubled in value against the U.S.
dollar since late 1985, when world monetary leaders agreed to
devalue the dollar to help the competitiveness of American exports
and trim Washington's massive trade deficit.
   Japanese economic growth, which registered a sluggish 2.5
percent in fiscal 1986, was 4.9 percent last year.
   Growth in imports outpaced exports, with goods from the European
Community and Asia's economic dynamos _ South Korea, Taiwan, Hong
Kong and ingapore _ outpacing shipments from the United States.
   While import volume was up 12 percent in 1987, exports rose by
only 1.1 percent, Fukinbara said. Manufactured imports scored a
substantial 45.6 percent gain, partly because Japanese exporters
were moving factories to cheaper sites overseas and shipping the
goods home.
   Japanese tastes were tending toward the affluent. Fukinbara
noted a rise in purchases of luxury goods from Europe and durable
consumer goods: videotape recorders, automobiles and television
sets, often with value-added features such as extra-wide screens.
   But soaring values of stocks and land, particularly in Tokyo,
are widening an assets gap among the predominantly middle-class
Japanese. The white paper noted that the average office worker no
longer can hope to buy a house and land in the capital even with
his lifetime savings.
   ``There may be a growing disparity between the haves and
have-nots in Japan,'' Fukinbara said.
   The report suggested that Japan do more to open its markets to
foreign goods, give public and private aid to developing countries
and use its growing influence to stabilize the global monetary
system and promote free trade.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
